<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Hirohito 1stLd-Writethru a0623 09-21 0817</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0623,0837</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emperor's Condition Stabilizes; Crown Prince Assumes Duties</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Akihito put in charge of
imperial affairs; Hirohito stable, stock market calm. Pickup 6th
graf pvs `News reports...'; DELETES 19th graf `Widespread
concern...' to conform</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cabinet on Thursday put Crown Prince Akihito
temporarily in charge of all imperial affairs, and Emperor Hirohito
remained in serious but stable condition four days after falling
ill, officials said.
   Hirohito's chief doctor said the 87-year-old monarch's condition
``clearly stabilized'' Wednesday after an intestinal hemorrhage
made the emperor vomit blood. But the doctor said he wasn't sure
the bleeding had stopped.
   The world's longest-reigning monarch was given oxygen and
intravenous feeding, officials and news reports said. But palace
officials, widely quoted in press reports, said the emperor on
Wednesday requested food and a television in order to watch his
favorite sport, sumo wrestling.
   Chief Cabinet Secretary Keizo Obuchi, the government's main
spokesman, said the Cabinet on Thursday morning agreed to appoint
Crown Prince Akihito, 54, in charge of all imperial duties.
   ``Taking into consideration the emperor's illness and (the time
required for) medical treatment, we have asked the crown prince to
temporarily assume (imperial) responsibilities,'' Obuchi said in a
nationally televised news conference.
   One year ago, when Hirohito underwent an intestinal bypass
operation, the prince took charge of all duties for three months.
Last December, Hirohito resumed seven of the 12 designated imperial
functions, which include placing an official seal on government
appointments and new laws, and convocation of Parliament.
   Tokyo's stock market plunged and then recovered on news of
Hirohito's condition Wednesday but remained calm in morning trading
Thursday following upbeat reports in local newspapers.
   News reports said government officials also began the process of
selecting a name for the next emperor's reign. Japanese normally
use the name and year of the emperor's reign in giving dates,
rather than the system generally used in the rest of the world.
   The emperor's chief physician, Akira Takagi, said the emperor
showed signs of jaundice and anemia, but his condition had
stabilized since he began vomiting blood late Monday night.
   On Tuesday, the emperor, in bed in the Imperial Palace, received
a total of 2.55 pints of blood in three transfusions.
   But Takagi said he ``couldn't say with confidence'' that
Hirohito's internal bleeding stopped. He said the emperor's
pancreas was even more inflamed than last September, when pressure
from the organ on the upper intestine forced doctors to perform the
intestinal bypass.
   At the Imperial Palace in central Tokyo, government officials
and diplomats continued to pay their respects while hundreds of
people gathered outside of the gates to bow and pray.
   The crowd included people of all ages, some having arrived by
chartered bus from more than 500 miles away.
   ``When I read newspapers reporting (the emperor) was in critical
condition, I felt like my grandfather was dying,'' said Aya Kitade,
a 22-year-old college student from Kyoto, 230 miles away.
   Each of the palace's seven gates was surrounded by people, some
weeping, some kneeling.
   ``I could not bear staying home and watching the emperor suffer
on television,'' said Eiyoshi Kiguchi, a 71-year-old Tokyo resident
who served in the navy in World War II.
   Kiguchi sat on the curb in front of the main palace gate and
rubbed tears from his eyes.
   ``I adore the emperor and always prayed for his well-being,'' he
said. ``He has been through a lot, and his life was full of
hardships. No emperor had such a wild life as him.''
   A middle-aged man said this may be the last chance for the
Japanese to express honest feelings about the emperor.
   ``If you make sympathetic remarks about the emperor or the
imperial family itself when the emperor is well, people will see
you as an imperialist or even a right-winger,'' he said. ``But now
that the emperor is visibly suffering, no one can attack you if you
express sympathy toward him.''
   Across Japan, Shinto shrines held services to pray for the
ailing monarch. Before he was forced to renounce his divinity by
U.S. occupation officials after World War II, the emperor was
considered a living god and a direct descendent of the sun goddess,
Amaterasu.
   Many older people still hold Hirohito in high regard, but
younger Japanese typically have given little thought to the
emperor. A minority strongly oppose the imperial system, calling it
a vestige of the militarism that dominated wartime Japan.
   Officials said Foreign Minister Sosuke Uno canceled a planned
trip Thursday to Washington for talks with Secretary of State
George Shultz. Although the Foreign Ministry did not give a reason
for the cancellation, it was known that the emperor's illness
threatened the visit.
   The government also asked Italian Prime Minister Ciriaco De Mita
to postpone a scheduled visit beginning Sunday, Kyodo News Service
reported.
</TEXT>
