<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FilmingFuror     09-21 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Filming Furor,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TV Commercial Filming Causes Furor In Posh Suburban Neighborhood</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spat is turning nasty on a tree-lined
street in this affluent Chicago suburb, where television commercial
crews at Ken Kessler's house are keeping neighbors awake with
late-night shoots.
   Kessler's next-door neighbors on Forest Avenue complain the
crews are too noisy, block their driveways with trucks and vans,
and have shooting sessions as late as 11 p.m.
   Kessler said Tuesday he believes his neighbors are just miffed
because their homes aren't being used as sets for TV commercials.
   ``To me it's pure and simple _ a problem of money and
jealousy,'' says the 45-year-old institutional stockbroker, who
rents his home to film crews for between $300 and $1,000 a day.
   ``Somehow I think it grates them that someone next door is
making money off their house. Really, I think that's the bottom
line,'' Kessler said.
   ``That's ludicrous,'' retorted Robert Fisher, who lives next
door and wants the city to restrict the Kesslers to just one
commercial a year at their home.
   ``After the second time I complained, the next day I got a call
from an agent saying, `Hey, do you want to use your house for a
commercial?'
   ``I said, `Absolutely not!' I have a beautiful home. I don't
want people tramping all through it. ...I bought my house to live
in _ not to use it as a filming location,'' said Fisher, 40, a
group controller for Zenith Electronics.
   The dispute in this suburb north of Chicago along Lake Michigan
has been brewing since Kessler and his wife, Ann, began renting
their three-story, 12-room home to film crews about three years ago.
   Their home has appeared since in commercials for McDonald's,
Illinois Bell, Kraft and Allstate and in an hourlong made-for-TV
film called, ``Thinking Big.''
   Fisher and Bob Bonges, who lives on the other side of the
Kesslers, have lobbied the Evanston City Council to enact an
ordinance restricting commercial filming.
   Fisher contends Kessler is violating zoning laws by operating a
commercial enterprise in his home.
   Kessler disagrees, saying he doesn't employ anyone.
   A council committee decided last week the dispute was too
limited to warrant a citywide law. But City Manager Joel Asprooth
took administrative steps to restrict film shootings to three per
year at the Kesslers.
   In the meantime, Kessler said he has asked the Neighborhood
Justice Center, an agency that mediates such spats, to try to
resolve the fight.
   ``We feel we're just defending our right to do in our house what
we want to,'' he said.
   Fisher said Kessler rejected his appeal to work out a neighborly
compromise and now he's not optimistic for an amicable resolution.
   ``We really don't speak to them. We don't like what they're
doing and they won't cut it out,'' he said.
</TEXT>
