<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Shultz-Shevardnadze     09-21 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz-Shevardnadze,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Human Rights At Top of Agenda as Shultz and Shevardnadze Meet This
Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Human rights will get high priority when
Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze meets Thursday and
Friday with Secretary of State George Shultz, a State Department
official told a congressional panel Tuesday.
   But little hope remains for finalizing the planned superpower
treaty cutting stocks of long-range nuclear ballistic missiles by
50 percent, Assistant Secretary of State Rozanne Ridgway told the
House Foreign Affairs subcommittee on European and Middle Eastern
affairs.
   Shevardnadze is to arrive Wednesday for his 28th meeting with
Shultz.
   ``We will press the Soviets to clear the books of the remaining
human rights cases,'' Ms. Ridgway said. Among the U.S. concerns to
be addressed, she said, are exit permission for members of divided
families, separated spouses, dual nationals and persons punished
for religious activity, including people jailed for trying to
monitor human rights under the Helsinki process.
   ``We will push on emigration'' and positive progress would
improve the prospects for concluding the review meeting at Vienna,
she said. ``We will also underscore the importance of the Soviets
pressing on with legal and other changes affecting the human rights
environment in the Soviet Union.''
   Ms. Ridgway said Shultz hopes ``to tie down'' with the Soviet
foreign minister some of the complicated, unresolved issues in the
ongoing U.S.-Soviet negotiations on the START, or strategic
long-range arms treaty.
   It is also hoped that Shultz and Shevardnadze will ``give a
push'' to agreement on verification procedures for the unratified
peaceful nuclear explosion and threshhold test ban treaties of the
1970s, she said.
   If that happens, the Reagan administration would submit the
pacts to the Senate ``for ratification early in the next
Congress,'' she said.
   Ms. Ridgway said the get together is the 28th for Shultz and
Shevardnadze.
   ``It may be their last (meeting) in Washington, but is not
expected to be their last meeting,'' she said, mentioning the U.N.
General Assembly both will attend next week in New York.
   Other occasions could follow, she said, noting that prospects
for East-West agreement at the current Vienna review of the 1975
Helsinki conference ``may fall into place'' later this year.
</TEXT>
