<1ST_LINE>u a AM-NitroEvacuation     09-21 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nitro Evacuation,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Wants Thousands to Leave Homes Sunday During Chemical Cleanup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN L. HERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency on Sunday plans to blow up a mystery container it believes
contains cyanide if it can evacuate enough houses around a plant in
Nitro, officials said late Tuesday.
   ``They plan to explode and burn a 30-pound container of what may
be filled with hydrogen cyanide. They don't know if it's full,
empty, partly full or unstable. If there's a problem it would
spread up to 3,000 feet,'' said Nitro Mayor Don Karnes.
   Karnes said he was skeptical that there was much danger, but
said he would recommend residents heed the government agency's call
for a voluntary evacuation around the closed Artel Chemical Co.
   Nitro, with about 8,000 residents, is about 12 miles west of
Charleston.
   ``I'd rather err on the side of safety,'' he said.
   Hydrogen cyanide is poisonous and can be fatal if inhaled or
absorbed directly, but it can be burned and its vapors contained.
   Federal officials took over the chemical plant after a roof
collapsed on already leaking drums whose contents were not all
identified.
   The EPA in July said the Artel site was a ``potential
emergency'' and a spokesman initially said that dangerous
substances such as methyl mercaptan, a chemical mixed in with
natural gas to give it an odor, stored at the plant could explode
at any time. Officials later played down any danger.
   A third EPA emergency town meeting is scheduled for Thursday
evening at Nitro Junior High School, 500 yards from the Artel plant.
   ``That tells me it's probably not all that dangerous. If it
were, they would have their meeting in Beckley or Parkersburg,''
Karnes said.
   Meanwhile, area schools are to conduct a practice evacuation
Wednesday morning.
   Three schools in Kanawha County and one in Putnam County are to
participate in the drill, officials said.
   County school officials said 28 buses would be sent to the
schools to determine how long it would take to get students out of
the area in the event there would be an explosion at the Artel site.
</TEXT>
