<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-88 0211EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Congress-Transportation     09-21 0730</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congress-Transportation,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Passes Railroad Drug Testing Bill, But Senate Prospects
Gloomy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An election-year bill requiring random drug
and alcohol testing for railroad workers seems to be headed for a
roadblock in the Senate, even though it has breezed through the
House.
   The chairman of the Senate committee that oversees the
transportation industry made that clear Tuesday, shortly after the
House approved the testing legislation on an unopposed voice vote.
   A spokesman for Senate Commerce Committee chairman Sen. Ernest
Hollings, D-S.C., said Hollings prefers a Senate version of the
bill that would also extend a wide-ranging testing program to
airline and trucking industry workers.
   Spokesman Emilio Pardo said Hollings would block the legislation
unless he was able to expand it ``to get all three modes
protected'' _ railroads, trucking and airlines.
   Time is also working against the drug-testing bill. The
congressional leadership is hoping lawmakers can adjourn for the
year by mid-October.
   Congress began working on drug testing legislation shortly after
the Jan. 4, 1987, collision between a loaded Amtrak passenger train
and three-linked Conrail engines in Chase, Md. After the disaster _
in which 16 people were killed and 175 injured _ two Conrail
crewmen admitted they had been smoking marijuana shortly before
their train ran through stop signals and into the path of the
Amtrak train.
   The legislation was held up for months because rail unions and
their supporters in Congress argued that the tests could be
inaccurate, might be used to harass workers and would be an
invasion of privacy.
   Labor leaders finally dropped their opposition this summer,
saying they were satisfied with provisions designed to protect
workers from erroneous laboratory results.
   ``This bill will make sure we don't have another Chase crash,''
the bill's sponsor, Rep. Thomas A. Luken, D-Ohio, said after the
vote.
   Another sponsor, Rep. Bob Whittaker, R-Kan., called the measure
a ``comprehensive, preventive and humane program.''
   Supporters say random testing would deter the consumption of
alcohol and illegal drugs by rail employees. The bill also would
require testing after accidents, for reasonable cause, before
hiring and as a part of annual physical examinations.
   Workers who test positive would be suspended without pay. They
would have their jobs restored to them if they successfully
complete a rehabilitation program.
   Shortly before the House approved the drug testing bill, the
Senate Commerce Committee rejected legislation that would have made
it easier for shippers who believe the rates they are charged by
railroads are too high to appeal to the government for help.
   On a 10-9 vote, the panel rejected a bipartisan bill that would
have revised the 1980 Staggers Rail Act, which deregulated the
railroad industry. The committee's action effectively killed the
legislation until Congress returns next year.
   Large segments of the coal, agriculture, utilities, chemical and
other industries _ which often have no alternative to rail shipping
_ have been complaining since 1980 that the Interstate Commerce
Commission has been doing little to protect shippers against
excessive prices charged by railroads.
   ``Captive shippers are being done wrong,'' said one of the
sponsors, Sen. John D. Rockefeller, D-W.Va., referring to
industries that must use railroads.
   Rockefeller's bill would have changed the complex formula the
ICC uses to decide whether rates are fair. In some cases, for
example, the burden of proof would be shifted to the railroads for
demonstrating that their rates are fair.
   Some opponents _ mainly Republicans _ argued that the ICC was
doing a good job of deciding rate cases, while others said the
legislation would be unlikely to be enacted this year because of
opposition in the House and by President Reagan.
   In other congressional action:
   _The Senate Commerce Committee approved a bill providing extra
federal aid to states that adopt several programs aimed at reducing
drunken driving. Among the initiatives the bill would encourage is
the immediate confiscation of a driver's license if he or she fails
a chemical test for intoxication, or refuses to take such a test.
   _The House voiced approval for legislation requiring the Federal
Aviation Administration to devote 15 percent of its research budget
to the study of airplane fire safety, aircraft maintenance, human
performance and the use of computer simulation models.
   _The House, also on a voice vote, directed the FAA to conduct
research on how new equipment has effected the performance of air
traffic controllers.
</TEXT>
