<DOCNO> AP880921-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-88 0212EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Pesticides     09-21 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pesticides,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pesticide Bill On Its Way To The Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plans to set an eight-year deadline for
finishing safety reviews of hundreds of pesticides sprayed on crops
are on their way to the Senate after gaining easy approval in the
House.
   ``Getting this bill to the president's desk is my top priority
as we wrap up this congressional session,'' E. ``Kika'' de la
Garza, D-Texas, chairman of the House Agriculture Committee, said
Tuesday as the House approved the measure on a voice vote.
   The Environmental Protection Agency would be required to
complete safety reviews of some 600 pesticides within eight years
under the bill. The research is designed to end use of the most
hazardous chemicals and limit use of others that present health
dangers.
   Not until the year 2024 would the agency finish the reviews at
the present pace, according to the General Accounting Office. Thus
far no deadline has been set for the research which began in the
mid-1970s.
   Business and government would share storage and disposal costs,
and a program under which the agency has paid $20 million to
manufacturers to buy up stocks of banned pesticides would be
largely ended under the three-year reauthorization of the Federal
Insecticide, Fungidice and Rodenticide Act.
   The Senate already has passed a similar bill and appeared likely
to act on the House version in the three to four weeks remaining
before lawmakers adjourn to campaign full time at home.
   Most envirionmentalists, however, are at most lukewarm to the
bill, a bare-bones measure without a number of provisions they
support, such as stepped up federal monitoring of groundwater,
which represents the basic drinking supply for millions of
Americans.
   Government research has shown some pesticides can lead to cancer
in laboratory animals and other severe health problems.
   Pesticides, an outgrowth of World War II chemical warfare
research, are now found in residue form in many fruits and
vegetables and even animal tissues that find their way onto the
American dinner table every day.
   Environmentalists have been campaigning with minimal success to
tighten pesticide regulation since 1962 when naturalist Rachel
Carson spotlighted the problem with her bestselling ``Silent
Spring.''
   Some environmentalists ripped into the House on Tuesday for
approving the three-year measure. They said it would take the issue
off the agenda without addressing some of the most serious problems.
   ``We're not willing to put pesticide regulation on the back
burner for three to four years,'' said Jay Feldman of the National
Coalition Against the Misuse of Pesticides. ``That's not any kind
of message to be sending out ... to people who are facing chemicals
in their drinking water, chemicals in their workplace and chemicals
in their food.''
   ``We think the bill is meaningless,'' said Dave Baker, political
director of the Friends of the Earth. He said the measure would
guarantee inaction until 1992.
   But Janet S. Hathaway, senior projects attorney of the Natural
Resources Defense Council, said the bill represents a plus for the
environmental cause because it guarantees that key issues such as
groundwater monitoring will have the spotlight to themselves next
year.
   De la Garza acknowledged that the measure did not go as far as
some would have liked.
   ``This is the art of the possible, this will not satisfy hardly
anyone but this is what we can do at this point,'' he said.
   Farmers have been highly suspicious of legislation they fear
would ban or raise the cost of pesticides, which are a fundamental
part of their business.
</TEXT>
