<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Iran-Contra     09-21 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Contra,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walsh Wants To Move CIA Agent's Iran-Contra Trial Out of
Washington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors are seeking dismissal of charges
against former CIA agent Joseph Fernandez that he lied about his
role in the Iran-Contra arms and money affair so they can move his
trial out of Washington.
   Independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh filed the motion Tuesday
in response to the refusal by Fernandez to stand trial in the
nation's capital for offenses that allegedly occurred in Virginia.
   Walsh said he planned to seek to indict Fernandez in Alexandria,
Va., on all the charges against Fernandez, including the allegation
that he conspired to deliver arms illegally to the Nicaraguan
Contra rebels and later lied about the clandestine supply network.
   The indictment says the alleged conspiracy took place in
Washington and elsewhere.
   But Fernandez, the CIA's former station chief in Costa Rica,
also is accused of four counts of lying about the operation to his
superiors and the presidential commission headed by former Sen.
John Tower, R-Texas, that investigated the Iran-Contra affair.
Those offenses allegedly occurred in Langley, Va., at CIA
headquarters.
   Prosecutors asked U.S. District Judge Aubrey E. Robinson Jr. to
dismiss all five counts, saying that ``the interest of judicial
economy and fundamental fairness dictate that the case should not
be splintered into unwieldy separate proceedings.''
   ``Rather, the case should be dismissed as a whole; at that
point, the government will re-present the case to a grand jury in
the Eastern District of Virginia, a forum to which the defendant
has no colorable objection,'' prosecutors said in their brief.
   The indictment returned June 20 accused Fernandez, 51, of
conspiring in 1985 and 1986 with former National Security Council
aide Oliver L. North and arms dealer Richard V. Secord to ship arms
to the Contras.
   Fernandez, who operated in Central America under the CIA
pseudonym Tomas Castillo, was accused of overseeing the
construction of an airstrip in Costa Rica from which planes flew to
drop supplies to the Nicaraguan rebels.
   To obtain a new indictment from a federal grand jury in
Alexandria, prosecutors would be able to summarize their case and
present transcripts of the original grand jury testimony of
witnesses against Fernandez.
</TEXT>
