<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Hastings     09-21 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hastings,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel To Decide In January On Hastings Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate panel says it will meet next January
to recommend whether a committee or the full Senate will hear
evidence in the impeachment trial of U.S. District Judge Alcee L.
Hastings of Miami.
   In a report approved 9-0 Tuesday, the Senate Rules Committee
said the chamber ``has clear authority'' to appoint an impeachment
committee for the second time in the nation's history, and to
continue proceedings that began this year into the next Congress.
   The report, which went to the Senate leadership, said the Rules
panel would conduct a hearing the week of Jan. 23 and issue a
report the following week on whether the committee approach was
proper for the Hastings case.
   Hastings wants the full Senate to hear testimony on allegations
that he conspired with a Washington, D.C., attorney to arrange a
bribe from two racketeers.
   ``If only 12 senators were receiving the testimony, by
definition, 88 would be unmindful of what transpired,'' Hastings
said after the report was issued. ``I don't want my trial decided
at the Press Club or the George Washington Hotel. I want them all
there seeing it and judging it for themselves.''
   Hastings said the decision to defer his trial, which he
estimated would last 21 days, until next year showed how little
appetite Congress has for impeachments.
   ``The bottom line is political. Everybody knows that the
business of the Senate is complex and sizable, and that impeachment
is not political fun,'' said Hastings.
   ``My case is a classic test case to let the American people know
that a constitutional amendment needs to be circulated to determine
if judicial accountability should be handled by something other
than Congress,'' he said.
   The House, in an action tantamount to an indictment, voted 413-3
to approve 17 articles of impeachment on Aug. 3. The case then went
to the Senate for trial, where conviction by a two-thirds majority
would remove Hastings from his lifetime job that now pays
$89,500-a-year.
   The main impeachment article accuses Hastings of conspiring with
Washington attorney William Borders in 1981 to obtain a $150,000
payment from two convicted racketeers in exchange for lenient
sentencing and return of forfeited assets.
   The Rules panel said, ``There are numerous impeachment cases in
which Congress carried over proceedings from one Congress to the
next, most involving cases in which the House continued its
inquiries from Congress to Congress,'' the Rules Committee said.
   ``In two cases ... Senate proceedings were continued from one
Congress to the next.''
   The full Senate sat as an impeachment jury and as judges for all
impeachment cases until the trial of former U.S. District Judge
Harry E. Claiborne in 1986.
   In Claiborne's case, a 12-member committee heard testimony for
seven days in September 1986 before the full Senate convened as a
jury in October and convicted the then-Las Vegas, Nev., judge.
   Hastings is the first U.S. government official to face
impeachment after winning acquittal in a criminal trial based on
the same charges. He also is the first black to go through the
impeachment process in which Congress determines whether an
official should be removed from office.
   Hastings' lawyer, Terence J. Anderson, has filed legal papers
that agree with the committee's recommendation to hold the
proceedings next year.
   The Rules Committee also recommended that House managers of the
case, who function as prosecutors, and Hastings be prepared to
proceed with witnesses by March 1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
