<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Iraq     09-21 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Iraq,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Praises Iraqi Pledge on Chemical Weapons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department is praising as a
``positive step'' an Iraqi pledge that appears to rule out future
use of chemical weapons either against foreign adversaries or the
country's rebellious Kurdish minority population.
   U.S. officials expressed hope Tuesday that the promise, made by
Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz, will head off the possibility of
congressional approval of economic sanctions against Iraq.
   Following what the State Department said was convincing evidence
that Iraq had used chemical weapons against its Kurdish population,
the Senate two weeks ago approved comprehensive sanctions against
Iraq, including a ban on agricultural and export credits.
   The State Department called the Senate action premature and
pressured Iraq to issue a firm statement declaring that it would no
longer engage in chemical warfare.
   Officials complained that the legislation could hurt American
exporters more than the Iraqis and said it was taken up without
prior consultation with the executive branch.
   Aziz's statement asserted that Iraq ``respects and abides by all
the provisions of international law'' concerning use of chemical
weapons, State Department spokesman Charles Redman said.
   The House Foreign Affairs Committee is expected to take up Iraqi
sanctions legislation on Thursday. It is not clear what impact
Aziz's statement will have on committee members.
   ``This is a positive step,'' Redman said. ``We take it to mean
that Iraq forswears the use of chemical weapons in internal as well
as international conflict. We will be watching closely to see that
this commitment is carried out.''
   On Sept. 8, Secretary of State George P. Shultz accused Iraq of
``unjustifiable and abhorrent'' behavior in using chemical weapons
against its Kurdish minority.
   Iraq has denied the U.S. charges, calling them ``absolutely
baseless'' but American officials contend that chemical warfare
contributed to the exodus of tens of thousands of Kurds from Iraq
to Turkey.
   Redman said the Iraqi statement referred to the 1925 Geneva
protocol barring chemical weapons use in international conflicts
and to other agreements that carry the weight of international law.
   He indicated that Iraqi use of chemical weapons against the
Kurds would not violate the Geneva agreement because of the
domestic nature of that conflict.
   He said use of chemical weapons during a civil conflict is
barred by a 1949 protocol that deals with war victims, and Aziz's
statement appeared to cover that agreement.
   Aziz said on Monday he would not agree to hold peace talks with
Iran in New York because ``I can't go to a town where there is a
campaign against the Arabs,'' an apparent reference to U.S.
hostility against his country.
   He agreed to one face-to-face meeting with Iran's foreign
minister in New York in early October but he ruled out additional
discussions there ``for political, security and practical reasons.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
