<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     09-21 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Takes Day Off from Campaigning to Prepare for Debate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush today is closeted with
his debate coaches, practicing how to ``be presidential'' when he
meets Democratic opponent Michael Dukakis for their first
face-to-face encounter on Sunday.
   The GOP presidential nominee will engage in a mock debate today,
with former deputy Treasury Secretary Richard G. Darman playing the
role of Dukakis, said a Bush campaign source.
   Senior staff to the vice president were asked to submit
questions on a variety of topics that might come up in the debate,
and several top advisers are involved in briefing Bush on the
answers, said Rich Bond, the campaign's national political director.
   Talking to reporters Tuesday aboard the campaign plane, Bond
described the debate preparation as ``diligent'' and said ``it will
be used for sharpening him up.''
   He declined to be specific about the rehearsals, but said: ``You
want to avoid costly mistakes and you want to come across as
presidential.
   ``What you've got to do at a debate at this level is be
presidential.''
   Bush has mentioned his own distaste for learning statistics but
said he needs to review that kind of material.
   But Bond commented: ``I don't think viewers will be
overimpressed with a mechanical recitation of facts and figures.
They'll be more impressed with whether the candidates have a grasp
of subjects.''
   The top aide made the comments as Bush took a quick trip into
New Jersey where he put on a patriotic show by touring a flag
manufacturing company and said, ``Flag sales are doing well and
America is doing well.''
   Bush, who has sought to turn the Pledge of Allegiance into an
election issue, addressed a rally outside the Annin Flag Co. of
Bloomfield flanked by enormous American flag banners.
   ``The flags you make fly over an America that today is stronger
and more prosperous than at any time in its proud history,'' Bush
told a group of several hundred people.
   He made some references to the economic record of his opponent
as governor of Massachusetts but without the same verve as he has
used to attack Dukakis' resume over the past several days.
   ``It's important to put all his (Dukakis) claims into
perspective before the debate,'' Bond said. ``Michael Dukakis is
not running away with the assertion that the `Massachusetts
miracle' is the best thing since sliced bread.''
   Dukakis officials have heatedly denied most of the allegations
raised by Bush about the state of the Massachusetts economy,
employement and taxation and have countered the Bush figures with
statistics of their own.
   Leading the Bush debate strategy sessions are media adviser
Roger Ailes, campaign chairman James A. Baker III, and pollster
Robert Teeter, Bond said.
   After the New Jersey speech, Bush got some debate pointers from
patrons at the Glenwood Diner when he stopped for a cup of coffee
and a slice of crumb cake.
   Several women in the diner told Bush he looked better in person
than on television. He asked them why they thought so.
   ``Because you're relaxed,'' suggested Lucie Galioto.
   ``You may have something there,'' the vice president said. Bush
said he would have to work on appearing more relaxed in front of
the cameras.
   Bond said New Jersey is one of nine states the campaign sees as
critical battlegrounds within the grasp of either candidate. The
other states Bond cited are California, Ohio, Pennsylvania,
Illinois, Missouri, Texas, Michigan and Wisconsin.
</TEXT>
