<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-USEncounter     09-21 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-US Encounter,0629</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Blast own Government in Conference With United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TBILISI, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At a U.S.-Soviet forum on human rights,
local people saved some of their sharpest barbs for their own
government.
   Participants from the southern Soviet republic of Georgia, where
a six-day friendship conference is being held, accused their own
officials of everything from treading on a local language to
destroying a historic monastery.
   ``The civil rights of my mother are being violated. She is being
forced out of her apartment with her daughter and her
granddaughter,'' one woman, her voice trembling, told the 500
people packed into the screening room at the Georgian Filmmakers'
Union building on Tuesday.
   The comment came on the second day of the annual conference that
brings together Soviet and American citizens. It is sponsored by
the Chautauqua (N.Y.) Institution and the Soviet
government-sanctioned Friendship Society.
   Tuesday's forum echoed the sharp exchanges that often embitter
superpower negotiations on human rights.
   ``American freedom rests on the bones of the Indians,'' said one
Soviet member of the audience in a comment to American panelists
Mark Palmer, U.S. ambassador to Hungary, and Spencer Oliver, chief
counsel to the House Foreign Affairs Committee.
   Some Georgians, however, used the forum to call on authorities
in Moscow to redress their complaints.
   Guram Mamoulia of Tbilisi accused the Soviet army of slowly
destroying a historic Georgian monastery by creating an artillery
firing range nearby.
   ``Two of my comrades came here today wanting to show fragments
of the shells that are destroying the monastery,'' the stocky man
said. ``But they were barred from entering.''
   Mamoulia appealed to Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev to
intervene personally.
   A complaint by another a Georgian member of the audience was
read aloud by Levan A. Alexidze, vice president of Tbilisi State
University:
   ``Why does the military continue to destroy major Georgian
monuments? Why are expelled Moslem Georgians denied their right of
regaining citizenship? Why is there no factory for
Georgian-language typewriters?''
   Soviet panelist Igor F. Blishchenko, one of his country's
experts on international law, expressed irritation with the
questions, saying there were more important matters to discuss.
   But Palmer said: ``We don't see anything small about a woman
being deprived of her apartment.''
   Only one of the Georgians' complaints was answered in detail. An
official from Georgia's agency for historic preservation said he
had received a letter from Defense Minister Dmitri T. Yazov saying
the artillery range had been shortened and the direction of fire
changed.
   The most emotional exchanges between Soviets and Americans came
during a discussion of Soviet Jews, many of whom have been trying
to leave the country for years.
   Oliver cited an Israeli government figure that 350,000 official
invitations have been issued to Soviet Jews so they can leave the
country.
   Samuel L. Zivs, first deputy chairman of the state-sanctioned
Soviet Anti-Zionist Committee, said Jewish emigration this year had
already topped 10,000 and would reach 15,000 by year's end.
   In contrast, only 917 Jews were allowed out in 1986, Zivs said.
   Soviet officials indicated they thought the tone of the meetings
had improved somewhat over the past two years, but not enough.
   Leonid I. Dobrokhotov, an official in the propaganda department
in the Communist Party Central Committee, said, ``If American
speakers in the past adopted the tone and spirit of a prosecutor,
here we have felt the tone of a teacher speaking to small children
...
   ``I share the attitude expressed by a number of Soviet speakers
that the best way to proceed would be to act as though we were all
students, and could learn from each other.''
</TEXT>
