<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Candidates-LegalIssues     09-21 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Candidates-Legal Issues,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Bush Differ on Affirmative Action</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush used an American Bar Association
questionnaire to criticize Michael Dukakis for his Massachusetts
prison furlough program, while Dukakis accused the Reagan
administration of eviscerating a program to provide legal services
for the poor.
   The two presidential contenders got in the digs while giving
statements on law-related issues to be published in the ABA
Journal. The responses were released Tuesday.
   ``Our No. 1 priority should be to ensure that those convicted of
violent crimes remain behind bars,'' Bush said when asked about the
nation's prisons. ``I strongly condemn the concept of placing such
felons on furloughs _ an idea embraced by Gov. Dukakis _ or putting
them in minimum security facilities.''
   Dukakis, the Democratic nominee, has come under repeated
criticism for a Massachusetts prison furlough program. A convicted
killer escaped while on furlough and raped and killed a woman in
another state. The program has since been changed.
   ``As a partial solution (to prison overcrowding) I favor
converting unnecessary military bases and other federal
installations to prison use,'' added Bush, the Republican nominee.
   Dukakis praised his state's ``intensive and highly successful
probation and parole supervision project to reduce overcrowding in
our prisons.''
   Both men said the long-term solution to overcrowded prisons is
construction of new prisons.
   The candidates also were asked their views of the Legal Services
Corp., the federally funded organization providing legal help to
the poor.
   President Reagan actively has sought to abolish the organization
but Congress has refused.
   Bush said the agency ``plays an important role'' in providing
legal services to the poor but said private attorneys also should
offer free help to those who cannot afford to pay.
   Dukakis said: ``While a Dukakis administration will encourage
private attorney involvement programs, it is clear that pro bono
work alone cannot meet the legal needs of the poor.
   ``The budget of the Legal Services Corp. has been savaged over
the past seven years and I will do all I can _ within the
constraints of a massive federal budget deficit _ to strengthen our
commitment to this vital program.''
   On affirmative action, Bush voiced opposition to racial quotas
but added, ``I do strongly support affirmative action programs
designed to remedy past discrimination and intend to by taking
aggressive steps to recruit minorities and other groups which
because of past discrimination have not yet been able join fully
the American mainstream.''
   The Reagan administration has opposed broad use of affirmative
action, seeking to limit it as a legal remedy for only those people
who themselves have been subjected to discriminatory treatment.
   Dukakis said that ``courts, appropriate public institutions and
local communities must have the ability to take whatever
affirmative steps are necessary to wipe out the lingering effects
of past discrimination.''
</TEXT>
