<DOCNO> AP880921-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-88 0302EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Quayle     09-21 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Says GOP Can Provide College Education, Health Insurance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Quayle departs for Phoenix 11:30 p.m. EDT; no PMs top likely.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Bush administration will guarantee
access to college for anybody who wants to go, Sen. Dan Quayle told
a university audience in pitching the Republicans as ``the party of
hopes and dreams.''
   At the University of Nevada-Las Vegas, the Republican vice
presidential nominee told 600 students and others Tuesday, ``We
understand the importance of higher education, and we're going to
make sure that anybody who wants to go to higher education will
have access to higher education, no matter what.''
   He did not elaborate, but George Bush has proposed allowing
parents to earn interest tax-free on savings bonds for college, and
pledged his support of the Pell Grant program, which President
Reagan once tried to curtail sharply.
   Quayle said, ``People want to see change and I can say we are
the party of change.'' He repeatedly compared Michael Dukakis to
former president Jimmy Carter.
   ``Gambling on another liberal sounding governor coming out of
nowhere would be a far greater gamble than anything you find on Las
Vegas Strip,'' he said.
   Quayle was flying to Arizona today to visit an award-winning
elementary school in Chandler and then to address the Rotary Club
in Phoenix, the city where he spent eight years of his youth.
   Later, he was headed to California and stops in Fresno,
Bakersfield and Los Angeles, where he was reuniting with his wife,
Marilyn, after her first solo campaign swing.
   The Indiana senator, at rallies in Boise, Idaho, and this
gambling capital, kept up his drumbeat of criticisms of Michael
Dukakis.
   In both Idaho and Nevada, he accused Dukakis of favoring broader
federal control over water on public lands. He charged that Dukakis
would let ``some Washington bureaucracy'' make decisions that could
adversely affect ranchers and farmers throughout the arid West.
   But Tom Herman, domestic policy adviser to the Dukakis campaign,
said Quayle is misrepresenting Dukakis' position.
   ``Once again, Dan Quayle simply has his facts wrong,'' Herman
said in Boston. ``But that's no surprise because he makes a habit
of misunderstanding and misstating the facts.
   ``Mike Dukakis believes that the federal government must
recognize the primacy of state water laws, particularly in the
West, that we must insure a steady and high quality water system as
a backbone of the Western economy.''
   Quayle, who once opposed raising the minimum wage, said he now
supports raising it from $3.35 to $4 an hour over the next two
years, coupled with a youth wage that would pay 80 percent of the
minimum.
   But Quayle said even the $4.55 minimum wage that Senate
Democrats are pressing for isn't enough for a single parent to
raise a family on. The answer is better training and education, as
well as an expanded earned income tax credit for the working poor,
he said.
   On the plight of the 37 million Americans with no health
insurance, Quayle suggested experimenting with letting small
businesses ``buy into the Medicaid program'' to cover their workers.
   Quayle got a warm reception from the crowd of more than 1,000 at
the Idaho capital. He encountered some heckling at the Las Vegas
campus, but many in the audience joined in a chant of ``Dukakis is
a wimp.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
