<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-88 0301EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PresidentialPoll     09-21 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presidential Poll,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll Gives Bush Lead On Several National Issues</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People say they would be better off
financially if Republican George Bush rather than Democrat Michael
Dukakis were elected president, according to a Washington Post-ABC
News poll.
   The poll also found Bush more capable of holding down taxes and
keeping the country out of war, while Dukakis was seen as clearly
better at protecting the Social Security system.
   The two were close on such personal characteristics as
experience, honesty, ability to be trusted in a crisis and ability
to get things done.
   Results of the survey of 1,271 likely voters were published in
today's editions of the Post. The survey, begun a week ago today
and finished Monday, found Bush leading Dukakis 50 percent to 46
percent if the election were being held today.
   Last week, a Washington Post-ABC News poll showed Dukakis
leading 48-45. The 3-point margin of error in both surveys meant
the candidates were essentially tied.
   Fifty percent of the respondents said they would be personally
better off financially under a Bush administration, compared with
38 percent saying they would benefit under a Dukakis administration.
   Forty-five percent said Bush would do better at keeping the
country out of war, compared with 38 percent for Dukakis.
Fifty-five percent said Bush would do a better job of holding taxes
down, compared with 31 percent for Dukakis. And 50 percent said
Bush would do a better job of controlling inflation, compared with
37 percent for Dukakis.
   However, Dukakis would do a better job than Bush of protecting
Social Security, according to 48 percent of the respondents,
compared with 38 percent who said Bush would do a better job.
   The survey also examined which issues were important to voters
and how strong they considered each candidate on those issues.
   According to the survey, six out of 10 respondents considered
holding down taxes to be a very important issue, two-thirds of the
respondents thought preserving American family values was a very
important issue and two-thirds found creating new jobs to be very
important.
   Bush had a slight lead in preserving American family values,
while Dukakis was seen as better able to create new jobs.
   The survey indicated that Dukakis still had trouble making
himself known among voters: 54 percent said they did not know
enough about the Massachusetts governor to judge whether he would
be a good president.
   Dukakis continued to benefit from his choice of Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen as a running mate, with 37 percent saying he would be more
qualified than his Republican counterpart, Sen. Dan Quayle of
Indiana, to assume the presidency. Only 9 percent said Quayle would
be more qualified.
</TEXT>
