<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Soviet     09-21 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Soviet,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz to Press Human Rights As Hope Fades For START Deal This
Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George Shultz plans to
press human rights issues in new talks with his Soviet counterpart
amid signs the Reagan administration has given up hopes of
completing a major nuclear arms accord this year.
   Shultz, in possibly his last full-scale meeting with Soviet
Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze, hopes to ``tie down some
unresolved issues'' in the stalled superpower negotiations to cut
long-range nuclear arsenals by 50 percent, Assistant Secretary of
State Rozanne L. Ridgway told a congressional panel.
   ``We certainly know we can't finish the START (Strategic Arms
Reduction Talks) treaty this year,'' Ms. Ridgway said Tuesday.
   Shevardnadze was scheduled to arrive here this evening and hold
talks with Shultz on Thursday and Friday, Ms. Ridgway said. The
Soviet foreign minister also was expected to call on President
Reagan.
   Although this week's meetings may be the final major talks
between Shultz and Schevardnadze on U.S-Soviet topics, ``it
certainly does not signal the end of the administration's
commitment to press forward'' on improving relations, Ms. Ridgway
said.
   ``We believe there is good work that can yet be done, and we
hope also to set the stage for the next administration _ of
whichever party it may be,'' she told the House subcommittee on
Europe and the Middle East.
   ``We will press the Soviets to clear the books of the remaining
human rights cases ... we will push on (freer) emigration,'' Ms.
Ridgway said. She mentioned exit for members of divided families,
separated spouses, dual nationals and people punished for religious
or political activity and said ``it would appear'' the exodus of
Soviet Jews may again reach 2,000 monthly, its level of the late
1970s. The August figure was 1,900.
   Progress on human rights in the Soviet Union is ``the key as far
as we are concerned'' to other pending issues, starting with a
successful conclusion to the current review conference in Vienna,
Austria, of the 1975 Helsinki East-West accords on security and
human rights, Ms. Ridgway said.
   ``We and our allies have been working very hard to bringing it
about _ but on our terms ... we are prepared to stay as long as it
takes to achieve it,'' she said, and ``there are prospects that the
final agreement pieces we insist upon at Vienna may fall into
place.''
   Negotiators in Vienna must agree on mandates for a new 35-nation
conference on confidence and security-building in Europe and on
negotiations on conventional arms by the NATO and Warsaw Pact
countries, Ms. Ridgway said.
   The Soviets have settled more divided family cases and lowered
emigration barriers, she said, but ``we still have problems in the
areas of freedom of assembly and speech.''
   Ms. Ridgway said the U.S. is satisfied with implementation of
the treaty concluded eliminating land-based intermediate-range
nuclear missiles. She also said Moscow appears to be keeping to its
schedule to withdraw its forces from Afghanistan by Feb. 15.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
