<HEAD>Reagan Unlikely To Hold News Conference Before Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan probably will not hold a
formal news conference until after his successor is chosen in the
Nov. 8 election.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, speaking Tuesday, did
not say why no news conference is foreseen in the next six weeks.
Reagan has an ambitious schedule of campaign trips on behalf of
Republican presidential nominee George Bush and GOP congressional
candidates before the election.
   The president's last news conference was at the seven-nation
economic summit in Toronto on June 21.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cruise Missiles to be Destroyed Next Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States will destroy the first of
the ground-launched cruise missiles it agreed to eliminate under
the U.S.-Soviet Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces treaty next month.
   The Defense Department announced Tuesday that 41 cruise missiles
and canisters and seven launchers are to be destroyed on Oct. 18-19
at Davis-Monthan Air Force Base near Tucson, Ariz.
   Under the treaty, Soviet officials are entitled to send up to 20
observers to watch the destruction in Arizona, according to
Pentagon officials.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Anti-Gun Group Says Semiautomatic and Automatic Assault Weapons on</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Increase
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Criminals, especially drug traffickers, are
increasingly arming themselves with powerful semiautomatic and
automatic assault weapons, an anti-gun group said.
   ``The number of assault weapons in civilian hands _ both
criminal and law abiding _ is estimated to be in the hundreds of
thousands, perhaps millions,'' the Education Fund to End Handgun
Violence said in a report released Tuesday.
   The group said police organizations, government agencies and
pro-gun control groups agree the number of such weapons has
increased dramatically in recent years, although no nationwide
statistics were available.
   Assault weapons have the capability of firing a large number of
rounds on a single magazine, great muzzle velocity and compact
design often including folding stocks that make it easier for the
weapon to be concealed.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Environmental Groups Want Ocean Clean-up Fund</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television actor Ted Danson is leading a
coalition of environmental groups in a campaign to get the next
administration and Congress to toughen laws against pollution of
the oceans.
   ``Saving the oceans will take more than election-year
rhetoric,'' Danson said at a news conference on Tuesday.
   Danson, co-star of the ``Cheers'' situation comedy, is president
and a founder of the year-old American Oceans Campaign based in
Santa Monica, Calif.
   Robert Sulnick, executive director of the campaign, said
supporters of next year's lobbying effort would try to win, among
other things, a ban on all dumping in the ocean and establishment
of a fund to tax companies and industries for cleanups.
</TEXT>
