<1ST_LINE>u p AM-WashPrimary 2ndLd-Writethru a0450 09-21 0801</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wash Primary, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0450,0820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Congressmen Battle In Democratic Senate Primary; Republican
Coasts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES returns; picks up material below dash.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID AMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Slade Gorton, attempting a Senate
comeback, coasted to a easy primary victory in Washington state
Tuesday while U.S. Rep. Don Bonker led fellow Democrat Mike Lowry
for their party's Senate nomination.
   As expected, Gov. Booth Gardner easily won renomination for a
second term in the Democratic primary.
   Gorton, a former state attorney general who swept into the
Senate on the Reagan landslide of 1980, demolished his lesser known
GOP challengers, former state Supreme Court Justice William Goodloe
of Seattle and Doug Smith, an Everett attorney and former White
House aide.
   With 32 percent of the state's 6,655 precincts reporting, Gorton
had 86 percent of the GOP vote, or 96,450 votes. Smith was a
distant second with 7 percent, or 8,297 votes, and Goodloe had 6
percent, or 6,810 votes.
   Lowry, the front-runner throughout the Democratic Senate primary
campaign, jumped to an early lead over Bonker, but then fell behind.
   ``It's gonna be a rollercoaster night,'' Bonker said.
   Bonker, who campaigned as a moderate who could regain the Senate
seat for the Democrats, had 53 percent of the Democratic vote, or
84,542 votes.
   Lowry, a self-described liberal who lost to Republican Sen. Dan
Evans in 1983, trailed with 47 percent, or 74,921 votes. It was
Evans' decision not to seek re-election that set off the state's
most exciting primary.
   Gardner, a popular Democrat who was one of Michael Dukakis'
earliest backers for the White House, enjoyed a whopping 90 percent
of the Democratic vote.
   Gardner had 146,805 votes, to 9,808 for political unknown Jeanne
Dixon of Bellevue, 4,738 for Richard Short of Grayland and 3,135
for Ted Parker Fix of Tacoma.
   State Rep. Bob Williams of Longview trailed King County
prosecutor Norm Maleng for the GOP gubernatorial nomination.
   With 30 percent of precincts reporting, Williams had 57,653
votes, or 61 percent, to Maleng's 34,017 votes, or 36 percent. Paul
Dean Santos of Port Orchard was a distant third with 2,256 votes,
or 2 percent.
   Maleng refused to concede, saying he would await further votes
from his political base, King County, which encompasses Seattle,
where 80 percent of the precincts had yet to be counted.
   In a hot race for Bonker's 3rd District congressional seat,
state Rep. Jolene Unsoeld, an Olympia liberal, won over John
McKibbin, a moderate Clark County commissioner.
   Unsoeld had 56 percent of the vote, with 30,006 votes to
McKibbin's 21,347, or 39 percent. John Libby Sr. of Olympia, an
adherent of the political extremist Lyndon LaRouche, trailed with 5
percent, or 2,697 votes.
   Bill Wight of Toledo won the Republican nomination in the 3rd,
with 14,366 votes. Bill Hughes of Vancouver was second with 8,757
votes.
   In Lowry's 7th district, former state Sen. Jim McDermott of
Seattle appeared headed for the Democratic nomination, which is
considered tantamount to election in the state's most Democratic
district.
   McDermott had 48 percent, or 6,727 votes, to lead Seattle City
Councilman Norm Rice, who was seeking to become the state's first
black congressman. Rice had 28 percent, or 3,882 votes. King County
Assessor Ruthe Ridder had 23 percent, or 3,263 votes.
   Robert Edwards of Renton led the GOP nomination, with 1,167
votes to Robert Blake's 1,009 votes.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In the Senate race, Lowry, 49, staked out the liberal ground,
and Bonker, 51, claimed the moderate stance. On the Republican
side, Gorton billed himself as the conservative choice despite
opponents' claims he wasn't conservative enough.
   Bonker, who has represented the 3rd District in southwestern
Washington since 1975, spent the early part of his campaign trying
to improve his name recognition. Lowry, whose 7th District included
the media center of Seattle, had no such problem. He's been in
Congress since 1979.
   Although they have similar voting records, the two disagreed on
several issues, chiefly those of interest to regional voters, and
Bonker hammered on those differences as the campaign wore on.
   Bonker criticized Lowry for not supporting his proposed ban on
exporting raw logs, an issue of keen interest in the Northwest.
While Bonker argued such exports cost mill jobs, Lowry said a ban
would hurt small logging companies.
   The two also disagreed over the Navy's proposed home port in
Everett, with Lowry calling it the ``home pork'' and siding with
environmentalists against the project. Bonker said it would be
vital to the Everett economy.
   Gorton lost his Senate seat to Democrat Brock Adams. Many felt
the upset lay partly in Gorton's icy image and perception that he
had stopped listening to voters.
   This time, Gorton vowed to ``hear better, to listen better.''
Among other things, he opposes higher taxes and favors efforts to
control crime and illegal drugs.
</TEXT>
