<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     09-21 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Share Prices Bounce Back on Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rebounded sharply on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange today, and the dollar moved up against the Japanese yen
after fluctuations throughout the session.
   The dollar, which opened at 134.05 yen, ended trading at 134.18
yen, up 0.03 yen from Tuesday's close of 134.15 yen. The currency
was traded in a narrow range of 134.00-134.19 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which fell
sharply in the morning session by losing 253.02 points, regained
164.08 points or 0.6 percent to rise back up to 27,712.66.
   A dealer with Daiwa Securities said traders started to buy
issues after they saw share prices fall sharply after Tuesday and
Wednesday morning amid reports of Emperor Hirohito's failing health.
   ``News about the emperor's serious condition was a negative
factor that affected investors psychologically,'' he said, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   Mitsuhiko Kinugasa of the Daiwa Bank said the dollar-yen rate
fluctuated because of two opposing forces in the market.
   Those who were attracted by the higher European interest rates
tended to sell the yen to invest in the European currencies, mainly
the West German mark, but others tended to buy the yen in
anticipation of a stronger currency, he said.
</TEXT>
