<1ST_LINE>r w PM-People-Warner-Wilding     09-21 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Warner-Wilding,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Elizabeth Taylor's Former Husband Helps Her Son Get Immigration
Waiver</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elizabeth Taylor's sixth husband, who happens
to be a member of a key Senate committee, is getting Congress to
help her son by another marriage avoid deportation because of drug
conviction 14 years ago.
   Without dissent, the Senate late Tuesday approved a waiver
exempting soap opera star Michael Wilding, who has the same name as
his late father, from a law that prohibits permanent resident visas
for aliens convicted of drug violations.
   The private relief bill was sought by Sen. John Warner, R-Va.,
Miss Taylor's sixth husband and the 34-year-old Wilding's
stepfather for six years until Warner and Miss Taylor divorced in
1982.
   Michael Wilding was born to Miss Taylor during her second
marriage, to the late British actor Michael Wilding.
   Now living in New York City and an actor on the television soap
opera ``The Guiding Light,'' Wilding was convicted in Wales in 1974
of possessing marijuana and cultivating marijuana plants in a house
he shared with six other people.
   He renounced his U.S. citizenship in 1971, but returned to the
United States 10 years later. Because of the marijuana conviction
in Great Britain, however, the Immigration and Naturalization
Service has refused to grant him a permanent resident visa.
   ``My knowledge and respect for this man developed during my
marriage to his mother, Elizabeth Taylor,'' Warner said in a letter
to the Senate Judiciary Committee. ``So far as I know, and his
mother knows, Mr. Wilding has lived a drug-free, law-abiding
existence since the occurrence of the offenses during his very
early life.''
   Warner said the INS has taken no definite steps to expel Wilding
but said the actor's attorneys anticipate the government will
commence deportation proceedings in the near future.
   ``I can attest from my personal knowledge, and that of his
mother, that Mr. Wilding would continue to be a law-abiding
resident of the United States,'' the senator said.
</TEXT>
