<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-88 0450EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-MOVE-Justice Bjt   09-21 0687</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-MOVE-Justice, Bjt,0709</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bitterness And Civil Suits Linger After Federal Move Case Closed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The decision to close a federal probe into
the fatal 1985 MOVE confrontation without indictments ends the
criminal investigation, but bitterness and civil suits linger in
the case.
   The U.S. Justice Department announced Tuesday that a grand jury
cleared Mayor W. Wilson Goode, other city officials and police of
criminal wrongdoing in the bombing of a west Philadelphia rowhouse.
   The police bombing _ approved by Goode _ and resulting fire that
officials allowed to rage out of control left 11 members of the
radical group MOVE dead and 61 homes destroyed.
   ``There's always going to be some nagging doubts about whether
justice prevailed in this case,'' said William H. Brown III, the
chairman of the mayor's special investigative commission, which
found Goode ``grossly negligent'' for his role in the events of May
13, 1985.
   Assistant Attorney General William Bradford Reynolds, head of
the Justice Department's civil rights division, said in Washington
that evidence was insufficient to seek indictments on any civil
rights violations.
   In a three-paragraph statement, the department said no report
will be issued by the federal grand jury that convened in
Philadelphia in April 1987. The panel based its inquiry on the work
of an FBI investigation launched in July 1985.
   A Philadelphia County grand jury in May strongly criticized city
officials for their handling of the confrontation but found no
reason to pursue criminal charges.
   District Attorney Ronald Castille, whose office presided over
the local investigation, said the federal decision ``confirms what
we said last May, that it was a series of tragic mistakes by
elected and appointed officials.''
   Goode was happy the investigation was completed.
   ``Two grand juries have fully investigated this matter and have
reached a point of no criminality involved. For that I am
pleased,'' Goode said.
   But others were angered by the federal grand jury's conclusion
and its decision not to release a report.
   Louise James, sister of MOVE founder John Africa, who died in
the blaze, said the investigations were prejudiced against MOVE.
   ``I said over and over that he (Goode) is a murderer and I'll
stick by that,'' said Ms. James, whose son also was killed in the
rowhouse.
   Added Brown: ``(To) deliberately place a bomb on that house ...
and having done that then make a decision to not put the fire out
and let it burn while children are in the house, if that's not
sufficient grounds to find that their civil rights were violated, I
don't what is.
   ``And to compound that by not even issuing a report to tell the
people how they came to their decision, I think is the height of
arrogance,'' he said.
   Five children and six adults died inside the barricaded rowhouse
when police bombed the dwelling to evict MOVE followers. The bomb,
dropped from a helicopter, contained the powerful military
explosive C-4.
   The bomb touched off a fire that raged out of control while
fireman held back, afraid they would be hit by gunfire that had
echoed through the poor neighborhood.
   Only two people escaped from the house: a woman known as Ramona
Africa and Michael Moses Ward, then 13 and known to MOVE members as
Birdie Africa. All MOVE members adopted the surname Africa and most
were black.
   Members of MOVE, whose name did not stand for anything in
particular, championed back-to-nature rituals, lived in filth,
refused to send their children to school and openly disobeyed
health and safety laws.
   Brown and Castille said civil lawsuits filed against city
officials by survivors and relatives of those who died would keep
the controversy alive.
   ``They all are going to have to face up to the very substantial
civil lawsuits,'' Brown said.
   Andino Ward, Michael Ward's father, said the federal decision
could strengthen the lawsuit filed on behalf of his son ``simply
because it may be the only viable alternative that will allow this
entire fiasco to come to the forefront and really name those who
should be named and held accountable for their actions in this.''
</TEXT>
