<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NoahRobinson     09-21 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Noah Robinson,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jesse Jackson's Half Brother Charged With Murder For Hire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor plans to seek the death
penalty against Jesse Jackson's half brother for allegedly hiring
members of a Chicago street gang to kill a man two years ago, a
newspaper reported today.
   Noah Robinson, a 45-year-old Chicago businessman and Greenville
native, was charged with murder Tuesday for the 1986 slaying of
Leroy ``Hambone'' Barber, who was shot outside a downtown building
owned by Robinson.
   Robinson turned himself in to police Tuesday evening and was in
the Greenville County Detention Center awaiting a bond hearing
today, Solictor Joseph Watson said.
   Although Robinson and Jackson share relatives in Greenville, the
former Democratic presidential hopeful has said he has had no
recent contact with his half brother.
   Robinson was the sixth person charged with murder for Barber's
slaying. Barber once worked for Robinson in Chicago and the two men
had had several altercations over the years, Greenville police have
said.
   Murder warrants were issued previously against five Chicago men:
Edgar Cooksey, Alan Earl Knox, Eugene Cleo Hunter, Henry Leon
Harris and Jackie Early Clay. Clay is a fugitive and the other four
are in police custody. Their ages were unavailable.
   Authorities have alleged that a five-member team from Chicago's
El Rukn street gang shot Barber in the head Jan. 2, 1986, after he
was called to a pay telephone outside a lounge in the Greenville
building.
   A former gang member, Tramell Davis, told authorities that the
leader of the El Rukns ordered Barber killed for harassing Robinson.
   ``Robinson's alleged involvement is he basically hired an El
Rukn hit team to come to downtown Greenville to kill Barber,''
Watson told The Associated Press on Tuesday.
   Watson would not comment further about the case and said police
were continuing their investigation along with the federal Bureau
of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms office in Chicago.
   The Greenville News quoted Watson today as saying he expected to
file in the near future notice of intent to seek the death penalty
against Robinson and ``other principal co-defendants'' because it
was a murder for hire.
   Calls by The Associated Press to Watson's home late Tuesday were
not answered.
   In a statement distributed Tuesday by the Rev. J.M. Flemming,
who accompanied him to the jail, Robinson said, ``I had no role in
or no knowledge of that killing prior to it happening.''
   In the statement, Robinson said the case against him was based
on statements by gang members with criminal records who were
offered cash and lenient sentences in exchange for testifying
against him.
   Flemming said Robinson was being treated unfairly.
   ``This ought not be taking place and would not be taking place
if Mr. Robinson was not a wealthy individual and a black individual
in the community,'' Flemming said.
   Robinson was charged in June with conspiring to kill Janice D.
Rosemond, who told a Chicago grand jury last fall that she
witnessed the 1986 slaying of Barber.
   Within weeks of her testimony, Ms. Rosemond was attacked in her
Greenville apartment. She survived five stab wounds and later
recanted her testimony about the Barber slaying, saying she had
been intimidated by police.
   Freddie E. Sweeney, who once worked as a janitor in one of
Robinson's companies, has been charged with assault and battery
with intent to kill Ms. Rosemond.
   Robinson and a former employee, Jake H. Oliver, are charged with
criminal conspiracy, intimidation of a witness, obstruction of
justice and accessory to a felony in connection with the stabbing,
and Robinson had been free on a $500,000 bond.
</TEXT>
