<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hurricane-Mexico     09-21 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hurricane-Mexico,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fifth Bus Found, Death Toll From Flash Flood Reaches 140</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities scouring a dry riverbed
discovered a fifth bus that was washed away in a flash flood
triggered by Hurricane Gilbert, and the confirmed death toll in the
disaster rose to 140.
   A ranching settlement of 100 families remained cut off from help
Tuesday by flooding and landslides in the mountains surrounding
this northern industrial center, said Nuevo Leon state government
spokesman Daniel Dimas.
   ``We're trying to find out what we can do to get supplies to
these people,'' he said.
   Authorities said the death toll from the flash flood in the
normally dry bed of the Santa Catarina River could go higher.
   ``We have recovered 140 cadavers. It's difficult to say how many
more there could be. It could be very terrible,'' Dimas said
Tuesday.
   He said most of the bodies were being found about 20 miles
downstream, and that wreckage of the fifth passenger bus was found
30 miles downstream.
   Earlier, authorities said they had recovered about 100 bodies
and estimated that 200 people were killed in the Saturday's
flooding.
   At least 31 people also died when Gilbert, the most intense
storm on record, ripped through the Yucatan Peninsula last week
with winds of up to 200 mph. The storm killed 30 people in Haiti,
26 in Jamaica, eight in Honduras and five in the Dominican Republic.
   Hurricane Gilbert dumped a foot of rain on Monterrey on Friday
and Saturday, sending a torrent through the Santa Catarina's
riverbed. The flash flood swept away four intercity buses and one
local bus traveling on roads built in the riverbed.
   Hundreds of homes were destroyed and thousands more flooded with
water and mud. About 30,000 people remained in shelters Tuesday,
and authorities estimated damage at $90 million.
   Some neighborhoods around the Monterrey area remained without
water due to damage to pumps. Health authorities recommended that
citizens boil water because of increased risk of viral and
bacterial infections in contaminated water.
</TEXT>
