<1ST_LINE>r i PM-CostaRica-Olympics     09-21 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Costa Rica-Olympics,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds Celebrate Nation's First Olympic Medal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of people spilled into the
streets of this capital to celebrate Costa Rica's first Olympic
Games medal _ the silver won by swimmer Sylvia Poll in the women's
200-meter freestyle.
   President Oscar Arias, winner of the 1987 Nobel Peace Prize,
told reporters before Tuesday's race that he would be glued to his
television set, cheering on the 6-foot-3 Costa Rican.
   Just before the race, the streets of San Jose appeared deserted,
and one television commentator asked viewers watching the
competition in Seoul, South Korea, to cross their fingers and wish
Poll luck.
   The silver medal in hand, hundreds rushed into the streets and
drivers honked their car horns to celebrate Poll's achievement.
   ``I was sure that Sylvia would win one of the three medals ....
It's like she said before she left Costa Rica: `I'll fight for my
country and all of Latin America,' and she did it tonight,'' said
Cristina Valvelde Vargas, 18, wiping tears from her eyes.
   ``Long live Costa Rica!,'' shouted one driver between blasts of
his car horn. ``They'll know who we are now,'' he said, alluding to
this democratic country's population of 2.5 million.
   Other celebrants embraced and shouted in San Jose's downtown
Cultural Park.
   Poll, 17, emerged as a world contender during the 1987 Pan
American Games in Indianapolis, where she won eight medals, three
of them gold.
</TEXT>
