<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     09-21 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Storms Send Summer On Its Way</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The last full day of summer saw the beginnings of blustery fall
weather with thunderstorms and showers sweeping through New England
and another storm system rumbling through the Southwest.
   Today is the last day of summer; autumn officially begins
Thursday with the autumnal equinox. The equinox occurs when
daylight hours nearly equal the hours of darkness. The moment the
sun appears to cross the Equator on its annual journey south occurs
at 3:29 p.m. EDT.
   Showers and a few thunderstorms this morning moved over New
England just ahead of a cold front extending from Vermont into the
southeastern part of the nation. Thunderstorms also rumbled through
New York City as well as Boston.
   A developing storm system over southern Nevada scattered showers
and thunderstorms over the southern Plateau and the southern
Plains. Thunderstorms delivered heavy rain to Carlsbad, N.M., late
Tuesday and early this morning.
   As much as 3 inches of rain was reported near Muleshoe, Texas.
Over 2 inches fell across Curry and Roosevelt counties in
east-central New Mexico. Street flooding was reported in Clovis and
Portales, N.M., as well as Elida and Artesia. Other showers and
thunderstorms were isolated over eastern Arizona and southern
Nevada.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
through Utah and northern Arizona, Southern California, the
Colorado Rockies, New Mexico and southwest Texas; lingering showers
in New England; mostly cloudy skies covering the northern Plains,
the upper Mississippi Valley and most of Texas; and mostly sunny
skies over the rest of the nation.
   High temperatures were forecast for the 70s or 80s across much
of the nation; in the 50s over northern Minnesota and North Dakota;
the 60s over Nevada, northern parts of the Pacific Northwest, the
northern Rockies and from the northern Great Lakes into northern
New England; the 90s from eastern Texas through the lower
Mississippi Valley into the southern Atlantic region and Florida;
and the 90s over parts of the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 35
degrees at Malmstrom Air Force Base near Great Falls, Mont., to 83
degrees at Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 72 fair; Boston 69 thunderstorm; Buffalo 61
cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 74 foggy; Cincinnati 55 fair; Cleveland 61
cloudy; Detroit 56 cloudy; Miami 80 fair; New York 69 fair;
Philadelphia 70 fair; Pittsburgh 64 cloudy; Portland, Maine 62
foggy; Washington 71 foggy.
   _Central: Bismarck 40 cloudy; Chicago 56 cloudy; Dallas-Fort
Worth 80 fair; Denver 58 cloudy; Des Moines 53 fair; Indianapolis
54 fair; Kansas City 61 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 50 cloudy;
