<HEAD>Dollar Steady, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was trading steadily against major
currencies on quiet European markets today as players awaited U.S.
inflation figures and a Group of Seven meeting.
   Gold prices fell sharply, toward $400 an ounce, after a steep
decline in New York on Tuesday.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar was expected to trade
in a narrow range in advance of the release at 11:30 a.m. (8:30
a.m. EDT) of U.S. consumer price index figures for August.
   Still, they said the market was unlikely to be much affected by
the figures, which were expected to show a small increase.
   Traders also were looking for some, but not much, guidance from
the meeting of finance ministers and central bankers from the Group
of Seven industrial countries in West Berlin on Saturday.
   Most players do not expect any change in present international
coordination policies, however, dealers said.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar edged up 0.03 yen to a closing 134.18 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 134.15 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.8717 West German marks, up from 1.8641
   _1.5810 Swiss francs, up from 1.5740
   _6.3617 French francs, up from 6.3385
   _2.1069 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1075
   _1,391.25 Italian lire, down from 1,391.50
   _1.2180 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2203
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.679 dollars,
cheaper for buyers than late Tuesday's $1.6865.
   On the precious metals market, gold prices continued to slide
following the Tuesday drop in New York, which traders attributed to
a growing investor disillusionment with gold.
   They said there was sentiment against gold as a long-term
investment and as a hedge against inflation.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $402 a troy ounce,
sharply down from $410 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning today, the
city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of
$401.60.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $402.50, down from $410.50 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold dropped $7.74 to close at a bid
$405.38.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.20 a troy
ounce, down from $6.36 bid late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
