<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Equinox 1stLd-Writethru a0422 09-21 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Equinox, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0422,480</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 2 grafs new, recasting to clarify that light-dark balance
refers to the day, not a specific time; picks up 3rd graf, Not
since.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Earliest Equinox of the Century</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The date when daylight hours nearly equal
those of darkness occurs Thursday, as the autumnal equinox makes
its earliest appearance so far in this century.
   The moment of equinox, when the sun appears to cross the Equator
on its annual journey south, occurs at 19:29 universal time, which
is 3:29 p.m. EDT.
   Not since 1897 has the equinox come this early, reports LeRoy
Doggett, head of the Nautical Almanac Office at the U.S. Naval
Observatory.
   The equinox will occur even earlier in four years, when it comes
at 18:44 universal time on Sept. 22, 1992, and also at 18:01 on
Sept. 22, 1996.
   And in 2000, the equinox will edge all the way back to 17:29
universal time on Sept. 22 of that year.
   The tendency of the equinox to occur earlier will continue,
Doggett said, at least until the year 2100, when the absence of a
leap year will shift it to later dates again.
   The equinoxes are the days of approximately equal amounts of
daylight and darkness. Many people, including calendar makers,
arbitrarily consider the autumnal equinox the start of fall, and
the spring equinox the start of spring, although there are no
official definitions of those seasons.
   The four-year cycle of inserting an extra day in leap years
tends to cause back-and-forth shifts in the calendar dates of
natural phenomena such as the equinoxes and solstices.
   All this equinox shifting occurs because the Earth's actual year
doesn't come out to an even number of days.
   The Gregorian calendar, now in use, is 365 days long _ 366 in
leap years. The leap day added every four years means the calendar
year averages out to 365 days, 6 hours.
   But it takes 365 days, 5 hours, 48 minutes and 46 seconds to go
from one equinox to the next.
   That means there is a difference of 11 minutes and 14 seconds.
   That doesn't sound like much, but over the centuries it adds up.
   To compensate, the calendar skips leap days in most century
years. The year 1900, for example, was not a leap year.
   But there's an exception: Century years that can be divided by
the number 400 are leap years. So, the year 2000 will be a leap
year, getting an extra day.
   And that means the calendar year will be a little longer,
causing the equinox to occur a little earlier that year.
   Thus the equinox won't be able to head back to its later dates
until after the year 2100, which won't be a leap year since it
can't be divided by 400.
   Universal time is also known as Greenwich time. It is five hours
later than Eastern Standard Time and four hours ahead of Eastern
Daylight Time. Thus 3:29 p.m. EDT Thursday _ 15:29 on a 24-hour
clock _ is 19:29 universal time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880921-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-09-21-88 0832EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FiresRdp     09-21 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fires Rdp,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Backfire Helps Firefighters Divert Vacaville Blaze</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A backfire and favorable weather helped hundreds of firefighters
divert a 5-day-old blaze away from expensive northern California
homes. Near Yellowstone National Park, a pilot survived the crash
of his firefighting helicopter.
   Although the fire west and north of Vacaville, Calif., continued
to burn over a 32-mile area today, about 500 residents who had been
evacuated were allowed back into their homes Tuesday.
   The only uncontained portion of the blaze was in rugged terrain
in an unpopulated area, firefighters said Tuesday after completing
a 10-mile-long fire break just west of Vacaville and setting fire
to brush west of the break.
   ``The backfire operation was pretty darn successful,'' said Kirk
Landuyt, a California Department of Forestry spokesman. ``The wind
has cooperated,'' pushing the controlled fire into the blaze and
keeping it from reaching homes on the edge of Vacaville, he said.
   Elsewhere across the West on Tuesday, the situation was improved
as the worst summer for fires in three decades wound to a close. In
all, nearly 70,000 fires have been tallied, blackening more than
4.1 million acres, about half of them in Alaska.
   ``I think fire season is just about over here,'' spokeswoman
Madelyn Kempf said as crews broke camp and began departing from the
34,500-acre Red Bench fire in Montana's Glacier National Park. Some
200 firefighters also left Oregon's Willamette National Forest on
Tuesday, although others remained behind to finish firefighting
efforts there.
   In the Yellowstone National Park area, only three of 13 blazes
that charred 1.6 million acres remained uncontained, said park
spokeswoman Amy Vanderbilt.
   ``It's been a fairly quiet day in terms of fire activity,'' she
said. ``We've still got crews out there working on (fire) line
construction and mop-up efforts.
   A helicopter pilot trying to fill a water bucket from a pond
while working on a fire burning in Shoshone National Forest just
east of Yellowstone crashed upside down, but climbed safely out of
his aircraft, said fire information officer Chris Thompson.
   A rescue team found the pilot sitting on the bank of the pond,
Thompson said.
   The Vacaville-area blaze destroyed seven homes Sunday and did an
estimated $7 million damage Monday to a cluster of military,
government and private communications towers and facilities on a
hilltop within fire lines.
   As of Tuesday night, the fire near the city some 45 miles
northeast of San Francisco had burned 22,000 acres and was 60
percent contained by a force of 1,882 firefighters. Backfires were
expected to increase the amount burned to 28,000 acres, said
Forestry Department spokeswoman Lori Lippitt.
   Firefighters were optimistic about two other major northern
California fires Tuesday night.
   One blaze, about 20 miles east of Redding, was reported 80
percent contained by a force of nearly 1,200 firefighters. Since
the weekend, it had blackened 7,790 acres and destroyed 24 homes
and 34 other buildings.
   The other fire was being fought by about 600 firefighters in
steep hills on the eastern side of Lake Berryessa. It had burned
4,800 acres by Tuesday evening, but the only threatened structures
were scattered ranch buildings.
   ``We're really optimistic. The fire is beginning to die down,''
said Forestry Department spokesman Bruce Hagen.
   Gov. George Deukmejian on Tuesday proclaimed states of emergency
for Shasta County around Redding, and Solano County around
Vacaville, the first step in making state and federal aid available
to wildfire victims.
</TEXT>
