<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th item of a0457 to CORRECT to `retrospective' sted
`retrospect'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cartoonist F.O. Alexander, who created ``Joe
Doakes,'' the everyday citizen bearing a heavy tax burden, is
having a retrospective of his works just in time for the fall
elections.
   The late Hubert Humphrey and astronaut-turned-senator John Glenn
are just two of the politicians depicted in ``Off and Running:
Election Cartoons 1952-1967,'' at Temple University.
   But readers of the Bulletin newspaper, which stopped publishing
in 1982, may best remember the short, balding, ordinary Joe Doakes,
an extra-pleasant, super-modest common citizen who was usually
being squeezed by the tax man.
   Alexander drew a cartoon for the Bulletin's editorial page from
1941 until his retirement in 1967. His work was syndicated to
newspapers across the nation.
   Alexander said he tended to be more liberal than many of his
colleagues.
   ``I wanted to attack Joe McCarthy for a long time,'' he said.
``He frightened everyone.''
   After his first anti-McCarthy cartoon was published, ``I was
thought to be a pinko and Commie.''
</TEXT>
