<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Helmsleys     09-21 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Helmsleys,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harry Helmsley Seeking Out of Tax Case for Medical Reasons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Real estate billionaire Harry Helmsley, facing a
tax evasion trial with his wife next week, has health problems that
could have him removed from the case, his attorneys say.
   The disclosure came Tuesday during a hearing where U.S. District
Judge John Walker agreed to unseal transcripts of previous
closed-door hearings concerning Helmsley's health.
   Helmsley, 79, and his 67-year-old wife, Leona, the self-styled
``queen'' of the Helmsley hotel chain, were indicted in April on
state and federal charges. They are accused of hiding some $4
million in renovations to their Greenwich, Conn., mansion as
business expenses and taking bogus tax deductions.
   The Helmsleys have pleaded innocent to the 188-count state
indictment and the 47-count federal indictment. State prosecutors
have agreed to let the federal case go first.
   The Associated Press and several other news organizations had
petitioned Walker to release the sealed papers. At the start of the
hearing Tuesday, the judge said he would ``permit the unsealing of
all records except grand jury materials.''
   Walker said the material to be unsealed within ``the next day''
concerned ``the physical condition of Mr. Helmsley and whether he
is fit to stand trial.'' His attorneys would give no details of
Helmsley's medical condition.
   In other pre-trial action, attorneys for the Helmsleys moved to
have their clients' case heard separately from their two former
aides. Walker also delayed decision on relocating the trial to
Philadelphia due to potentially prejudicial pretrial publicity.
   Defense lawyer Gerald A. Feffer said the Helmsleys need a
separate trial from defendants Joseph V. Licari and Frank J. Turco
because the Helmsleys plan a conflicting defense.
   The Helmsleys will charge that the pair, onetime Helmsley
employees, created false invoices in order to cover up their own
thefts, not to help the Helmsleys defraud the government of tax
revenues, Feffer said.
   The Helmsleys are slated to go on trial next Monday, but
Assistant U.S. Attorney James DeVita asked for a three-week delay
so government experts could evaluate Helmsley's health records to
see if ``more medical examinations are warranted.''
   Walker said he would decide Thursday on DeVita's request.
Helmsley's chief lawyer, John Wing, said he had no objection to the
delay although he doubted further tests would reach a different
result.
   Neither of the Helmsleys was present at the hearing.
</TEXT>
