<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0444 09-21 0877</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0444,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Challenges Bush to State His Stand on Health Care</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 new grafs after pvs 4th graf bgng, He was, with
Dukakises' Yom Kippur message; Dukakis event 1:15 p.m. EDT; lead
prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis is deriding
Republican George Bush's record as one of such neglect and
indifference to the needy ``that even the American flag can't
hide'' his shortcomings.
   Dukakis challenged his GOP presidential rival on Tuesday to come
out ``from behind the flag'' and tell the voters what he proposes
to do about health care for Americans who can't afford it.
   Dukakis said he wants to guarantee them all health insurance,
beginning with legislation to require that all employers offer
basic coverage to working people and their families.
   He was announcing another health care proposal today, this one
to offer prenatal and infant care for all, guaranteed by the
government. That was to be announced in Dukakis' one campaign
appearance of the day, at Brigham and Women's Hospital, near his
Brookline home.
   The Massachusetts governor and his wife Kitty, who is Jewish,
wished ``a very happy and healthy New Year'' to their friends in
the Jewish community on Yom Kippur, the holiest of Jewish holidays.
   They issued a message vowing their support for peace between
Israel and its Arab neighbors, respect for human rights, the right
of Soviet Jews to emigrate freely and for ending ``all forms of
racism, bigotry and anti-Semitism and discrimination'' in the
United States.
   Dukakis said Tuesday his ultimate goal is universal national
health insurance, to match the program he signed into law in
Massachusetts less than six months ago.
   ``The simplest and the fairest and the most affordable first
step toward that goal is to require all employers, with some
exceptions for small businesses, to provide basic health insurance
for their workers and dependents,'' the governor said at Western
Kentucky University in Bowling Green, Ky.
   Dukakis said his first-stage program wouldn't cost the federal
government anything _ and could actually save money by reducing
expenditures for uninsured patients.
   He offered no figures on the cost to employers.
   The Dukakis campaign said it had no firm cost estimates,
although issues adviser Christopher Edley said the employer phase
of the Massachusetts system will cost employers about $1,000 a year
for each newly-insured worker.
   Dukakis kept his focus on selected themes during a two-day
southern swing that ended Tuesday night. In Little Rock, Ark.,
Houston and Kentucky, he talked about economics, then energy, then
health care.
   Dukakis sought to turn Bush's Pledge of Allegiance issue into a
boomerang, taunting his rival for flag-waving. The vice president
has assailed Dukakis for his 1977 veto of a bill to require
Massachusetts schoolteachers to lead their pupils in the pledge
each day.
   At the time, Dukakis cited a court ruling that the legislation
was unconstitutional.
   The Democratic nominee said the vice president isn't talking
about problems such as health care for people who can't afford it
and don't have adequate insurance.
   ``Today he's visiting a flag factory,'' Dukakis said
sardonically. ``Mr. Bush, don't you think it's about time you came
out from behind that flag and told us what you intend to do to
provide basic health care for 37 million of our fellow citizens?
   ``The fact is that he has no plan, but he does have a record _ a
record of indifference, a record of neglect, a record that even the
American flag can't hide.''
   Dukakis said that from now on, he intends to stick to his own
issues agenda, and leave it to his aides and allies to reply to
accusations by Bush and other Republicans.
   ``We're going to make sure that's the message, not some
response,'' he said.
   In Little Rock, Dukakis had listed an agenda of designated
issues for the campaign weeks ahead, among them opportunities and
work for people on public assistance, programs to ease the
insecurity of the elderly and proposals to make good housing
affordable to all Americans.
   Even so, the Dukakis organization was having some problems
executing the plays in its new game book. His health care proposal,
not brand new but packaged and promoted as a major campaign
initiative, was presented at a dawn briefing in Houston by Dukakis
advisers. Then Dukakis went to a Houston hospital, dramatizing the
issue in a discussion of health care and insurance costs with a
dozen patients and family members in a cancer ward waiting room. He
told them he'll do something about the problem ``if all goes well
on the eighth of November ... Spread the word.''
   But the candidate didn't get around to making his centerpiece
speech on the subject until hours later.
   Most of Dukakis' time during the next four days was set aside
for debate practice. The Democratic nominee was looking at likely
issues and, with his aides, rehearsing questions that may be put by
panelists when the candidates meet in Winston-Salem, N.C., Sunday
night.
   Dukakis' flight home from Bowling Green was detoured for an
unscheduled maintenance stop at Dulles International Airport
outside Washington, D.C. A landing light had to be repaired before
the Presidential Airways jet could go on to a night landing in
Boston.
</TEXT>
