<FILEID>AP-PX-09-21-88 0935EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeltaCrash     09-21 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Delta Crash,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Clicks' On Crash Tape May Indicate Plane's Flaps Were Improperly
Set</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A preliminary analysis of evidence in the crash of
Delta Flight 1141 shows the jet's wing flaps may have been lowered
for takeoff but in an improper position, according to a report
published today.
   The Dallas Morning News quoted a source familiar with the
investigation as saying that analysis of the plane's cockpit voice
recorder picked up the sound of two ``clicks.''
   Some investigators say the clicks could be the sound of the crew
moving the Boeing 727-200's flap-selection lever, first to the
2-degree setting and then to the 5-degree position. The lever
should have been moved a third time to the 15-degree angle, the
report said.
   Federal investigators have previously targeted the flaps in a
search for the cause of the Aug. 31 crash, which killed 14 people.
They have been trying to determine whether the plan's flaps,
movable surfaces on the wings that provide extra lift, were
extended in their proper 15-degree position at takeoff.
   ``What you hear (on the tape of the cockpit conversation) are
two `clicks' in quick succession,'' the newspaper quoted the source
as saying. ``That means that the flaps were at least at the
5-degree setting.
   ``If it's 2 degrees or 5 degrees or 15 degrees, there are
differences'' in the way the plane flies, the newspaper quoted a
safety board official as saying.
   ``The question of whether there would be noticeable differences
... all of this will have to be determined through performance
analysis of the aircraft.''
   The plane's flap control lever has notches that could produce
clicking sounds as the lever is moved, the newspaper said.
   ``Obviously, if they (the crew) thought they were at one flap
setting when in fact they were at another, there could be
problems,'' another NTSB official was quoted as saying.
   But a safety board investigator cautioned that the sounds on the
voice recorder had not yet been fully analyzed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
