<HEAD>Authorities Seek Identity Of Tot Found Among Homeless</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blond, blue-eyed baby Stephen smiled and
played with a stuffed bear as police and social workers tried to
figure out who he is and how he wound up among the city's homeless.
   The child, 8 to 10 months old, was found Friday in a van parked
near Civic Center. A woman living in the van said she had been
given the baby by another woman who had gotten him from still
another adult, police said Tuesday.
   The parents on Thursday asked a man identified only as Tom to
``care for Stephen for a few hours,'' said police Sgt. Holly Pera.
The couple never returned.
   Police held a news conference Tuesday appealing for help in
identifying the child.
   The Department of Social Services receives six to eight
abandoned baby cases a month, but most are infants left at a
hospital or brought in by relatives, said program Director Eurtha
Trammell.
   Social workers said the baby is healty, alert and well cared
for. He is being kept in a foster home.
