<HEAD>Town's 20th Suspicious Fire Since May</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JEFFERSON, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 20th suspicious fire in Jefferson
since May has damaged an unoccupied log cabin under construction,
police said today.
   The fires have unnerved the small White Mountains town of 900
people, and many families remain awake through the night and keep
firearms loaded.
   The latest fire, reported Tuesday night, extensively damaged the
inside of the 1{-story cabin 10 miles from the center of town,
police said.
   Before Tuesday, most recent fire was a blaze that damaged a home
Aug. 23.
   The rash of fires began in brush and fields but soon moved to
homes and barns. No one has been badly injured or killed, but
several families have been left homeless.
   Authorities have refused to divulge many details of their
investigation, but Jefferson's 32 volunteer firefighters and 12
other people have taken polygraph tests.
   Two fires deemed suspicious also have broken out in neighboring
Lancaster, one Aug. 11 in an abandoned farmhouse and one the next
day in a vacant downtown building.
</TEXT>
