<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--Legionnaire'sDisease     09-21 0150</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Legionnaire's Disease,0153</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Health Alert Out On Legionnaire's Disease: Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The county has issued a health alert to
doctors because of an outbreak of Legionnaire's disease that killed
seven people at a retirement home and the UCLA Medical Center, a
published report said today.
   The Department of Health Services asked doctors to watch for
serious pneumonia-like symptoms in patients who are elderly or
whose immune systems are not functioning properly, the Los Angeles
Times reported.
   The alert was issued July 29 and continues through this month.
   The notice was a routine precaution because no evidence points
to an ongoing problem, said Dr. Shirley Fannin, director of the
county's disease control program.
   Legionnaire's disease, similar to pneumonia or a debilitating
flu, is caused by the Legionella bacteria, so named because 29
infected people with the bacteria died after an American Legion
convention in Philadelphia in 1976.
</TEXT>
