<HEAD>Homeless Woman To Stand Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The girlfriend of Robert T'Souvas, the
homeless man and My Lai massacre veteran who was shot to death
earlier this month, faces a homicide charge in the killing.
   Allegheny County Deputy Coroner Arthur Gilkes ruled Tuesday that
there was sufficient evidence against Kathlynn T'Souvas, 36, in the
death of Robert T'Souvas. She was charged with criminal homicide.
   No trial date has been set.
   Robert T'Souvas, 39, was shot to death Sept. 3. He had served in
Vietnam and was among those charged in the 1968 massacre at the
village of My Lai. The charges later were dropped.
   Police Detective Robert McCabe said the homeless woman admitted
shooting T'Souvas in an argument over a bottle of vodka.
Pathologist Christoper Biwojno said Robert T'Souvas was ``acutely
intoxicated'' at the time of his death.
   Ms. T'Souvas, who took T'Souvas' name even though they were not
married, was drinking beneath the Smithfield Street Bridge with him
and another homeless man, David Bozic, 42, authorities said.
   The three entertained themselves by shooting rats and cans with
Bozic's .22-caliber handgun. At some point, Bozic went for food.
   T'Souvas was lying on his side with a bottle of vodka between
his legs, when Ms. T'Souvas ``picked up the gun and said she wanted
the vodka,'' McCabe said. ``He mumbled something and she shot him
in the right side of the face behind his ear.''
</TEXT>
