<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-88 1227EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Davis     09-21 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Davis,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Wisconsin Congressman Glenn Davis Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAUKESHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Rep. Glenn R. Davis, who served in
Congress for 20 years from Wisconsin, died today at his home in
Arlington, Va., his son said.
   State Sen. Mac Davis said his father, 73, had suffered from
leukemia for several years.
   Davis, a Republican, served in Congress from 1947 until 1957,
when he ran unsuccessfully for the seat vacated by the death of
Sen. Joseph R. McCarthy. Davis lost in the Republican primary to
Walter Kohler, who was defeated by Democrat William Proxmire.
   After practicing law in Waukesha for seveal years, Davis was
elected to Congress again in 1964 and served until his defeat by
Robert Kasten in the 1974 GOP primary.
   A native of Vernon, Davis graduated from the old Platteville
State Teachers College in 1934 and from the University of Wisconsin
Law School in Madison in 1940.
   He was elected to the state Assembly in 1940 but resigned before
the end of his first term to enter the U.S. Navy. He served in the
South Pacific.
   Survivors include his wife, Kathryn; his son; and four daughters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
