<HEAD>Death Toll Rises In Air Show Disaster</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAINZ, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death toll from the Ramstein air
show disaster increased to 67 today following the death of a
27-year-old West German man, a West German official said.
   Juergen Dietzen, a spokesman for Rhineland-Palatinate state,
said the man died in a Cologne hospital early today from severe
injuries suffered in the Aug. 28 jet crash.
   Dietzen said 84 people remained in hospitals throughout the
country and that 20 were listed in critical condition.
   The catastrophe occurred when three Italian stunt planes
collided while performing at an annual air show at the U.S. Air
Base at Ramstein.
   Authorities gave the following nationality breakdown of the
dead: 59 West Germans, three Americans, one Dutch citizen, one
French citizen and the three Italian pilots.
</TEXT>
