<HEAD>Reagan Tells Mulroney He's Happy Over Trade Bill's Passage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan telephoned Canadian Prime
Minister Brian Mulroney on Tuesday to express his pleasure at
Senate passage of the U.S.-Canadian free trade agreement, the White
House said today.
   Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Reagan placed the call about
5:20 p.m. EDT and talked with Mulroney for about 10 minutes.
   Fitzwater said the president described the pact as ``an historic
agreement and one of the major successes of his presidency.''
   He said Mulroney ``was optimistic'' about prospects for approval
in the Canadian Parliament.
   ``The agreement proves that trade barriers can be negotiated
away,'' the spokesman quoted Reagan as saying.
   He said Reagan added that he expects to receive the agreement
from the Senate in the next few days for his signature.
