<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bentsen 1stLd-Writethru a0466 09-21 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0466,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Promises to Bolster Rural Health Care</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 13 grafs new with Bentsen speech; picks up pvs 5th graf
bgng, Dukakis on Monday; deletes pvs grafs 8-9 bgng, Bentsen
``makes,'' to tighten.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Previous LUBBOCK</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HALE CENTER, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential nominee
Lloyd Bentsen today proposed a $100 million plan to bolster rural
health care, including federal subsidies to financially troubled
hospitals threatened with closure.
   Speaking in a high school auditorium in this West Texas town of
2,300 people, the Texas senator said rural hospitals are shutting
down and farmland residents are ``terrorized by the prospect of
illness.''
   ``Millions of Americans in rural areas are being denied one of
the basic necessities of life. They are losing their access to
quality health care,'' he said.
   ``It means that some children die who could have been saved. It
means illness lingers that could have been cured.''
   The day after Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis announced a
plan to require employers to provide health insurance coverage for
all workers, Bentsen outlined these proposals aimed directly at
rural health care:
   _A ``hardship fund'' to subsidize rural hospitals in danger of
being closed.
   _Expansion of the National Health Service Corps, which provides
scholarship assistance to medical, dental and nursing students who
agree to serve in rural areas.
   _Increased federal subsidies for nursing education.
   _Restoration of federal funds for migrant and community health
centers.
   Bentsen said the Reagan administration had slashed the last
three programs. His campaign staff estimated that all four programs
would cost $100 million.
   The senator said ``it's sure obvious we have a problem'' in
rural America under the Reagan administration, which he said ``has
done nothing to turn it around.''
   ``We have not seen a single proposal from them to stem the tide
of hospital closures in rural America,'' he said.
   Bentsen stressed health care today after touring depressed oil
areas of Texas and Oklahoma on Tuesday and stressing Dukakis'
promise to bolster the energy industry.
   Dukakis on Monday evening told oilmen in Houston that his
administration would get the wells pumping again, even if that took
government subsidies. And he announced that Bentsen would lead the
drafting of a national energy policy, including movement toward
further deregulation of natural gas.
   Bentsen followed up on Tuesday by going to Longview, Texas;
Oklahoma City; and Odessa, Texas, to deliver the message on a more
local and personal level, with rallies, a forum and interviews with
local news media.
   ``The Republicans like to ask: Are you better off today than you
were in 1980? They had better not ask that question in Oklahoma or
Texas, because the answer is no,'' he said at the Oklahoma rally,
making the first appearance in that state by either Democratic
candidate.
   And taking a page from the Republican strategists, the Bentsen
campaign did not schedule any wide-open news conferences Tuesday or
today, so as not to compete with the message Dukakis was trying to
convey.
   While trying to run what the Democrats say is a positive
campaign on the issues, Bentsen has been taking sharper shots at
Republican Dan Quayle, George Bush's running mate. In attacking
Quayle on Tuesday, Bentsen rhetorically scored the Reagan
administration's record on energy issues.
   ``I tell you, their record is as empty as Dan Quayle's resume,''
he said, getting his biggest applause from more than 1,000 people
at the rally in Oklahoma City.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
