<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea-Protests     09-21 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Protests,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Fight Police, Disgrace Olympic Flag</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Korea-Olympics, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of radical students threw
firebombs and rocks at police and scrawled slogans on a huge
Olympic flag in anti-government and anti-Olympic protests
Wednesday, police said.
   No one was arrested or injured in the protests in Seoul and
Suwon, 25 miles south of the capital, police officials said.
   About 300 students of Kyunghee University in Suwon fought police
and wrote slogans on an Olympic flag with the five-ring symbol, the
officials said.
   In downtown Seoul, about 100 students shouted anti-Olympic
slogans at a street demonstration and ran away when police rushed
in 10 minutes later, they said.
   The students in Suwon said the Olympics in Seoul will strengthen
authoritarian rule in South Korea and raise the risk of war with
North Korea, which is bocotting the Games.
   The slogans on the Olympic flag included ``Down with
dictatorship'' and ``Dictatorial Olympics,'' police said.
   Protesters did not break through the lines of troopers, the
officials said. The school is next to a soccer training camp used
by some Olympic teams, but it did not appear to be in use at the
time.
   ``Oppose the dictator's Olympics,'' the students shouted,
according to the officials.
   Police tried to hold off the protests by throwing back rocks and
did not fire tear gas, the officials said. Police are under orders
not to use tear gas during the Olympics, which opened Saturday and
will last until Oct. 2.
   Radical students are staging the protests to demand the Games be
shared with communist North Korea to help reunite the divided
Korean peninsula.
   Scattered anti-government and anti-Olympic demonstrations have
been reported in recent weeks, but they have little public support.
Most South Koreans want to make the Olympics a success and have
criticized the protests.
   North Korea is boycotting the Olympics because its demand to
co-host the Games was rejected. The International Olympic Committee
said the Games are awarded to a single city and cannot be shared.
</TEXT>
