<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-McCarthy     09-21 0169</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-McCarthy,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>William McCarthy, Head of Bookstore Chain, Was 61</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William J. McCarthy, a book merchant for 36 years
who became president and chief executive of the Kroch's &
Brentano's bookstore chain, has died. He was 61.
   McCarthy, who lived in Evanston, died Tuesday at the University
of Chicago's Bernard Mitchell Hospital.
   ``He truly loved every aspect of the book business: the
advertising, the distribution, the stock room,'' said his wife,
Virginia, a retired librarian. McCarthy was driving a taxicab in
1952, while completing work on a master's degree in English
literature, when he answered an advertisement for a salesman's job
at Kroch's.
   Over the years, he rose through the management ranks and, in
1986, became the bookstore chain's third president and chief
executive officer. He succeeded Adolph Kroch, who founded the store
in 1907, and Kroch's son, Carl.
   McCarthy is survived by his wife, a daughter and two sons.
   Funeral services are scheduled for 10 a.m. Thursday at St.
Athanasius Catholic Church in Evanston.
</TEXT>
