<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Attack     09-21 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Attack,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Red Army Faction Says It Attacked Top Government Official</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's most notorious terrorist
gang Wednesday claimed responsibility for a shotgun attack on one
of Chancellor Helmut Kohl's key advisers.
   A letter with the stamp of the leftist Red Army Faction said
West Germany's ``imperialistic economic policies'' prompted the
attack Tuesday, shortly before the first rounds of the World Bank
meeting in Berlin.
   A second letter, purportedly written by Italy's Red Brigades
terrorist group as well as by the German gang, urged a coordinated
``armed struggle in Western Europe.''
   The first letter said a ``commando squad'' of the Red Army
Faction attacked Hans Tietmeyer, a state secretary in the West
German Finance Ministry. Tietmeyer was not injured when his car was
fired on near his home in a Bonn suburb.
   ``The federal prosecutor cannot exclude that a kidnapping had
beek-International Monetary Fund
meeting in West Berlin, which begins with preliminary talks on
Thursday.
   The Red Army Faction did not make a direct link to the West
Berlin talks, but it did mention Tietmeyer's status as a delegate
of the World Bank as well as the International Monetary Fund.
   ``Our commando squad Khaled Aker attacked Hans Tietmeyer, state
secretary in the Finance Ministry,'' the two-page statement said.
The letter was mailed to a news agency and obtained by The
Associated Press.
   ``He (Tietmeyer) has a central role in the formulization,
coordination and carrying out of imperialistic economic policies.
In the last few years, there has been no important economic or
currency decisions in which he was not an important participant,''
it added.
   The statement said Tietmeyer was ``responsible for murder and
massive misery in the Third World'' because of his involvement in
international policies governing financial assistance for poor
nations.
   It was signed ``Commando Khaled Aker, Red Army Faction.''
   Roland Bachmeier, spokesman for the Interior Ministry, said
investigators were not familiar with the name ``Khaled Aker.''
   The Red Army Faction has used foreign terrorist names to
designate its own commando squads carrying out attacks in West
Germany.
   The federal prosecutor's office said investigators have
determined the pump-action shotgun used in the attack on Tietmeyer
was stolen by the Red Army Faction in a 1984 gunshop robbery.
   It said investigators were looking for a black Mercedes, another
unidentified car and a motorcycle that were seen in the area before
the shooting.
   Tietmeyer wrote an article for the Thursday editions of the West
German financial newspaper Handelsblatt, but he did not mention the
Tuesday attack.
   His article urged industrial nations to keep helping developing
countries reach higher standards of living.
   Security officials say the Red Army Faction has about 20 members
and several hundred sympathizers. It has been responsible for
arson, bombing and assassination attacks on government, industrial
and military targets since its formation in the early 1970s.
   The group claimed responsibility for the 1986 murder in Bonn of
West German diplomat Gerold von Braunmuehl.
</TEXT>
