<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-88 1519EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-IndianArt     09-21 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Indian Art,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northern Plains Indian Art Show Could Help Economy of Reservations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIOUX FALLS, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major show of little-known northern
Plains Indian art could give it international stature and help the
economy of Indian reservations, which are some of the poorest
regions in the nation, the show's director says.
   Northern Plains Indian artists are ``an untapped economic
resource,'' Shirley A. Bordeaux, project director for the three-day
Tribal Arts '88, which opens Friday.
   Bordeaux, who is from the Rosebud Sioux Indian Reservation, said
Tuesday the art show will attract several hundred serious art
buyers and collectors and about 100 Indian artists.
   ``We have a mission to help Indian people,'' she said.
   The show could lead to a stable market for the artists and will
help bring new money to the reservations, Bordeaux said.
   Artists will make important contacts at the show that will lead
to more sales and ``meaningful part-time employment for a segment
of the population,'' she said.
   On Friday, six judges will select 45 winners, including best of
show and the best works in the two major categories: tribal arts
and fine arts. Tribal arts includes beadwork, quilts, leather work,
metal work and dolls. Fine arts includes painting, pottery,
sculpture, graphics and photography.
   As original drawing by the late South Dakota Indian artist Oscar
Howe will be auctioned at the Friday night juried art show at Old
Courthouse Museum downtown. Tribal Arts '88 is dedicated to Howe's
memory.
   The show could lure 10,000 people to Sioux Falls, said Barry
LeBeau, one of the organizers.
   ``The establishment of a northern Plains Indian art market up
here in our own region is long overdue,'' he said. ``We have been
receiving nothing but praise and encouragement from the arts
world.''
   The show started with a federal grant from the Administration
for Native Americans.
   It has been advertised in publications worldwide. Bordeaux said
corporate and individual art buyers will attend.
   ``There is an interest in Indian art, and I think a particular
interest in northern Plains art,'' she said.
   Bordeaux said most of those invited to show their wares are
established artists from South Dakota, North Dakota, Montana,
Nebraska and western Minnesota, but some new artists are included,
she said.
   The organizers are helping artists handle art buyers. A workshop
for artists was held Wednesday in Sioux Falls, where experts
discussed marketing, pricing, copyrights and other techniques
``that will help them sell their work for a fair price,'' Bordeaux
said.
   On Sunday, the winner of the best of show will be awarded a
$1,000 prize, and the winners of the tribal arts and fine arts
categories each will win $500. Organizers say the prize money
should have special meaning for the winners.
   It was donated by Indian tribes, organizations, individuals and
businesses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
