<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JamesDean     09-21 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-James Dean,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>James Dean Festival Draws Thousands To Tiny Hometown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRMOUNT, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of James Dean fans are expected
in the actor's tiny hometown this weekend to mark his death, in
1955, with a film festival, look-alike contest and lasso
competition.
   The 13th annual festival also will include pilgrimages to Dean's
grave in Park Cemetery, said festival coordinator Ann Warr, who
runs the Fairmount Historical Museum, which is full of Dean
memorabilia.
   The film festival will feature Dean's ``Rebel Without a Cause,''
``East of Eden'' and ``Giant.''
   ``The lasso contest is designed after the same trick Dean
performed in `Giant,' '' Mrs. Warr said. ``He twirled a rope around
his hand with a rock attached to the end to see how many knots
could be tied in it.''
   Dean was born Feb. 8, 1931, in nearby Marion and spent his early
years in California. When his mother died of cancer, he returned to
Indiana and lived in Fairmount with his aunt and uncle, Ortense and
Marcus Winslow.
   Last year, more than 20,000 fans from all over the world
descended upon the town of 3,287 people during the festival weekend.
   ``We are expecting 25,000 to 28,000 people this weekend,'' said
Ron Spall, a spokesman for the Grant County Convention & Visitors
Bureau.
   Hotels, motels and campgrounds have been booked for months.
   ``When they check in, they make reservations for the next
year,'' said Jag Bohra, manager at Marion Inn.
   Marcus Winslow Jr., who was 11 when his first cousin died, said
Dean's popularity has resurged in the last 10 years.
   ``Maybe it's because of the resurgence of the '50s,'' he said.
``He hasn't aged any. The characters he played and his movies are
still popular. His movies fit in today.''
   After graduating from high school, Dean left Fairmount for
California, where he attended UCLA and started acting in
commercials and films.
   In 1952 he went to New York, where he was cast in a couple of
Broadway plays, including ``The Immoralist.'' Then director Elia
Kazan signed him to star in ``East of Eden.''
   Dean was killed soon after he completed ``Giant.'' It and
``Rebel Without a Cause'' were released after his death at age 24.
   Dean died Sept. 30, 1955, when his silver Porsche Spyder crashed
near Paso Robles, Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
