<DOCNO> AP880921-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-88 1633EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PersonalIncome     09-21 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Personal Income,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Personal Income Posts Sluggish Growth</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphics NY27,28</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans' personal income in August increased
only half as fast as inflation, the government said Wednesday,
providing analysts with more evidence that economic growth has
eased, at least temporarily.
   The Commerce Department said income grew a sluggish 0.2 percent
in the worst showing since a 0.4 percent decline in January. Income
was up a strong 0.7 percent in July and 0.6 percent in June.
   Meanwhile, personal consumption spending, which includes
everything except interest payments on debt, rose a moderate 0.5
percent following a 0.3 percent gain in July.
   The numbers are consistent with other recent government reports
showing that the economy slowed in August from its vigorous pace
during the first half of the year.
   The unemployment rate for the month jumped to 5.6 percent from
5.4 percent in July. Retail sales were off by 0.2 percent.
   ``The key question is was this just a little summer hiatus and
are we going to get back on track in the autumn or does it indicate
something more fundamental,'' said Robert G. Dederick, an economist
with Northern Trust Co. in Chicago.
   ``My own view is it is a hiatus,'' he said. ``I don't see any
reason why the economy decided to go into hibernation, although it
may have taken a little siesta, primarily because of the heat.''
   Analysts have blamed the summer heat for cutting into
back-to-school sales and, Richard Peach, an economist with the
Mortgage Bankers Association of America, said heavy use of air
conditioners strained utilities in some parts of the country.
   ``There were brownouts in the Northeast. It's not inconceivable
that because of the unavailability of power, employers had to work
half time or put people on temporary layoff,'' he said.
   As in June and July, personal income in August was held back by
declines in subsidy payments to farmers. The payments shrank $6.2
billion in August and $6.1 billion in July.
   However, farm income excluding subsidies fell $3.2 billion in
August, more than four times the July decline of $700 million.
Analysts blamed the slippage on the Farm Belt drought that
shriveled crops and parched pastures.
   Wages and salaries, a key component of personal income, were up
a modest 0.3 percent in August compared with a large 1.0 percent
gain in July.
   However, personal interest and dividend income both grew faster,
with interest income increasing 0.6 percent following a 0.5 percent
rise in July and dividend income up 1.2 percent after a 0.9 percent
gain a month earlier. The gains were a reflection of rising
interest rates and strong corporate earnings.
   Disposable, or after tax, income was up 0.2 percent in August
and 0.6 percent a month earlier.
   ``It was a month in which income growth was very moderate indeed
and did not keep up with inflation,'' Dederick said. A price index
tied to the personal income report rose 0.4 percent, double the
income gain.
   With spending rising slightly faster than income, the personal
savings rate _ savings as a percentage of after-tax personal income
_ edged down from 4.2 percent in July to 3.9 percent in August. The
savings rate this year has averaged 4.1 percent, up from 3.2
percent last year.
   The spending gain was strongest for services, up 0.7 percent
following a 0.6 percent rise in July. Purchases of non-durable
goods rose 0.2 percent following a 0.3 percent increase a month
earlier. Purchases of durable goods, ``big ticket'' items expected
to last three or more years, were unchanged after falling 0.6
percent in July.
   The changes left personal incomes at a seasonally adjusted rate
of $4.08 trillion and personal consumption spending at an annual
rate of $3.26 trillion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
