<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MooseAttack     09-21 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Moose Attack,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moose Turns Tables On Bowhunter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who shot a moose while bowhunting
in the Lake Clark National Preserve was gored and kicked after he
approached the animal he thought was dead, the National Park
Service said.
   Rangers said Donald Hewkin, 30, of Zion, was alone Friday when
he spotted a bull moose and hit it with three arrows.
   The moose fell, and Hewkin assumed it was dead and approached,
rangers said. As he reached the animal, it started to rise, rangers
said. Hewkin turned to flee and the moose gored him with one antler
tine in the left buttock, rangers said.
   The moose tossed Hewkin in the air and kicked him several times.
The moose then ran a short distance and dropped, rangers said.
   Hewkin was able to walk a mile to his hunting party's camp,
where his companions tried for 24 hours to alert passing aircraft.
   Saturday, two rangers on routine patrol by plane spotted the
party's red distress flag. Hewkin was flown to Port Alsworth, then
to Central Peninsula General Hospital in Soldotna, where he was
treated and released.
   Rangers said they could not find the wounded moose.
</TEXT>
