<1ST_LINE>u w BC-Economy-Glance     09-21 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Economy-Glance,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inflation Steady, Housing Starts, Income Down, Spending Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the economic reports released
Wednesday by the federal government:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>INFLATION:</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Higher costs for food, shelter and gasoline sent consumer prices
up 0.4 percent in August as the effects of the drought began to
ease. The increase, equivalent to an annual inflation rate of 5.2
percent, was the same as in July. Higher rents and gasoline prices
in large part replaced food as the sharpest spurs to higher prices,
the Labor Department said.
   Energy prices jumped 0.9 percent on a 3 percent boost in
gasoline prices, their sharpest gain in a year, and shelter costs,
reflecting higher rates for hotel and motel rooms, were up 0.6
percent, the steepest in seven months.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>HOUSING STARTS:</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing constructon fell 3.3 percent in August after increases
of 1.4 percent in July and 5.2 percent in June. Single-family homes
were built at an annual rate of 1.09 million, up 2.1 percent from
July, but that was offset by a 16.9 percent drop in apartment
construction to a 350,000-unit rate, its lowest level since the end
of the last recession in 1982.
   Overall, the Commerce Department said, housing starts were at an
annual rate of 1.44 million units last month, down 49,000 units
from July.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>PERSONAL INCOME:</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Reductions in farm subsidy payments held Americans' personal
income to a modest 0.2 percent gain in August, while spending rose
0.5 percent.
   The $7.2 billion rise in income to a seasonally adjusted annual
rate of $4.08 trillion followed gains of 0.7 percent in July and
0.6 percent in June.
   Wages and salaries were up 0.3 percent in August vs. 1 percent
in July. After tax income was up 0.2 percent in August and 0.6
percent in July. Farm subsidy payments shrank $6.2 billion in
August and $6.1 billion in July; income excluding subsidies fell
$3.2 billion and $700 million, respectively.
   Spending on everything except interest payments on debt rose 0.5
percent following a 0.3 percent gain in July and a 1.3 percent jump
in June.
</TEXT>
