<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-88 1733EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SoleSoothers     09-21 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sole Soothers,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Foot Ministry' Uplifts Souls by Soothing Soles of Homeless</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To the down-on-their-luck residents of
Orlando's homeless shelter, a ``foot ministry'' provides a welcome
relief by soothing their soles while uplifting their souls.
   Four women in an informal, non-religious group wash and massage
the feet of the poor and the tired.
   ``Feels good,'' Carol Strail, 33, said as she lifted her feet
from the basin of hot water and Epsom salts so Bette-Sue Hartwick
could examine them.
   Ms. Hartwick, an X-ray technician, held Ms. Strail's feet and
asked, ``Any blisters?''
   No, said Ms. Strail. Now that she has some soft-soled shoes, her
feet are better. She'd spent the day working in a greenhouse in
nearby Apopka, preparing rubber plants for shipment.
   Ms. Hartwick, wearing rubber gloves and kneeling on the tile
floor of the converted bus station, blotted the woman's feet with a
towel and then rubbed some skin lotion on them.
   ``It gives them a little bit of pampering,'' Ms. Hartwick said
Tuesday.
   The hot water revives and the cool lotion soothes. But more than
anything, the attention seems to restore _ if only briefly _ a
sense of dignity that comes from being pampered. Each of the 20
residents who signs up for the foot ministry also gets a pair of
new socks.
   The ministry, modeled on programs for the homeless in Atlanta
and Washington, was suggested by Sister Julie Sullivan, a Roman
Catholic nun and executive director of the Coalition for the
Homeless of Orlando, which runs the shelter.
   She found that foot care is one of the most overlooked health
problems of the homeless, who generally do not have good shoes and
who spend a great deal of time walking or in jobs that require
hours of standing.
   Ms. Hartwick and Roseanna Pratt, who work together at the Mayer
Family Care Center, helped organize the group recently with the
help of donations from their employer and their churches.
   So far, they have made two visits to the shelter, but hope to
make it a regular service.
   Ms. Pratt, a medical secretary, said she is pleased that people
are affected by such a simple act. Massaging feet will not get
people jobs or help them learn employable skills, she said, but it
might remind them that others care about their struggle.
   ``This is our country,'' she said. ``These are our own people.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
