<HEAD>GOP Chairman Says Dukakis Refused To Visit State Military Bases</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS pvs 7th (last) graf bgng, Standing on, to CORRECT,
identifying vessel as battleship instead aircraft carrier.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An aide to Michael Dukakis dismissed as
``deception and disinformation'' a claim by GOP National Chairman
Frank Fahrenkopf that the Democratic nominee refused repeated
invitations to visit military bases in Massachusetts as governor.
   ``Unfortunately for the governor, he cannot hide the fact that
in his 10 years as governor, he has refused, although invited many,
many times, to visit even one of the military installations of our
great nation in the state of Massachusetts,'' Fahrenkopf said
Tuesday while campaigning for Republican nominee George Bush.
   ``This is the latest round of Republican deception and
disinformation,'' said James Dorsey, the governor's press
secretary. ``Never let the facts get in the way of a good story,
(it's) the first rule of deceptive campaigning.''
   Dorsey said a quick check of his files showed that Dukakis
visited Fort Devens, an Army installation near Shirley, Mass., in
March 1986. He said Dukakis also visited the Camp Edwards military
reservation, which contains a National Guard installation, and Otis
Air Force Base on Cape Cod in September 1985 for a change of
command ceremony.
   He said there also are photographs at Dukakis' campaign
headquarters showing the governor visiting Fort Devens during his
first term in 1974-78.
   Fahrenkopf did not elaborate on the allegation in his disputed
statement. Press officials at Republican Party headquarters in
Washington, telephoned for comment, said they were unfamiliar with
the matter.
   Standing on the deck of the retired World War II battleship
Alabama at Mobile on Tuesday, Fahrenkopf said there will be
``severe cuts in defense spending'' and threatened cutbacks in Navy
plans for West and Gulf coast homeports if Dukakis is elected
president.
