<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SlaveAuction     09-21 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Slave Auction,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NAACP Protest Ends Fund-Raising Mock `Slave Auction'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEMPLE TERRACE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NAACP protests prompted a church
school to cancel its fund-raising ``slave auction,'' in which
students dressed as clowns would work one day for the students who
bought them.
   Mock auctions have been held for more than 15 years at the
750-student Temple Heights Christian School, owned by the First
Baptist Church of Temple Heights.
   But this year, a black student complained to the NAACP, and the
auction was canceled Tuesday.
   ``I felt hurt by the plan to hold the auction,'' said Charrise
Williams, 17, and one of three blacks in the 45-member senior
class. ``I felt that my feelings were not being considered.''
   The Tampa chapter of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People wrote to the school urging another
way be found to raise money.
   ``The concept of slavery is distasteful, offensive and
embarrassing, particularly to a race of people who were brutalized,
killed and treated as less than human beings,'' said Helen LaCount,
who heads the NAACP's legal redress committee.
   Ms. Williams said the auction was not her first encounter with
racist attitudes at the school. The teen-ager's mother, Teresa,
said her daughter had been called racially offensive terms as well
by some students.
   ``And when my daughter reacted to that stuff, they kept telling
her that she was too sensitive,'' said Mrs. Williams, a nurse who
moved from Washington, D.C., last November.
   ``I don't think they would hold a Holocaust scene and defend it;
I don't think they should hold a slave sale,'' she said, adding she
was unsure if she will keep her daughter in the school.
   ``After all, my daughter told the school she was against it.
They should have known that once you offend one student with
something like this, you have offended one too many,'' Mrs.
Williams said.
   Principal Randy Hurst said Wednesday that after the student
complained, school officials agreed to change the name and format
of next year's fund-raising event.
   ``We were going to go through with it this year because the kids
had already bought their clown outfits,'' he said. ``It seemed like
everything was fine, no one was upset.
   ``Then I got a call from the NAACP. There you have it,'' he
said. ``We've been doing this for so many years, it never had any
racial overtones, just a fun day for the students.''
   Hurst said he has permanently canceled the auctions. They
traditionally raised $1,000 to $1,500, and were never meant to
demean blacks, he said.
   In the auction, students in clown outfits stand on a block and
are auctioned. The purchased ``slave'' spends the next day with the
``master'' doing minor chores like carrying books and perfoming
ridiculous stunts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
