<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-88 1853EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-YomKippur     09-21 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yom Kippur,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brooklyn Youth Says He's Sorry for Burning Synagogue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Jews atoned for their sins Wednesday on Yom
Kippur, the most solemn of Jewish holy days, a 12-year-old boy
accused of setting fire to a synagogue said he, too, was sorry for
what he had done.
   The boy, identified as Joey, said he was just out to have fun
when he and a 15-year-old companion allegedly desecrated
Congregation Sharai Torah in Brooklyn last Saturday morning.
   The two face charges in family court that they spray-painted
swastikas in the Orthodox synagogue and set fire to six Torahs _
the handwritten scrolls of the first five books of the Old
Testament.
   The congregation observed Yom Kippur _ the Day of Atonement _ at
a nearby Jewish school, using a Torah donated by an Ohio synagogue.
``We believe that everything, including this fire, is from God,''
said the president of the congregation, Hirsch Wolf.
   Joey said in an interview with New York Newsday that he hadn't
known what a synagogue was and did not vandalize it out of
anti-Semitic feelings. If he had the opportunity, he said, he would
tell members of the congregation, ``I'm really sorry.''
   ``These kids didn't know what they were doing,'' said Joey's
mother, Anna Cadet Santiago. ``My son has a lot of remorse. He's
scared.''
   But Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward said that the damage in
the synagogue looked like more than vandalism.
   ``They deliberately took the Torah and put it down on the floor
and stepped on it,'' he said.
   The crime, occurring on the Sabbath before Yom Kippur, shocked
Brooklyn's huge Jewish community. An estimated 10,000 people turned
out Sunday for a memorial service for the burned Torahs.
   Among those sending messages of condolence to the synagogue was
Roman Catholic Cardinal John O'Connor, who called the arson attack
``a heinous crime.''
   The president of the Rabbinical Council of America, Rabbi Max N.
Schreier, issued a statement Wednesday calling it an ``act of
ruthless vandalism the likes of which have not been seen since the
Holocaust.''
   Joey told the newspaper the 15-year-old, Louie, came to him
Friday night. ``He said, `You want to have fun?' I said, `Sure.' I
thought we were going to run around and make noise. He didn't say
nothing about the fire.''
   Inside the synagogue, the boys knocked over books and discovered
some liquor, Joey said.
   ``He had a can of spray paint,'' Joey said of Louie. ``He was
drawing swastikas all over. He started pouring liquor on ... the
cabinet,'' referring to the wooden ark where the synagogue's Torahs
were stored.
   Joey said Louie removed one of the scrolls, unrolled it on the
floor, and then lit a box of matches and threw it into the ark. The
boys panicked and ran, he said.
   ``I knew I was in trouble,'' Joey said. ``I knew I did something
wrong.''
</TEXT>
