<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     09-21 0930</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0972</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tammy Wynette, country music's heroine
of heartbreak, was fighting in court to regain control of her home,
which was seized by U.S. marshals to pay for a $900,000 judgment
against her.
   She filed an emergency bankruptcy petition Tuesday and a motion
Wednesday seeking to regain possession of the home, attorney Steve
Lefkovitz said.
   He said Miss Wynette and her husband, George Richey, filed a
Chapter 11 petition on behalf of themselves and Tammy Wynette
Enterprises.
   Miss Wynette, best known for her hits ``Stand By Your Man'' and
``D-I-V-O-R-C-E,'' was performing Wednesday on the West Coast and
her husband was with her, the attorney said. Richey, whose real
name is George Richardson, planned to fly back to Nashville to deal
with the matter, Lefkovitz said.
   ``She's a very fine woman and it's unfortunate all this had to
happen,'' he said.
   Miss Wynette, 46, had no comment, said Kent Arwood, a spokesman.
   Lefkovitz said the bankruptcy petition was filed after the
Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp. took steps to seize the
couple's personal assets to satisfy the $900,000 court judgment.
   Lefkovitz said he asked bankruptcy court Wednesday for an
expedited hearing on his request to turn the assets back to the
singer and her husband.
   Another attorney for the couple, Ralph Gordon, said the two had
some investments in Florida that were financed by Sunrise Savings &
Loan of Boynton Beach, Fla., which failed.
   As a result of the failure, the FSLIC won a $900,000 judgment
against the couple. A court order Monday allowed U.S. marshals to
enter the home to enforce the judgment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor-singer Gary Morris is recording an
operatic version of ``Les Miserables'' on the heels of performing
the lead of Jean Valjean in the musical.
   Morris performed the role on Broadway from November 1987 through
May.
   ``I've always sought projects that allow me to test new ground
and stretch my voice,'' Morris said. ``Working on this, my first
operatic recording, has been very challenging and rewarding.''
   His country hits include ``Wind Beneath My Wings.'' He also has
sung in a pop version of the opera ``La Boheme'' in New York with
Linda Ronstadt, and had a recurring role on the television show
``The Colbys.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former world figure skating champion
Dorothy Hamill-Forsythe glided into a new role this week: mother.
   Hamill-Forsythe, an Olympic gold medalist in 1976, gave birth to
a daughter Monday night at Desert Hospital, spokesman Randy
Bevilacque said.
   She and her 6-pound, 14-ounce baby, named Alexandra, went home
Tuesday. ``Mother and baby are both doing fine,'' said Bevilacque.
   The former skating star is married to Dr. Kenneth Forsythe.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Queen Elizabeth II will make her first visit to
Spain this year, as the two countries mark the 400 years since the
defeat of the Spanish Armada.
   The British monarch and her husband, Prince Philip, will make a
state visit to Spain next month at the invitation of King Juan
Carlos and Queen Sofia, Buckingham Palace said Wednesday.
   After the Oct. 17-21 visit, the British and Spanish royal
couples will spend a private weekend in the Spanish island resort
of Majorca.
   English ships defeated the Armada, a fleet of more than 100
ships sent by Spain in an ill-fated attempt to invade England, in
the summer of 1588.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Don Johnson says he likes his new role in the
film ``Sweet Hearts Dance'' because it's so unlike what fans of his
``Miami Vice'' role would expect.
   ``Mostly I was offered body count pictures. That is, if by page
seven I hadn't slain 15 people it wasn't a Don Johnson movie,''
Johnson said.
   When he was sent the screenplay of ``Sweet Hearts Dance,''
Johnson said, ``I read it, then reread it because I was shocked
that it was so good.''
   ``I hadn't seen that kind of relationship between men in films
for a long time,'' he said.
   Directed by Robert Greenwald, the film traces the life of a
carpenter in a small New England town who gets more satisfaction
out of climbing gymnasium ropes with his high school buddy, played
by Jeff Daniels, than by going home to his wife, played by Susan
Sarandon.
   Johnson's reputation for being difficult and demanding didn't
stop Greenwald from going after him. ``He is as emotional and moody
and funny and smart as Wiley Boon is,'' Greenwald said, referring
to the character he playes in the movie.
   ``I will never, as long as I live, say that he's easy. But he is
good,'' the director added.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country singer Steve Earle has been fined $500 and
given a year's probation after he pleaded no contest to a reduced
charge of resisting arrest.
   Earle, 33, had been charged with assaulting a Dallas Police
officer after a New Year's Eve peformance.
   The plea came Tuesday while a jury was being selected for his
trial on a felony assault charge. The reduced charge of resisting
arrest was a misdemeanor.
   Authorities alleged that Earle scratched officer L.R. Allen with
his fingernails and hit him with his knee during a scuffle outside
Dallas Alley, a Dallas night spot.
   Earle, who could have faced up to 10 years in prison if he had
been convicted on the original charge, said that his plea was not
an admission of guilt and maintained that the officer attacked him.
   Earle is known for his album ``Guitar Town'' and his style of
combining country with rock and blues.
