<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Anti-NukePetition     09-21 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Anti-Nuke Petition,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pro-Nuclear Power Group Raises $5.5 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Activists opposed to a November ballot question
that could force the closing of Massachusetts' two commercial
nuclear power plants have raised more than $5.5 million to defeat
the referendum, according to disclosure statements.
   Sponsors of the referendum, Citizens for Safe Energy, have
raised $280,184, according to the disclosure forms.
   ``Getting rid of the emotion on this issue is really tough,''
said Robert Palmer, spokesman for the Massachusetts Citizens
Against the Shutdown organization, also known as the Vote No on 4
Committee.
   ``Money does not buy the vote, but money produces information,''
Palmer said Tuesday. ``This is what needs to be done to get the
message across.''
   Palmer said the money would be spent primarily for radio and
television advertising. He also said the money being donated by
utilities comes out of earnings and has no effect on electric rates.
   Leading contributors to the committee have been Boston Edison
Co. with $1.4 million, the Yankee Atomic Electric Co. with $1.7
million and Montaup Electric with $450,759, according to disclosure
reports filed with the Office of Campaign and Political Finance.
   But the committee claims more than 45,000 citizens have joined
its cause, including more than 100 academic, civic, business and
labor leaders, some of whom oppose nuclear power generally but also
oppose the potential sweeping impact of the ballot proposal.
   Question 4 on the Nov. 8 ballot would ban the operation of any
power plant that generated nuclear waste, effectively shutting down
the state's two nuclear power plants _ Pilgrim Station in Plymouth
and Yankee-Rowe in western Massachusetts. A similar referendum
question was defeated by voters last year in Maine.
   According to the financial disclosure, nearly $1.8 million of
the Vote No funds have been spent for telephone polling and direct
mail. A Los Angeles media consulting firm will design the
committee's media strategy.
</TEXT>
