<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LowellSlayings     09-21 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lowell Slayings,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Investigating Two Unusual Killings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOWELL, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The slayings of a homeless man who was
stabbed 14 times and disemboweled and of another man who was
covered with silver paint have stunned this community that had had
only two previous killings this year.
   Three teen-agers are being held in the death of the 73-year-old
homeless man, police said Wednesday. He was beaten, stabbed and
left bleeding in an alley Sunday night while the youths discussed
how to finish the job.
   The body of the man covered with silver paint was found in a
field Tuesday night. He apparently was beaten with a paint can
found nearby, said Lowell Police Capt. Tom Cullen.
   ``It was an unusual situation. People thought it was all over.
Less than 48 hours later, we had another,'' Cullen siad.
   The homeless man, Louis Pozyck, had lived in Lowell for 10 years
and was often seen pushing a shopping cart looking for cans, which
he collected for money, Cullen said. He was awarded the Bronze Star
during World War II.
   ``He was kind of a character. He hung around Lowell, was
harmless, had a lot of friends. Turns out he's a decorated war
hero. We didn't know that until he was killed,'' he said.
   Sunday night Pozcyk was sleeping in an alley when a youth
confronted him, Cullen said.
   ``It appears he was woken up by one of them and told to take
off. He was kicked in the face and stabbed by one person who left
the scene.''
   The assailant met two friends and the three returned to the
alley and Pozyck was again stabbed, he said.
   ``Then they went to a shopping center. They decided they better
go back and make sure he was dead, (they discussed) maybe they
should burn him.''
   The youths returned to the alley a third time and one of them
disemboweled the man, Cullen said. Neighbors who heard the man's
screams called police.
   Brian Gobis, 18, and Michael Morrisette, 17, both of Lowell were
charged with murder Monday and were being held without bail, Cullen
said. A hearing has been set to determine if the 16-year-old
suspect can be tried as an adult, said a spokesman for the
Middlesex County District Attorney's office.
   In the second murder, the man, whose name was being withheld,
was found in a field a few hours after he had gone to buy paint.
   ``At first it looked like a ritual-type killing, but then as we
tried to reconstruct it, it appeared that the paint can was the
weapon,'' Cullen said.
   No arrests have been made in that case.
   Lowell, with a population of about 100,000, is 25 miles
northwest of Boston. Police Sgt. Patrick Burns said Wednesday
afternoon that to his knowledge the city had had only four murders
so far this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
