<DOCNO> AP880921-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-88 1533EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Economy Bjt   09-21 0922</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy, Bjt,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inflations Stays At 5.2 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Higher food, shelter and gasoline prices
maintained an annual inflation pace of 5.2 percent in August as the
effects of the drought on consumers began to ease, the government
said Wednesday.
   Food and beverage prices rose 0.5 percent for the month,
compared with 0.9 percent in July when the Labor Department said
the greatest impact of the dry weather in the Farm Belt began
reaching consumer pocketbooks.
   But gasoline prices jumped a whopping 3 percent in August, the
biggest increase in 12 months. Analysts noted that the normal
summer vacation season price spikes for gasoline are usually over
by August, but that there were shortages of unleaded grades in many
markets this year.
   Despite lower utility bills and home energy costs, shelter
expenses also were up 0.6 percent in August, their largest increase
in seven months, the Labor Department said.
   ``Increases in the food, shelter and energy components accounted
for over four-fifths of the August advance in the consumer price
index,'' the government said.
   When combined with large price declines for clothing and natural
gas, the overall August price increases were the same as the 0.4
percent in July.
   The calculated annualized rate also was the same for both months
_ 5.2 percent _ in contrast to a 4.4 percent inflation rate in 1987
and the first six months of this year, Labor Department economists
said..
   ``We have a gradual worsening of underlying inflation, but it is
gradual ... sneaking in, sort of like dust through a window,'' said
Robert G. Dederick, an economist at Northern Trust Co. in Chicago.
``One month is up, one month is down, but pretty soon you have
higher inflation.''
   But private analysts agreed with a White House assessment that
there was nothing alarming or dramatic in the numbers.
   ``The scare that we're off to the races or that an inflationary
sprial is under way has not materialized and it won't
materialize,'' said Larry Chimerine of the WEFA Group, a Bala
Cynwyd, Pa., consulting firm.
   ``There is a gradual acceleration of inflation heavily
concentrated in material prices and prices of imported goods,''
Chimerine said. ``But at this point it is not spreading throughout
the economy.''
   A separate report by the Commerce Department showed personal
income rising a modest 0.2 percent in August, the smallest gain in
eight months, although much of it represented declines in both farm
subsidies and farm income. Wages and salaries were up just 0.3
percent.
   After adjustments for inflation, the Labor Department said
Americans' average weekly earnings fell a percipitous 1.3 percent
in August. The decline in workers' buying power was the third in
the past four months and the worst ever on record since the
government began keeping tabs on real earnings in 1964.
   The decrease stemmed from a 0.9 percent drop in the average
number of hours worked, from 34.9 hours to 34.6 hours, and the 0.4
percent hike in consumer prices. Average hourly earnings were
$9.24, unchanged from July.
   Another Commerce Department report showed housing construction
falling 3.3 percent last month, with a steep drop in new
apartments. For the first eighth months of this year, housing
starts are running 9.9 percent below the same period in 1987.
   Analysts said apartment construction has never recovered from
the blow suffered from the elimination of tax shelters in a law
taking effect in January 1987.
   The easing of food price increases had been anticipated by most
analysts. Grocery prices alone were up 0.8 percent last month, but
that compared with a jump of 1.4 percent in July, the biggest
increase in 4{ years.
   ``About 90 percent of the August advance was due to price
increases for items that were adversely affected by the drought _
fruits and vegetables, cereal and bakery products, poultry and
eggs,'' the government said.
   Fruit and vegetable prices rose 1.3 percent atop a 2.9 percent
gain in July. They have jumped a total of 10.6 percent over the
last year. Cereal and bakery product prices were up 1.6 percent,
the largest monthly increase since January 1981, reflecting higher
prices for wheat, oats and eggs, the government said.
   Excluding food, there were wide price swings in both directions.
   The 3 percent increase in gasoline prices, for example, was
partially offset price declines of 1.2 percent for natural gas, 0.8
percent for home heating oil and 0.2 percent for electricity.
   Apparel prices fell another 1.6 percent after smaller declines
in June and July, reflecting what the government said were
unusually large end-of-season discounts for women's clothing.
   But auto financing charges and used car prices jumped 1.5
percent in the month and auto insurance rates climbed another 0.8
percent.
   ``If there is any surprise, it's in the number of large price
changes,'' said Donald Ratajczak, director of economic forecasting
at Georgia State University. ``It indicates that sellers are having
a hard time determining what is an acceptable price in the
marketplace.''
   Ratajczak said preliminary data from his own surveys suggest the
same thing occuring this month.
   ``The big declines in clothing and natural gas prices are
over,'' he said. ``Next month the fall fashions come in, so
clothing should be up sharply. And school tuitions will come in
even bigger.
   ``But the effect of the drought pretty much should have run its
course by then and we shouldn't have another large increase in food
prices,'' Ratajczak said. ``And gasoline prices shouldn't be up.
We'll have a couple of good things and not-so-good things.''
</TEXT>
