<HEAD>Campaign Jetliner Has Problem With Indicator Light</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The landing gear indicator light on
Democratic vice presidential nominee Lloyd Bentsen's campaign jet
failed in an approach to Sacramento on Wednesday, forcing the pilot
to swoop low for a visual inspection before landing.
   The flight from Lubbock jet landed successfully with no
injuries, as five fire trucks stood by in case of an emergency. In
addition to the visual inspection of the landing gear by the
control tower, a member of the flight crew peeled back the rug of
the Boeing 737 jetliner and checked the gear through a peephole in
the floor.
   The pilot of the America West Airlines charter, Bentsen's
regular campaign jet, said the indicator for the right landing gear
had not shown at the control panel. The visual inspection enabled
the pilot and control tower to determine that the gear had lowered.
