<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official News Agency Says 10 Killed In Rocket Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghanistan's official news agency
said Wednesday that 10 people were killed and eight wounded when
rebels rocketed the capital the day before.
   It contrasted with a Tuesday night report on official Radio
Kabul that indicated 62 people died in the attack.
   The communist Bakhtar news agency said the 10 deaths occurred
when six rockets landed in separate parts of the city late Tuesday
afternoon.
   Radio Kabul, monitored in Islamabad, said in its Pashto-language
broadcast Tuesday night that since the April 14 signing of the
Geneva accord providing for a Soviet troop withdrawal, ``Kabul and
its suburbs were hit by criminals' rockets 15 times, and the 16th
rocket attack took place tonight.
   ``As a result of the attack, 62 innocent people, including women
and children, were killed and 104 were wounded,'' it said.
   But the radio earlier reported the 10 dead, and it appeared the
announcer meant to say there had been a total 62 dead from all 16
attacks.
   Western diplomatic sources have reported the number of guerrilla
rocketings and casualties to be much higher.
   Weekly accounts relayed from Western embassies in Kabul report
incoming rockets almost every day.
   Moslem insurgents fired dozens of rockets into Kabul airport on
Sept. 1 and 5, blowing up a massive ammunition dump and destroying
at least five aircraft. Moscow's Tass news agency put casualties at
nine dead but Western and guerrilla sources said they believed it
was more like 50 or more.
   The guerrillas have been fighting the Marxist government since
the communists seized power in a 1978 military coup.
   Under the Geneva agreement, all of an estimated 100,000 Red Army
troops are to leave Afghanistan by Feb. 15.
</TEXT>
