<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     09-21 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALONA, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If one picture is worth a thousand words,
then how much is one word worth? Math teacher Richard Oyer wants
his seventh- and eighth-grade students to find one that's worth $1
million.
   Oyer, a teacher at Mid-Prairie Junior High School, assigned each
letter of the alphabet a value _ A equals $1, B equals $2, and so
on to Z, which is worth $26 _ and challenged his students to find a
word tha, when the letters' numerical value is multiplied, equals
$1 million.
   For example, the word ``cab'' would be $6: C ($3) times A ($1)
times B ($2).
   The reward for finding a winning word is best expressed with a
letter not a numeral.
   ``The first student that brings it in gets an `A' on the
assignment,'' Oyer said.
   Proper names are not allowed. The word has to be in the
dictionary.
   Oyer said he knows of at least two words worth a million,
although students have yet to find one. So far, the closest is
village, at $997,920, located by Heidi Troyer, an eighth-grader.
   Oyer said he cannot take credit for designing the competition.
``It's not original with me. It came from The Arithmetic Teacher,
put out by the National Council of the Teachers of Math,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opponents of Montana's ``bottle bill''
are looking for a fast talker.
   State law says any political action committee must include its
name in recorded or printed advertisements.
   The opponents of Initiative 113 are officially known as the
Committee Against Forced Deposits: Montana Grocers, Recyclers, Soft
Drink Bottlers, Beer Distributors, Container Manufacturers and
their National Affiliates, and other Montana Businesses and
Concerned Citizens.
   It takes about 14 seconds for most people to read the group's
name slowly, Capps said, and the committee needs to cram that into
its radio and TV spots.
   The name _ CAFDMGRSDBBDCMNAMBCC for short _ was adopted to
ostentatiously satisfy a requirement enforced by the state
Commissioner of Political Practices that committee names accurately
reflect the opponents' interests. Bottle bill backers had gotten
the commissioner to throw out two simpler names the committee
adopted.
   ``If we're going to have to make a mockery about what we're
doing, it's best to bring it out in the open,'' committee treasurer
Frank Capps said Monday.
   The ballot initiative would require 5-cent deposits on bottles
and cans containing carbonated beverages.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PLACERVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new El Dorado County jail would
be ready to open except for one problem: the cell doors won't lock.
   Faulty electronics have affected the high technology locks,
along with television monitors and a communication system, Jail
Commander Ed Newman said recently.
   ``These are very dramatic problems,'' said Newman, adding that
13 flawed electronic panels are ``literally the hands and feet of
the officers.'' The panels have been shipped to a Maryland
electronics company to be reworked and won't be back for three
weeks.
   The jail's design relies on a central control post from which
guards can electronically open and close cell doors, communicate
with inmates and operate lights.
   To compensate the county for the delays, General Services
Director Joe Winslow said the jail's contractor, F&H Construction,
is paying a daily penalty of $1,250 that started Sept. 6.
</TEXT>
