<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-88 1922EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HousingStarts     09-21 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Housing Starts,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Apartment Construction Down Sharply, Single-Family Home Building
Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY23</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Apartment construction in August sunk to the
lowest level in more than six years, outweighing a small gain in
single-family home building, the government said Wednesday.
   The Commerce Department said housing construction fell 3.3
percent last month to an annual level of 1.44 million units. A 16.9
percent plunge in the volatile apartment category to 350,000 units
more than offset a 2.1 percent gain in single-family homes to 1.09
million units.
   The single-family home category has fluctuated in a fairly
narrow range this year at an annual rate of around 1.1 million
units. However, the apartment sector has approached a rate of
500,000 units in some months and now rests at its lowest point
since June 1982, when the last recession was ending.
   ``The single-family level is pretty good. It's been an
incredibly stable element of the market, but the multi-unit number
is staggering,'' said David Seiders, chief economist of the
National Association of Home Builders.
   Analysts have been expecting housing activity to taper off
because the Federal Reserve Board has been pushing up interest
rates since late March in an effort to curb inflation.
   But, Seiders said home buyers appear to be turning to adjustable
rate mortgages, which cost less than fixed-rate mortgages but whose
rates can change.
   Also, fixed-rate mortgages have not risen as fast as many
economists were expecting. According to the Federal Home Loan
Mortgage Corp., fixed-rate mortgages, not including add-on fees
known as points, hit a high of 10.71 percent in mid-August but have
since eased, dropping to 10.4 percent last week.
   The overall decline in August housing starts followed gains of
1.4 percent in July and 5.2 percent in June.
   For the first eight months of 1988, housing starts have been
running 9.9 percent below the level of activity during the same
period in 1987. Single-family construction is lagging by 6.7
percent while apartment construction trails by 17.6 percent.
   Mark Obrinsky, an economist with the U.S. League of Savings
Institutions, said apartment construction was dealt a heavy blow
when the tax law that took effect in January 1987 reduced the
profitability of real estate investments. Also, vacancy rates are
high.
   The vacancy rate for rental housing was 7.7 percent in the
April-June period this year, compared with rates between 5 percent
and 6 percent through the 1960s and 1970s, he said.
   Building permits, a good barometer of future housing activity,
were up 1.9 percent last month to 1.45 million units a year, after
falling 4.9 percent in July.
   By region, housing starts fell 20.7 percent in the Northeast to
207,000 units and 17.2 percent in the Midwest to 240,000.
   Starts were up 14.3 percent in the West to 424,000 units and up
0.4 percent in the South to 565,000.
   ``The Northeast is taking a beating now,'' said Michael
Sumichrast, a private housing economist in Washington. ``The New
York sales market is practically dead. It's still suffering from
the financial market collapse'' and layoffs in the securities
industry.
</TEXT>
