<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WilliamsParole     09-21 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Williams Parole,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyer Says Panel Recommends Parole Next Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Teamsters President Roy L.
Williams could be paroled from federal prison as soon as Tuesday
under the recommendation of a U.S. Parole Commission panel, his
lawyer said Wednesday.
   F. Russell Millin said the commission is to act on the
recommendation of the parole examiners by Friday, a deadline
imposed by a federal judge, Millin said. The commission is not
bound by the recommendation, but a spokesman told The Kansas City
Star such recommendations are followed 90 percent of the time.
   Joseph Korbinsky, a commission spokesman in Washington, refused
to disclose the examiners' recommendation after the hearing in
Springfield.
   Williams was convicted in 1982 of conspiring to bribe former
U.S. Sen. Howard Cannon of Nevada to influence trucking
deregulation. Williams, a longtime Kansas City area labor leader,
was forced to resign the union presidency, which he had held for
about a year, following his conviction.
   The commission's guidelines called for his release after 24 to
36 months of the 10-year sentence he began serving in December 1985.
   But the commission set Williams' parole date in 1990 after his
links to organized crime were established by testimony he gave in
another case. Earlier this month, the commission set a new date of
Jan. 13, 1989, saying it was a reward for Williams' cooperation and
in consideration of his health. Williams, 73, suffers from
emphysema and an enlarged heart.
   U.S. District Judge William R. Collinson reviewed Williams'
petition for release and ruled last month that the parole
commission was unconstitutionally punishing him for admissions the
government forced him to make about his links to reputed mob
leaders. He said he would order Williams' release Friday if the
board did not reconsider his parole.
   Bruce C. Houdek, a second Kansas City lawyer representing
Williams, said the examiners said their recommendation would
include a condition that Williams ``would continue to cooperate
with the authorities.''
   Houdek said Williams told examiners Tuesday that ``he was sick
and wanted to go home to his farm in Leeton.''
</TEXT>
