<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Greece     09-21 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Greece,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspended Military Base Talks to Restart, Minister Meeting Dukakis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiations on U.S. use of Greek military
bases will resume in Athens early next month, Greek Foreign
Minister Karolos Papoulias announced Wednesday after meeting with
Secretary of State George Shultz.
   But there has been no change on the deadlocked issue that
prompted a U.S. break off of the talks Sept. 5 _ Greece's demand
for U.S. forces to vacate Hellenikon air base at Athens
International Airport, Papoulias told reporters.
   Besides Hellenikon, the five-year U.S.-Greece bases agreement
expiring this year covers the Nea Makri U.S. communications base
near Athens, a naval and an air base on the island of Crete and 20
smaller installations.
   Hellenikon is an issue on which the Greek and American sides
``have taken different opinions.... However, the outcome of the
negotiations cannot be judged at this point; they can only be
judged when the negotiations are completed,'' Papoulias said.
   The foreign minister, who described his State Department talks
as constructive, said negotiations would resume the first week of
October.
   Departing from wide-ranging discussions and lunch with Shultz
and other senior U.S. officials at the State Department, Papoulias
said he was flying to Boston on Wednesday afternoon to meet
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, the Democratic presidential
nominee whose parents were born in Greece.
   The election campaign has stirred intense interest in Greece,
``well-justified because Dukakis is the son of Greek immigrants to
America,'' Papoulias said.
   The foreign minister sought meetings with both Dukakis and his
Republican rival, Vice President George Bush, said Achilles
Paparsenos, the Greek Embassy press attache. A Bush meeting has not
yet been fixed for Papoulias, who plans to attend the U.N. General
Assembly next week in New York, the attache said.
   After seeing Dukakis, the Greek foreign minister plans to return
to Washington for meetings Thursday with several members of
Congress and with Commerce Secretary William Verity and U.S. Trade
Representative Clayton Yeutter in his dual capacity as the current
ministerial chief of the European Economic Community, Paparsenos
said.
   Those attending the lunch Wednesday with Papoulias included
Ambassador Alan H. Flanigan, the chief U.S. negotiator, who
suspended the Athens talks earlier this month to return to
Washington for instructions on the surprise Greek demand to quit
Hellenikon.
   Papoulias also met with Assistant Secretary of State Rozanne
Ridgway, who on Tuesday described Hellenikon as a central issue in
the negotiations. The United States has a contingency plan for
quitting Hellenikon if there is no agreement, but has not started
any preparations to leave, she told a congressional hearing.
   The U.S. bases issue does not affect the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization because the agreement under renegotiation is a
bilateral matter not covering use of the installations by NATO,
Papoulias said.
   Urban development and congestion around Athens airport are major
reasons Greece wants U.S. forces to quit Hellenikon, Paparsenos
said.
   Shultz briefed Papoulias on the U.S.-Soviet dialogue and the two
discussed U.S.-Common market trade relations, the Middle East,
southern African and East-West issues, the foreign minister said.

</TEXT>
