<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Homeless-Housing     09-21 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless-Housing,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Won't Block Sales of Foreclosed Federal Property</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. District Judge Oliver Gasch refused
Wednesday to bar the Department of Housing and Urban Development
from selling single-family homes it had acquired through mortgage
foreclosures to the highest bidder.
   Gasch issued an order denying a preliminary injunction requested
by a coalition of advocates for the homeless but said the reasons
for his ruling would be made public later.
   Two temporary restraining orders, issued last month, prevented
HUD from selling houses in Michigan and Washington, D.C. and its
suburbs.
   HUD general counsel J. Michael Dorsey, commenting on the
decision, said through the press office that the department's
inventory of 47,000 foreclosed houses would go on sale Thursday
morning through its field offices.
   ``HUD will continue to make certain single-family acquired
properties available to homeless providers through lease and
discount sales programs,'' he said.
   The coalition, represented by the National Housing Law Project,
had argued that HUD had violated the law by selling its stock of
foreclosed single-family homes to the highest bidder without
determining whether they could be beneficial to the homeless and
low-income people.
   Gasch was told by the coalition last Friday that HUD receives
70,000 houses each year - about 7,000 a month - but the agency
``cannot proceed as if it is simply in the real estate business.
They must consider the homeless,'' said attorney William Bradford.
   ``We are disappointed that he did not grant the preliminary
injunction,'' Bradford said of Wednesday's order. However, he
declined further comment until a written opinion is issued by Gasch.
   HUD has said that it generally sells the homes to the highest
bidders -frequently investors - but insists that it has several
programs designed to help homeless people find places to live.
   Recently, HUD has been selling an average of 7,100 properties
each month -houses that had Federal Housing Administration mortgage
insurance and that went into foreclosure when their owners could no
longer keep up the mortgage payments. The program has produced some
$2.4 billion in proceeds since Oct. 1, the start of the current
fiscal year.
   HUD officials had argued that the temporary restraining orders,
if upheld, could cost the agency $3 billion a year and bankrupt its
single-family mortgage insurance fund.
</TEXT>
