<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BrawleyRelocation 1stLd-Writethru a0633 09-21 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brawley Relocation, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0633,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sharpton Confirms Brawleys Living In Virginia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with Sharpton confirming move.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 30-day jail sentence will ``continue to hang
over'' Glenda Brawley even though she and her family have moved to
Virginia after months of controversy over an alleged racially
tinged sexual assault, authorities said Wednesday.
   Mrs. Brawley is the mother of Tawana Brawley, the black
teen-ager who said she was abducted and raped by a gang of white
men.
   ``At any point for the rest of her life, if she returns to the
state of New York, she is subject to being arrested,'' said Timothy
Gilles, a spokesman for state Attorney General Robert Abrams, said.
   Gilles did not say if authorities would pursue the Brawleys in
Virginia or ask for help from authorities there.
   The Wappingers Falls family left the state several weeks ago
after Mrs. Brawley was sentenced for refusing to testify before a
grand jury investigating the allegations made by her daughter.
   ``Tawana wanted to go to school in a normal setting,'' the Rev.
Al Sharpton, an adviser to the family, said Wednesday. ``People (in
Wappingers Falls) were constantly looking at her in class as a
victim of this rape.''
   He said the family would remain in Virginia Beach, Va., at least
through the end of the school year.
   Following the advice of the Sharpton and attorneys C. Vernon
Mason and Alton Maddox, the family has refused to cooperate with
investigators. They maintain the criminal justice system
discriminates against minorities.
   The New York Daily News said Miss Brawley is attending the Floyd
E. Kellam High School.
   The Brawleys' new home is in an apartment complex that has a
racquetball court, pool, whirlpool, sun deck, jogging trail,
volleyball court and clubhouse, the News said. Rent is about $600 a
month.
   Miss Brawley, reported missing for four days last November, was
found in a plastic garbage bag with excrement smeared and racial
epithets written on her body.
   Abrams was named special prosecutor and a grand jury began
investigating the teen-ager's charges, but it has been thwarted by
the family's refusal to testify. The grand jury also reportedly
voted to subpoena Miss Brawley but she has stayed out of state to
avoid being served with the summons.
   A grand jury is expected to issue a report on its seven-month
investigation within several weeks. Abrams has said the panel has
not been able to substantiate Miss Brawley's claims.
</TEXT>
