<DOCNO> AP880921-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-88 1713EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland     09-21 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walesa Says Changes in System, Not Faces, Needed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity's Lech Walesa, commenting on
the resignation of Prime Minister Zbigniew Messner's government,
said Wednesday that Poland does not need another personnel shakeup,
but a change in the system.
   The influential communist weekly Polityka gave front-page play
Wednesday to a deputy's remarks in Parliament that the government
lacks independence and is too subordinate to the Polish United
Workers (Communist) Party.
   Messner and all 19 of his Cabinet ministers, under attack for
their handling of the economy, stepped down Monday in the first
mass resignation of the government in Poland's postwar history.
   The Sejm, or parliament, is scheduled to meet Sept. 27 to name a
new prime minister, who would have a brief period to assemble a new
government, the state-run PAP news service said.
   Under Poland's political system, the party is the ultimate seat
of power. It appoints the government through its mandated majority
in parliament. The party sets goals, and it is the responsibility
of the government to execute them.
   ``I am against personnel shakeups. I am for systematic
changes,'' Walesa, a Nobel Peace laureate, said in a telephone
interview.
   ``If the personnel changes don't bring about any systematic
changes, then they are good for nothing.''
   Walesa said, however, that removal of Messner and his Cabinet
``may enable certain systematic changes.'' He said the government
had been ``burdened by negative solutions.''
   His remarks were echoed by journalist Tadeusz Mazowiecki, a
senior adviser to the outlawed Solidarity free trade union movement
which Walesa helped found and formerly headed.
   Mazowiecki said the government changes would be positive ``if
one were to look at it as a manifestation of some broader changes .
.. If it is to be only a personnel shakeup, then we are not
interested.''
   Deputy Mikolaj Kozakiewicz told parliament on Monday that the
government cannot be held responsible for Poland's problems because
it lacks freedom of action. He cited the dominance of the party
apparatus over day-to-day government affairs.
   ``I am only stating aloud what everybody has known for some
time, that under the present political system, the government has
not been, and is not, sovereign,'' Kozakiewicz, a reform-minded
member of the communist-allied Peasant Party, said.
   ``It is impossible to institute radical economic and
socio-political changes without an equally radical change in the
manner of exercising the leading role of the party.''
   Polityka on Wednesday ran a front-page story on the government's
removal, under a headline saying: ``Government Collapsed, Problems
Remained.''
   The article devoted considerable space to Kozakiewicz's remarks
and commented, ``In our country, the crisis has covered the whole
system of ruling, and it is not new faces in the government that
will help overcome it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
