<2ND_LINE>AM-Kennedy-Kenyan,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kenyan Activist Wins Robert F. Kennedy Human Rights Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dissident Kenyan lawyer Gibson Kamau Kuria won
the 1988 Robert F. Kennedy Human Rights Award, judges for the fifth
annual prize said Wednesday in an attack on human-rights conditions
in Kenya.
   A statement announcing the $30,000 award said Kuria was
imprisoned without trial from February to December of 1987,
including nine months in solitary confinement, and was subjected to
mental and physical abuse.
   ``He was forced to stand naked before his interrogators'' and
was threatened with death and denied medical care and legal
assistance, it said.
   ``President (Daniel arap) Moi has presided over a steady
deterioration of the rule of law,'' said Rose Styron, chair of the
judges panel. ``Kenya today is a land where only the animals are
truly free.''
   ``Murder, torture, intimidation have all served to twist a
peaceful land into a perverse nation,'' she said. ``A patriot like
Gibson Kamau Kuria is punished and humiliated for defending the
rights of his fellow citizens.''
   The announcement of the award _ to honor people ``who strike out
against injustice and oppression at great personal risk'' _ was
made by Kathleen Kennedy Townsend, daughter of the former U.S.
senator and attorney general.
   Kuria is to be honored at a ceremony at Georgetown University in
Washington Nov. 15, but the statement said he had been denied a
passport to leave Kenya.
</TEXT>
