<HEAD>VP Debate, Baseball Playoff Times Conflict</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The time for the debate between vice
presidential candidates Dan Quayle and Lloyd Bentsen may be moved
because it conflicts with a scheduled major-league baseball playoff
game, a debate official said.
   Bob Neuman of the Commission on Presidential Debates said the
commission has informally approached ABC television and
representatives of the Quayle and Bentsen campaigns about adjusting
schedules.
   The Oct. 5 debate at the Omaha City Auditorium is scheduled to
begin at 8 p.m. CDT. ABC is scheduled to broadcast the first game
of the American League baseball playoff series beginning at 7
o'clock that night.
   Neuman said the debate commission hopes the starting times of
the game and the debate could be moved to allow ABC to broadcast
the debate.
   ``We're hoping for a little give and take on both sides,''
Neuman said, adding that no formal negotiations had begun.
   ``We're just making inquiries right now,'' he said.
   ABC News spokeswoman Joanne Berg said the network's coverage
plans for the debate have not been completed.
