<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nigeria-Floods     09-21 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nigeria-Floods,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Dam Collapses In Rain-Soaked West Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dam collapse in western Nigeria let
loose a wall of water that killed several people and left 100,000
homeless in a low-lying farming area, government-run radio and a
newspaper reported Wednesday.
   The dam was the fourth to give way in Nigeria in recent weeks
because of torrential rains, the heaviest in western Africa in two
decades.
   The rains killed more than 130 people and left hundreds of
thousands homeless.
   Radio Nigeria said a concrete dam collapsed Tuesday on the
Enrinle River in Oyo state, flooding farmland and damaging bridges.
It said precise casualty figures were not immediately available,
but Punch newspaper reported several deaths.
   Nigeria earlier reported that heavy flooding in a wide area
across the country's northern tier had claimed at least 50 lives.
Many victims died when their homes collapsed. Others drowned. Three
were reported killed by crocodiles that were swept into their
villages.
   Benin, Nigeria's western neighbor, appealed Sunday for help for
more than 100,000 people without shelter there after the rains.
   In the Sahel, the dry stretch of land on the southern fringe of
the Sahara, Burkina Faso has reported 16 dead, many roads washed
out and farmland flooded. Niger reported 13 deaths. Rains in Chad
took 49 lives.
   On the West African coast, heavy rains have been nearly wiped
out the rice crops of Liberia and Sierra Leone. The rains do
promise, however, the best harvests since two decades of drought
began in the Sahel.
</TEXT>
