<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NoahRobinson     09-21 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Noah Robinson,0599</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jesse Jackson Half-Brother Jailed In Gang-linked Slaying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chicago businessman Noah Robinson, Jesse
Jackson's half-brother, remained jailed Wednesday on murder charges
in a case described by authorities as a gangland-style execution.
   ``This is absolutely the most complicated case we've ever worked
on,'' said Detective Keith Morton. He said Tuesday's arrest follows
a 2{-year investigation that took him to Chicago 10 times in the
past year.
   Robinson was the sixth person charged with murder in the 1986
slaying of Leroy ``Hambone'' Barber outside a Greenville business
owned by Robinson. Five others, alleged members of Chicago's El
Rukn street gang, were charged several weeks ago.
   Barber once worked for Robinson in Chicago and the two men had
had several altercations over the years, the Greenville Piedmont
reported Wednesday.
   Robinson, 46, surrendered Tuesday and was being held at the
Greenville County Detention Center. A bond hearing Wednesday was
postponed at the request of Robinson's attorneys and was not
immediately rescheduled.
   The warrant charging Robinson said witnesses and co-defendants
allege that Robinson hired people to murder Barber.
   Matt Hawley, deputy assistant solicitor, said his office
probably will seek the death penalty against Robinson. Hawley said
under state law hiring, directing or soliciting a murder is
considered an aggravating circumstance.
   The Rev. J.M. Flemming, a Greenville pastor, distributed a
statement by Robinson that said: ``I had no role in or no knowledge
of that killing prior to it happening.''
   In the statement, Robinson said the case against him was based
on information given to police by El Rukns who have criminal
records and were offered cash and lenient sentences in exchange for
testifying against him.
   He attacked their credibility and provided the arrest records of
some co-defendants who he said were cooperating with the
investigation.
   Robinson's attorney, Robert F. Simone of Philadelphia, described
Robinson's case as a relatively simple one.
   Simone said Wednesday the case ``has to do with whether you
believe the government's informants. It's all a question of
credibility or believability.''
   Robinson owns a construction company and several other
enterprises across the country. He has maintained that he is a
victim of a political conspiracy caused partly by the success of
his half-brother.
   Robinson and Jackson share the same father, but the former
Democratic presidential hopeful has said he has had no recent
contact with his half-brother.
   Jackson said from his Chicago home Wednesday that he was
unfamiliar with the particulars of Robinson's case.
   ``It would be ill-advised to comment on something I know nothing
about,'' he said. Asked how he felt about the death penalty in
general, Jackson said, ``I choose not to comment on any of it at
this time.''
   The Greenville Piedmont reported that Robinson and Barber were
childhood friends in Greenville. In 1977, Robinson hired Barber as
a janitor in Chicago.
   Four years later, Barber and another Greenville man robbed
Robinson at gunpoint. Barber was sent to prison for the robbery,
but Robinson rehired him when he was released in 1984, the
newspaper said.
   Authorities have alleged that five El Rukns shot Barber in the
head Jan. 2, 1986, after he was called to a pay telephone outside a
lounge in Greenville. A former gang member, Tramell Davis, has told
authorities that the leader of the El Rukns ordered Barber killed
for harassing Robinson.
   Robinson said a few days before Christmas in 1985, Barber
punched him in the face while he was visiting his parents in
Greenville, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
