<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gibraltar-IRA     09-21 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gibraltar-IRA,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Kept in Dark So IRA Agents Could Enter, Policeman Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GIBRALTAR (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Gibraltar police officer testified
Wednesday that this British colony's border officials were
purposely kept uninformed about an anti-terrorist operation to
permit an IRA unit to enter unhindered from Spain.
   The operation resulted in British commandos shooting and killing
three unarmed Irish Republican Army members on March 6.
   Gibraltar Police Chief Inspector Joe Ullger told a coroner's
inquest that neither Gibraltar immigration officers nor those in
customs were informed of the operation because ``the only way for
it to succeed was to allow the terrorists to come in'' to the
colony.
   His disclosure came under cross-examination on the 12th day of
the inquest into the deaths of Sean Savage, 24, Daniel McCann, 30,
and Mairead Farrell, 31.
   Members of Britain's elite Special Air Service (SAS) branch of
the military, who fired more than two dozen bullets into the bodies
of Farrell, McCann and Savage, testified that the anti-IRA mission
had been to arrest the three.
   Another witness, Gibraltar resident Josephine Celecia, testified
Wednesday that from her second-floor bedroom window, she saw one of
the soldiers standing over two fallen bodies at a filling station
across the street, and then heard four or five shots fired.
   She said that earlier she had seen McCann and Ms. Farrell
walking together toward the border.
   ``I looked away and then heard two loud bangs,'' she said.
   Mrs. Celecia said when she looked back she saw ``a man whose
hands were pointing towards the ground with two people lying
there.''
   She said she then heard four or five more shots.
   Michael Hucker, the lawyer for the seven SAS commandos involved
in the operation, challenged her statements.
   ``A lot of this (you're saying) just isn't the truth,'' Hucker
said. ``The events have been muddled over the months.''
   ``I'm just saying what I saw,'' Mrs. Celecia said.
   The seven commandos and several British intelligence officers
have testified they believed the three were armed and dangerous and
on a mission to set off a car bomb in Gibraltar by a radio-control
device when they were shot.
   The commandos who did the shooting said they fired with intent
to kill when the three answered their challenge with ``sudden and
aggressive movements.''
   After the shootings, police found no radio-control device and no
bomb in the car parked by Savage in Gibraltar, but the IRA
acknowledged the three were members on active service.
   Two days later police found a car linked to the IRA unit packed
with 141 pounds of Czechoslovak-made explosives in nearby Marbella,
Spain.
   Critics of British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government
have claimed the deaths show an unofficial ``shoot-to-kill'' policy
against IRA members. The outlawed IRA seeks unification between
Protestant-dominated Northern Ireland and the Roman Catholic Irish
republic.
   The inquest has no powers of prosecution, but is expected to
determine whether the soldiers' actions were lawful.
   Ullger acted as liaison between police officials directing the
operation and Gibraltar's undercover police surveillance team. He
said Spanish police were informed of the operation and were given
photos of the three, but failed to spot them.
</TEXT>
