<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Radon     09-21 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Radon,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Cites Drinking Water as Possible Source of Household Radon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radon gas evaporating out of drinking water
could be ``as large a contaminant as anything we're dealing with,''
the head of drinking water programs at the Environmental Protection
Agency said Wednesday.
   Water-source radon every year probably accounts for a few
hundred fatal lung cancers caused by breathing radon indoors, which
the agency has estimated could total as many as 20,000 deaths a
year, said Mike Cook, director of the agency's Office of Drinking
Water.
   Radon, a radioactive gas that can be concentrated in houses,
generally arises from the soil beneath a home, working its way
through foundation cracks or other entrances.
   But experts have known for several years that water can carry
radon, posing its danger not in the drinking of the water but by
liberating into the air in showers, washing machines and other ways.
   Cook commented in an interview on a discussion on the ``USA
Today Television Show'' quoting results of a survey of wells across
the country that said 72 percent had ``dangerously high'' radon
levels.
   Cook did not use the term ``dangerous.'' He said the poll
findings referred to a water contamination of radon that would
increase the risk of getting lung cancer by about one in 10,000,
the risk level used informally by some EPA programs to determine
when action is needed.
   This risk level would correspond to 200 picocuries per liter of
water, which the agency believes would add 0.02 picocuries per
liter to the air in a typical home _ roughly a tenth of the normal
outdoor concentration.
   A picocurie is a standard measure of radiation.
   Last week's call for home tests said homeowners should find the
radon source and try to reduce it if indoor contamination is above
4 picocuries per liter of air. The agency says this concentration
increases the risk of lung cancer by about one in 100.
   Probably half the private wells in the country show some
contamination with radon and about 30,000 public water supplies
contain 200 picocuries per liter with perhaps 5,000 systems above
2,000 picocuries per liter, Cook said.
   ``We believe it accounts for only a few percent'' of all radon
deaths, but ``At a few hundred deaths per year, radon looms as
large a contaminant as anything we're dealing with,'' Cook said.
``Our recently adopted volatile organic compound regulations are
aimed at 30 deaths a year.''
   The agency's current regulations on radioactivity in water do
not cover radon, but EPA expects to ask for public comment soon on
possible options, Cook said.
   The water-source concern arose the same day that two employees
of EPA's waste programs released a letter to Administrator Lee M.
Thomas asking if the agency were not overlooking a source of indoor
radon in building materials.
   The two employees, Hugh Kaufman and William Sanjour, said in
their letter that the agency in 1978 considered classifying some
sources of building materials as hazardous waste but eventually
left them unregulated.
   ``We have never seen any studies'' of whether building materials
contribute to the radon problem, Kaufman and Sanjour said.
   EPA spokesman Chris Rice said the agency had concluded that
building materials could be significant contributors to radon only
in the West, where uranium mill waste might have been used, or
where phosphate slag from Florida had been used.
   ``Kaufman has not been involved with radon for 12 years,'' said
Dave Cohen, the agency's chief press officer. ``Since then, the
agency has found building materials to be negligible. Hugh hasn't
stopped to find out what's been going on.''
   ``We could not accept the conclusion that there is nothing to
regulate,'' Kaufman and Sanjour said, suggesting that radon tests
could be made a condition of government-guaranteed housing loans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880921-0157 </DOCNO>
