<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0705 09-21 0877</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0705,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Promises Health Care for Mothers, Babies; Prepares for
Debate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 3-4, He spent...as well, to add mock debate set
for Friday, picking up 5th pvs, During the...getting ready''; ADDS
two grafs after last graf pvs to add meeting with Greek foreign
minister</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis said Wednesday the
Reagan-Bush administration has given ``a cold shoulder'' to
children and families, and he promised that if elected no poor
mother or child will go without essential health care.
   Dukakis commented at Brigham & Women's Hospital in a speech that
was his only public appearance on a day spent mostly in preparation
for Sunday's first presidential debate with Republican rival George
Bush.
   He spent considerable time reading briefing papers on issues
likely to arise at the debate and also has rented a meeting room at
a downtown Boston hotel for practice sessions. A campaign source
said Dukakis was scheduled to take part in a mock debate Friday
with Washington attorney Bob Barnett standing in as Bush, a role he
played in 1984 when Bush debated Democratic vice presidential
candidate Geraldine Ferraro.
   Preparations included a meeting Wednesday with Sen. Bill Bradley
of New Jersey, and meetings were scheduled later in the week with
Govs. Mario Cuomo of New York and Bill Clinton of Arkansas as well.
Bradley and possibly Cuomo were to sit in on the mock debate, said
the source, who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
   During the hospital tour Dukakis was asked if he wanted to talk
about the debate and he quickly answered, ``No.'' But as he walked
away from reporters he said he was ``slowly getting ready.''
   Dukakis, as has been his practice in recent days, sprinkled
criticism of Bush into his speech, ridiculing the vice president's
stated commitment to the needy by listing what he said were cuts
the Reagan administration has made to Medicaid and numerous other
programs that assist poor families.
   ``When children and their families have needed a helping hand,
Mr. Bush's administration has given them a cold shoulder,'' Dukakis
said at the hospital, where he met with two new mothers and their
babies. ``When the time came to stand up for our children's health
care needs, George Bush was nowhere to be found.
   ``But he was there when his administration conducted an annual
assault on immunization programs,'' the Democratic presidential
nominee said. ``He was there when they cut maternal and child
health programs. He was there when they cut nutrition supplements
for pregnant women and their families. And he was there when they
cut off Medicaid for 700,000 children.''
   Dukakis said his national ``Healthy Start'' program would be
modeled after a Massachusetts program that has served 16,000 women
since 1985 and has been cited as a factor in the reduction in the
state's infant mortality rate.
   ``We know that we can give all of our children, especially those
most at risk, a healthy start on life,'' Dukakis said in his
speech, which was interrupted several times as one of the children
he shared the stage with took a stroll past the Massachusetts
governor.
   The Dukakis program, like the state program, would provide care
for pregnant women and later to their children when uninsured or
underinsured. Dukakis aides said it would cost $100 million in the
first year but that the money would be made up within 12 months
because the prenatal care would help prevent serious illnesses in
the baby's first year.
   Dukakis, whose father was a family doctor, recalled that ``when
I was growing up, he talked the principle that every doctor lives
by: `Above all, do no harm.' I wish somebody had told that to
George Bush.''
   He said that during the Reagan years the number of children
immunized has dropped 20 percent and that the incidence of several
childhood diseases has increased. ``Today, an infant born in this
country has less chance of survival than those born in 18 other
countries, including Spain and Singapore,'' Dukakis said.
   He was introduced by his daughter-in-law, Lisa Dukakis, who is
expecting her first child in January.
   The ``Healthy Start'' program is part of the Democratic ticket's
focus this week on health care. Dukakis on Tuesday detailed his
plan for a universal health care system financed largely by
employers, and his running mate, Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen,
announced a rural health care initiative on Wednesday.
   Dukakis has been increasingly critical of Bush in recent weeks
but did not deliver a line in the prepared text of his speech that
attacked the vice president's upbringing: ``His vision of America
doesn't extend beyond the gates of the country club.''
   He did continue to include in his oratory lines associated with
John F. Kennedy, at one point saying that his vision was of an
America ``with new horizons to reach and new frontiers to conquer.''
   Dukakis also met Wednesday afternoon with Greek Foreign Minister
Karolos Papoulias, who came to Boston after meeting Secretary of
State George Shultz in Washington to discuss negotiations on U.S.
use of Greek military bases.
   The foreign minister sought meetings with both Dukakis and Bush
but a meeting with Bush has not been scheduled, an aide to
Papoulias said.
</TEXT>
