<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-88 2029EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-PeaceTalks     09-21 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Peace Talks,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition in South-West Africa Rejects Meeting U.N. Chief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition parties in
South-West Africa rejected on Wednesday a meeting in this country
with U.N. chief Javier Perez de Cuellar, who planned to discuss
independence for the territory.
   Some political parties in the South African-administered
territory, also known as Namibia, said Perez de Cuellar should have
planned to visit the territory during his trip to South Africa.
   The U.N. secretary-general is coming here to discuss
negotiations to bring peace to southern Africa.
   Perez de Cuellar was due to arrive at Waterkloof air force base
near Pretoria on Wednesday night, but his takeoff from Paris was
delayed and the arrival was rescheduled until after midnight
Thursday, the South African Foreign Affairs Department said.
   He is scheduled to be in South Africa on Thursday and Friday,
then head to Angola on Saturday to continue talks aimed at
resolving wars in Angola and South-West Africa.
   Perez de Cuellar offered to consult Thursday in Pretoria with
leaders of the more than 40 political parties in Namibia, which
South Africa rules in violation of U.N. resolutions.
   The Cabinet of Namibia's ``transitional government,''
representing 17 political parties, plans to meet with Perez de
Cuellar. The remaining parties either rejected the offer or gave no
indication they will attend.
   ``If the secretary-general was coming to see Namibians, he
should come here (to Namibia),'' Danny Tjongarero, spokesman for
the the legal political wing of the South-West Africa People's
Organization, said in Windhoek, capital of Namibia.
   SWAPO's outlawed armed wing has been fighting since 1966 to oust
South African rule. The organization is widely favored to win any
independence elections in the territory.
   Other opposition parties complained that they learned of Perez
de Cuellar's invitation only on radio and television broadcasts.
   ``The secretary-general should have the proper respect for the
Namibian people and invitations should be done accordingly,'' said
Othillie Abrahams, leader of the Namibia Independence Party.
   Perez de Cuellar is to meet Friday with President P.W. Botha to
discuss the U.N. plan for Namibian independence.
   South Africa agreed to end its 73-year rule and allow U.N.
observers to oversee the transition to independence, but only if
Cuban troops withdraw from neighboring Angola.
   U.S.-mediated talks among Angola, Cuba and South Africa are
trying to achieve a regional settlement.
</TEXT>
