<1ST_LINE>u p AM-DebatePrep 1stLd-Writethru a0638 09-21 0892</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Debate Prep, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0638,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dispute Settled Over Lectern Height</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RECASTS lede and SUBS grafs 4-7, A disagreement...N.C., with
six grafs to show Dukakis campaign disputing the lectern agreement,
picking up 8th pvs, Dukakis had...or 14; also SUBS 16th graf, He
met...defense advice, picking up 17th pvs, Thomas
Donilon...Democratic governor, to show Dukakis having mock debate.
^By RITA BEAMISH</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators for George Bush and Michael
Dukakis were still squabbling over who should ask the questions in
Sunday's first 1988 presidential debate, and a Dukakis spokesman
disputed information from the Bush side that agreement was reached
on how high the candidates' lecterns should be.
   Both candidates spent at least part of Wednesday going over
issues and likely questions with advisers as they counted down the
days to a confrontation that both sides consider crucial.
   Dukakis made a campaign appearance in Boston, but Bush stayed
out of the public eye. Both men have limited public schedules the
rest of the week as debate preparations intensify.
   A disagreement over how high the lecterns should be for the
lanky Republican nominee Bush and the five-inch-shorter Democrat
Dukakis ended in compromise, according to one source in the Bush
campaign.
   Bush, the source said, will speak at a 48-inch lectern, down
slightly from his customary 52 inches. Dukakis, the source said,
will stand behind a 41-inch lectern and will use a small riser.
   But campaign spokesman Leslie Dach disputed the 41-inch figure,
saying he doesn't know how high it will be for Dukakis.
   As for a riser, the Dukakis campaign hasn't addressed that
issue, and ``any other information is just the Bush campaign's
misinformation,'' he said.
   On Tuesday, the campaigns had quibbled over the matter, Dukakis
officials pushing for shorter lecterns for both, Bush staff members
arguing for a minimum of 46 inches and saying their 6-foot-one
candidate would not stand behind anything that made him stoop.
   Under discussion on Wednesday was the makeup of the panel of
journalists that will question the two presidential contenders
during the debate at 8 p.m. EDT at Wake Forest University in
Winston-Salem, N.C.
   Dukakis had proposed that television anchors from ABC, NBC, CBS
and CNN serve as the moderator and three questioners for the first
debate, with a panel of print journalists filling those roles for
either the vice presidential debate on Oct. 5 or the second
presidential debate on Oct. 13 or 14.
   The Bush campaign offered a list of 10 questioners and four
moderaters, from TV and print media, from which to select the
panelists.
   Meanwhile, President Reagan weighed in with encouragement for
his vice president. Asked whether he'd given Bush any hints in
preparation for the debate, he responded with a chuckle, ``Take no
prisoners.''
   When Bush was asked last week whether he would try to emulate
Reagan's ability to project a personable image, he said he might
review some of Reagan's debate tapes ``because I think it is
important to be able to say what you feel in your heart.''
   The Republican candidate was scheduled for only one campaign
event the rest of the week _ a $5 million fund-raiser in Houston on
Thursday with Reagan.
   On Wednesday, Bush engaged in a mock debate with former Deputy
Treasury Secretary Richard Darman playing the role of Dukakis.
Darman is a protege of Bush campaign chairman James A. Baker III.
   To prep Dukakis, the Bush role in practice debates is being
played by Washington lawyer Robert Barnett, a return engagement of
his portrayal of Bush in debate rehearsals with 1984 Democratic
vice presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro. Dukakis will have a
mock debate with Barnett on Friday, a campaign source said.
   Dukakis had one campaign stop on Wednesday, a health care event
at a hospital. He also put in some time on gubernatorial chores at
the Massachusetts statehouse in addition to reviewing debate
briefing papers.
   He met with advisers including Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., who
has given him foreign policy and defense advice. Bradley and
possibly Gov. Mario Cuomo, with whom Dukakis is meeting this week,
were to sit in on the mock debate.
   Thomas Donilon, a top official of Walter F. Mondale's campaign
four years ago, was coordinating debate preparation for the
Democratic governor.
   Dukakis aides reviewed tapes of the governor's debates earlier
this year during the Democratic presidential primary contests as
well as Bush's performance in the Republican primary debates and
his 1984 debate with Ferraro.
   Both campaigns were trying to lower expectations for their
candidates so Sunday night's performances would seem good by
comparison. The debate comes at a time when most polls show the
race is close, with Bush perhaps slightly ahead.
   ``Dukakis is a good debater,'' Bush told reporters recently on
his campaign plane. ``He is a professional college debater and I'm
not.''
   But Dukakis spokesman Dach countered, ``Remember, Bush has the
experience of these debates, the '84 debate, which is the only
relevant experience.''
   All sides agree that the first debate is critical.
   ``Tens of millions of people are going to watch and they're
going to form their opinions by themselves,'' said Dach. ``In the
primary debates very few people watched and opinions were formed by
the next day's headlines.''
   Bush's national political director Rich Bond said: ``You want to
avoid costly mistakes. And you want to come across as
presidential.''
</TEXT>
