<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-21 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seasonably Cool In North, Hot In South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cool weather extended across much of the North and the far West
on Wednesday, while the Gulf Coast states and the southern half of
the Great Plains had hot weather, fairly normal there for the last
full day of summer.
   A warm front over the central Plains helped produce some showers
and thunderstorms over Nebraska and western Iowa. Other showers and
thunderstorms occurred over Florida, the lower Mississippi Valley
and the Southwest.
   Rain moved off the coast of Maine by early afternoon, after
affecting the Northeastern states for a couple days. But some light
rain and drizzle lingered in western New York state.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included
three-tenths of an inch at Green River, Utah, and almost two-tenths
of an inch at Griffiss Air Force Base, at Rome, N.Y.
   Cloudy skies and cool temperatures reached from the Great Lakes
region across Minnesota to North Dakota. Temperatures were in the
50s and 60s in the early afternoon, with a few 40s in North Dakota
and Minnesota.
   Temperatures were close to 90 degrees Wednesday afternoon in
Florida, the Gulf Coast states, Texas and across the Plains as far
north as Kansas. Orlando, Fla., tied a record high of 94 degrees.
Manhattan, Kan., had 92 degrees at 2 p.m. CDT.
   The desert Southwest had a break from the heat as mid-afternoon
temperatures were only in the 70s to middle 80s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 45
degrees at Devils Lake, N.D., and Jackson, Wyo., to 98 degrees at
Harlingen, Texas. The nation's low Wednesday morning was 23 degrees
at Truckee, Calif.
   With fall officially beginning at 3:29 p.m. EDT on Thursday, the
national forecast called for showers and scattered thunderstorms
from the region west and northwest of the Rockies across the
range's central and southern reaches, the southern high Plains,
Nebraska, the middle Mississippi Valley and the lower Ohio Valley
to Wisconsin and Michigan. Scattered showers were expected in
western New York, and scattered afternoon showers and thunderstorms
in central and southern Florida.
   High temperatures were predicted to be in the 70s or 80s across
much of the nation, except for 60s in Washington state and near the
Canadian border from northern Minnesota to northern New England,
and 90s from the southern Great Plains through the lower
Mississippi Valley and Gulf Coast states to the south Atlantic
Coast states.
</TEXT>
