<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Coddington     09-21 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Coddington,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Decides On Death In Coddington Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLACERVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury Wednesday decided that gambler
and math whiz Herbert Coddington, convicted of the strangulation
murders of two women and sexual assaults on two teen-age girls,
should receive the death penalty.
   The El Dorado County Superior Court jury reached the verdict in
the penalty phase of the lengthy murder trial after 3{ hours of
deliberations over two days. Superior Court Judge Terrence Finney
set sentencing for Nov. 18.
   Coddington, 29, lowered his head and stared at the defense table
as the verdict was read.
   Joette Hotchkiss, one of the jurors, said the panel took five
votes before it agreed on the death penalty.
   ``The whole jury was very disturbed about Herb's lack of
remorse,'' she said. ``The only time he was emotional was when his
mom was on the stand, or when (District Attorney Ron) Tepper said
something he didn't like.''
   Jim Whiting, son of victim Maybelle Martin, 69, burst into tears
and was led from the courtroom.
   ``I don't even understand the emotions that went through me when
I first heard the verdict,'' he said. ``When I tried to have
compassion for her (Coddington's mother), I kept thinking about my
mother.''
   Coddington's lawyers said he believed he received messages from
God through traffic signals when he committed the crimes in May
1987, but the prosecutor said Coddington was a deliberate killer
who kept diaries of his acts.
   ``I think the jury reached the right verdict,'' Tepper said.
   Coddington, who has a fondness for disguises, was convicted Aug.
11 of strangling Reno modeling agency owner Martin and Dorothy
Walsh, 73, at his South Lake Tahoe mobile home.
   He also was convicted of imprisoning two teen-age models in a
specially built chamber in his bedroom and sexually assaulting them
over a two-day period.
   According to testimony, Coddington lured the women and girls to
his home by pretending to be a producer of an anti-drug videotape.
The girls, then aged 12 and 14, were models in Martin's agency.
   But after the females arrived, Coddington strangled Martin and
Walsh and stuffed their bodies into trash bags, and locked the
girls into a soundproof room.
</TEXT>
