<DOCNO> AP880921-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-88 2004EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-Nicaragua     09-21 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Nicaragua,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan Envoy Says Washington Blocking Visas</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department is blocking visas for
most Nicaraguans who want to attend President Daniel Ortega's
speech to the General Assembly, Nicaragua's U.N. ambassador said
Wednesday.
   Ortega family members, including his wife and children, his
doctor, chief of protocol and many of his senior advisers are among
the 22 to 25 Nicaraguans whose visas will not be processed in time
for the Sandinista leader's Sept. 28 address, said the Nicaraguan
U.N. ambassador, Alejandro Serrano Caldera.
   The State Department told the Nicaraguan Mission that Ortega and
some senior Nicaraguan officials will receive their visas in time
for their scheduled arrival Saturday, said Serrano.
   But Serrano said the State Department also told the Nicaraguan
Mission that the other 22 to 25 visas will not be decided until
Oct. 4, a week after Ortega speaks to the 159-member General
Assembly.
   In Washington, a State Department official denied that the
administration is delaying or blocking the visas.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the U.S.
Embassy in Managua is working as fast as it can on the visa
requests, but has been slowed by personnel shortages.
   The official noted that Nicaragua expelled eight U.S. diplomats
from Managua in July and has refused to allow the State Department
to replace them.
   The leftist Sandinista government accused the U.S. diplomats of
interfering in Nicaragua's internal affairs. The State Department
retaliated by expelling eight Nicaraguan diplomats from Washington.
   Serrano said Ortega will deliver his speech, but said the delay
in visa approval is a violation of the United States' treaty with
the United Nations under the Headquarters Agreement.
   That agreement requires the host nation to allow U.N. missions
and diplomats to maintain offices and conduct normal business.
   Nicaraguan envoys took up the matter with the U.N.'s legal staff
and hope to receive word from them Thursday, said Serrano.
   Serrano, speaking Spanish and assisted by a translator, said the
State Department told Nicaraguan officials that Foreign Minister
Miguel D'Escoto, Deputy Foreign Minister Victor Hugo Tinoco and
their security staffs will receive visas by Saturday.
   They have not yet received visas, he said. The Nicaraguan
delegation for this year's General Assembly is about the same size
as in previous years, he added.
   Serrano said that if the United States has a dispute with
Nicaragua, it should be dealt with between the two nations. ``We
cannot see how any other considerations can apply,'' he said.
   The United States since 1981 has supported the rebels seeking to
overthrow the Nicaraguan government.
</TEXT>
