<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SouthAfrica 1stLd-Writethru a0657 09-21 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0657,0580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb, Detentions, Winnie Mandela Visit To Fugitives</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT 3 grafs after 3rd pvs, Black activist ... UPDATING
with fourth man entering U.S. consulate. PICKS up 4th graf pvs, The
government ... EDITS throughout to capitalize U.S. Consulate.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded in a concrete
trash bin at the main white bus terminal in Johannesburg at rush
hour Wednesday, injuring 19 people, almost all of them white
commuters, police said.
   A white police constable was among the injured. More than 100
bombs have exploded in the country since a national emergency was
declared June 12, 1986.
   Black activist Winnie Mandela visited three escaped detainees
who sought refuge in the U.S. Consulate nine days ago. She
criticized American restrictions barring the detainees from giving
interviews.
   A fourth person entered the consulate Wednesday, apparently
after escaping from detention, a State Department official in
Washington said. The official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
identified the man as Clifford Ngcobo and said he was given
temporary refuge in the consulate.
   The duty officer at the consulate early Thursday refered all
questions to the U.S. Information Office in Pretoria, but telephone
calls there went unanswered.
   No additional information on the man was available.
   The government detained 11 activists in Cape Town, where 75
anti-apartheid organizations are planning a weekend gathering to
discuss opposition to government actions. Lawyers and relatives
said the activists were taken from their homes by police under
emergency laws which do not require them to confirm the detentions
or give a reason for the actions.
   In the port city of Durban, police said 160 people were arrested
after hundreds of striking black dockworkers, some carrying sticks
and pipes, held an illegal gathering.
   Police said they were released after their names and addresses
were taken down. The strike began Tuesday in protest against the
dismissal of a worker and to demand higher pay.
   Mrs. Mandela, wife of jailed African National Congress leader
Nelson Mandela, visited the three black escapees at the U.S.
Consulate, on the 11th floor of a Johannesburg office building. She
said they were in a boardroom, crowded with furniture, and that
their food was provided by the black community.
   She said U.S. officials, under orders from Washington, were
refusing to let the three communicate directly with the news media,
a condition which they initially agreed to but now want to change.
   ``To highlight the position of detainees and their own
conditions it is necessary for them to communicate with you,'' she
told a press conference in an empty ground-floor office of the
building.
   ``We would like to see the Americans a little more committed
than they are,'' she said.
   A U.S. Embassy spokesman, Barry Walkley, said in response that
the U.S. government was concerned with ``maintaining the
appropriate posture of a diplomatic mission,'' as well as the
well-being of the activists, who escaped Sept. 13 from a
Johannesburg hospital where they were undergoing physiotherapy.
   ``We agreed that they can convey messages through their legal
representatives,'' he said,
   Encamped at the U.S. Consulate are two leaders of the banned
United Democratic Front _ Murphy Morobe and Mohammed Valli Moosa _
and the chairman of the banned National Education Crisis Committee,
Vusi Khanyile.
   Mrs. Mandela said the three are wary of government promises that
they will not be rearrested if they leave the consulate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
