<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TheGrove     09-21 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-The Grove,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cedar Grove: `A Time Bomb Waiting To Explode'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Shooting Protest, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHREVEPORT, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The site where a street riot by hundreds
of black people ended early Wednesday, is a poor, violent and
dangerous neighborhood known locally as ``The Grove.''
   State Sen. Greg Tarver, who is black and a former Shreveport
city councilman, called the area officially known as Cedar Grove
``a time bomb waiting to explode.'' He blamed high unemployment
among black teen-agers and a feeling that police are not providing
equal protection to blacks.
   The riot broke out after a white woman fatally shot a black man
Tuesday night near Palmer Park, an area described by police as a
curb-service market for crack, the smokable form of cocaine.
   Police familiar with Cedar Grove said drug-related stabbings,
shootings and arson have grown common in that area of this
northwestern Louisiana city of 250,000.
   ``You can come through here any time, get robbed, get cut, get
shot,'' said Richard Kenner, a policeman who has patrolled the
midnight-to-dawn shift in the area for more than seven years.
``There'll be 100 people standing around and nobody saw anything.''
   A decade ago, the area was a working class mix of whites and
blacks, but white flight to the suburbs left the neighborhood more
than 90 percent black, with practically all the whites living in a
middle class area on the fringe.
   Work on Interstate 49 has carved up the area, and the vacant
buildings along the route make the area look like a war zone.
   Drugs also have carved up the community, with the elderly and
families feeling intimidated by dealers working out of business
fronts and parking lots, police say.
   ``The drugs are there,'' said Officer Cedric Wilson, who also
patrols Cedar Grove on the night shift. ``And it's only going to
get worse before it gets better.''
   Racial tensions are high, fueled by a slaying by a white
teen-ager of a black teen-ager on Aug. 4 at a restaurant that
borders Cedar Grove.
   Police say many of the younger Grovites, as that area's
residents have become known, have become belligerent to officers
responding to crime reports.
   As in the Tuesday night and Wednesday morning rioting, officers
have been pelted with rocks when they are called to the area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
