<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NorthernIreland     09-21 0172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northern Ireland,0176</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Explodes Near Belfast City Hall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded near City Hall
Wednesday night, damaging nearby property but apparently injuring
no one, police said.
   It was the fourth bombing in four weeks in the rejuventated
commercial and business center of Belfast.
   The Irish Republican Army, which is fighting to end British rule
in Northern Ireland, claimed responsibility.
   IRA bombings in the 1970s caused widespread damage in the center
of Belfast, turning it after nightfall into a darkened, deserted
area shunned by crowds. Bars and restaurants were shuttered and
public transport non-existent in the area.
   Following a major redevelopment program, city authorities on
Aug. 25 organized ``Belfast's Big Night Out'' to mark the return of
late-night shopping and other amenities to the city center. About
80,000 people took part in the festivities.
   News reports say the latest bombing campaign, which started Aug.
24, the night before ``Big Night Out'' festivities, is thought to
be a revival of the guerrillas' ``commercial war'' of the 1970s.
</TEXT>
