<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush-Police 1stLd-Writethru   09-21 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Police, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0740,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boston Police Union Endorses Bush For President</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with additional information including
comment from Dukakis; also CORRECTS relationship of Horton victims
to show man was fiance sted husband.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leadership of Boston's police union endorsed
George Bush for president in a unanimous vote Wednesday, saying the
vice president would do a better job than Massachusetts Gov.
Michael S. Dukakis of seeing after the needs of law enforcement.
   Dukakis, the Democratic presidential nominee, said he wasn't
surprised and said he still had the support of most law enforcement
organizations both in Massachusetts and across the country.
   The 51-0 endorsement by the Boston Police Patrolman's
Association, the largest law enforcement in New England, led to a
change of plans for the Bush campaign. Campaign spokeswoman Alixe
Glen said Bush would travel to Boston on Thursday to accept the
endorsement.
   The union represents 1,500 members.
   The trip to Boston is the second this month for Bush and affords
the vice president a chance to embarrass Dukakis politically. Bush
toured Boston Harbor early this month and claimed Dukakis did
little to clean up the heavy pollution in the harbor.
   Union President Robert Guiney said union leaders were pressured
from the highest levels of state government to thwart the vote.
``We had a few calls,'' Guiney said.
   ``Maybe people took us for granted,'' he said. ``The police
officers in this state are upset with the governor and his
policies.''
   One officer emerging from the vote at the union's hall in the
Dorchester section of Boston said, ``We're sick and tired of all
these drug addicts and all these furloughs for murderers out in the
state and we felt we had to send a message.'' The officer declined
to give his name.
   Gov. Dukakis said the association ``has a history of supporting
Republicans.'' He also pointed to previous endorsements he has
received from law enforcement organizations including the
Massachusetts Police Association, the International Brotherhood of
Police Officers, the International Union of Police Associations and
the Combined Law Enforcement Associations of Texas, which is Bush's
home state.
   ``I'm very proud of the fact that the entire law enforcement
community has endorsed me,'' Dukakis said.
   Dukakis has come under frequent attack from Bush for the state's
former policy of releasing convicted first-degree murders on
weekend furloughs. One notorious case involved convicted murderer
Willie Horton, who escaped in 1985 and was arrested the following
spring for raping a Maryland woman and stabbing her fiance.
   Dukakis has fired back that the Reagan-Bush administration has
granted prison releases to serious criminals from federal prisons.
Dukakis also reversed his stand on the furlough policy, coming out
in favor of a policy that continues some furloughs but bans them
for convicted first-degree murderers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
