<HEAD>Bush Says Solidarity Should Be Legalized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush met with a Polish
Solidarity figure Wednesday and reaffirmed his support for the
legalization of the trade union movement in the Eastern European
nation.
   ``Relations between the United States and Poland need to be put
on a realistic and constructive footing,'' he said in a statement
after meeting with Janusz Onyszkiewicz, the public spokesman for
Solidarity.
   ``I hope that the current discussions between the leadership of
Solidarity and the Polish government will prove fruitful in
establishing a national dialogue, pluralism and the right of
association,'' Bush's statement said.
   It said the vice president looks forward to the legalization of
Solidarity _ ``the legalization of true freedom of individual and
political association in Poland.''
   ``I applaud the continuing attempts by Polish workers and
citizens to achieve greater freedom,'' the statement said.
