<2ND_LINE>AM-Wash Primary, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0690,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Candidates On The Move After Washington State Primary</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Lowery disputed ..., to make it liberal, sted
libel.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Mike Lowry, making his second run for the
Senate, won a spirited Democratic primary for the right to face
Republican Slade Gorton, who is making a comeback bid after losing
his seat two years ago.
   And the man they both seek to replace, retiring GOP Sen. Dan
Evans, predicted Wednesday the lessons from Gorton's upset in 1986
by Democrat Brock Adams would enable Gorton to win this time out.
   ``We're in great shape. We feel very good. Our position
contrasts with Mike Lowry on almost every issue,'' Gorton said.
   Lowry disputed those who characterize him as a liberal, saying,
``What I am is a middle-of-the-road candidate with my positions
.... That's how we got the votes, our common-sense approach to what
this country should be doing.''
   In other primary results Tuesday, state Rep. Bob Williams, an
evangelical conservative, upset King County prosecutor Norm Maleng
in the GOP governor's race and in November will face Democratic
Gov. Booth Gardner, who easily won his primary.
   Gardner said the results showed ``just how comfortable the
people are with the direction we have taken as governor.''
   With 99 percent of precincts reporting, Gardner had 502,855
votes, or 90 percent of the Democratic votes. On the Republican
side, Williams had 173,253 votes; Maleng had 127,579.
   U.S. Rep. Don Bonker of Vancouver lost the Democratic Senate
nomination to Lowry, his old friend and ally, after a vote tally
that was neck and neck for much of the evening. He pledged to
support Lowry in the general election campaign.
   Evans held the Senate seat since Henry ``Scoop'' Jackson's death
in 1983 but elected not to seek a second term. Evans beat Lowry,
49, for the seat in 1983.
   With 99 percent of the state's 6,655 precincts reporting, Lowry
had 55 percent of the Democratic vote, or 275,840 votes, to
Bonker's 45 percent, or 225,376 votes.
   Gorton, 60, a former state attorney general who swept into the
Senate on the Reagan landslide of 1980, demolished his lesser-known
challengers, former state Supreme Court Justice William Goodloe of
Seattle and Doug Smith, an Everett attorney and former White House
aide.
   Gorton took 86 percent of the GOP vote, or 322,270 votes. Smith,
who had called Gorton too liberal, was a distant second with 8
percent, or 29,662 votes, and Goodloe had 6 percent, or 24,436
votes.
   In Spokane on Wednesday, Lowry stressed his Eastern Washington
roots and said his experience living on both sides of the Cascades
would give him an understanding of statewide issues.
   Lowry denied his votes were out of step with the rest of the
state's delegation, saying that he voted with the delegation about
96 percent of the time.
</TEXT>
