<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SoloOarsman     09-21 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Solo Oarsman,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Solo Oarsman Rows Across Atlantic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLIFDEN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unemployed British plumber arrived in
western Ireland on Wednesday after rowing 2,300 miles across the
Atlantic Ocean alone in a 20-foot boat he built.
   Sean Crowley, 25, set off from Halifax, Nova Scotia, on June 17,
and landed 96 days later at Clifden, County Galway.
   ``I capsized nine times in all, and five times in one day,''
said Crowley of Croydon, 10 miles south of London. ``There were
times when I felt I would not make it. But the boat was good and
strong and saw me through.''
   Crowley said he realized he was nearing land Tuesday night when
he saw a lighthouse flashing at Slyne, on Ireland's west coast.
   ``I just stared in disbelief and in relief,'' he said. ``I could
not believe I had done it. The lights looked so beautiful. It was
great to feel I was nearing land after three months ... great when
I landed to see people, cows, land.''
   Crowley said some fishermen came to meet him Wednesday ``and
when they heard I had crossed the Atlantic they brought me ... a
few pints of beer.''
   Crowley named his boat Finn Again after another rowboat _
Finnigan's Wake _ in which he and a friend rowed across the
Atlantic in 1986 from the Canary Islands, off the coast of
northeast Africa, to South America.
</TEXT>
