<HEAD>Ms. Bhutto Gives Birth; Opposition Rejoices</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS three grafs after 11th to include background on
initial reports that baby due in December, allegations that Zia set
election date because of pregnancy; PICKS up 12th graf: Ms.
Bhutto...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By IQBAL JAFFERY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition supporters beat drums and
danced in the streets after opposition leader Benazir Bhutto gave
birth to a 7-pound boy on Wednesday.
   ``Benazir is very lucky to have a boy as her first child,'' said
Amina Bibi, a peasant woman among 500 people dancing and munching
sweets outside the hospital.
   ``I'm jubilant,'' exclaimed her husband, businessman Asif Ali
Zardari. The baby is the couple's first child.
   ``Mother and child are safe and healthy,'' Dr. N. Sethan
announced.
   People also gathered to celebrate in the city's working-class
Lyari district, a stronghold of Ms. Bhutto's left-leaning Pakistan
People's Party.
   Ms. Bhutto, 35, who still uses her maiden name professionally,
was admitted at midnight Tuesday to Lady Dufferin Charity Hospital,
where Sethan performed a Caesarean section Wednesday morning. The
doctor said Ms. Bhutto would stay at the hospital for three days
before resting at home for a week.
   The opposition leader studied at Radcliffe College in Cambridge,
Mass., before studying at Oxford. After returning to Pakistan, she
chose to wed Zardari in December in a traditional Islamic arranged
marriage.
   Ms. Bhutto is awaiting a Supreme Court ruling on elections
scheduled for Nov. 16. Before he died in a plane crash Aug. 17,
President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq said candidates must run as
individuals, rather than affiliated with parties.
   Ms. Bhutto, who feels that would favor governing party
candidates, challenged the decree and the caretaker government
asked the court to decide.
   If elections are held on a party basis, Ms. Bhutto's Pakistan
People's Party is expected to do well against Zia loyalists, who
are split into two factions of the center-right Pakistan Muslim
League.
   Zia deposed Ms. Bhutto's father, Prime Minister Zulfikar Ali
Bhutto, in a 1977 military coup. Bhutto was hanged two years later
on conviction of complicity in the murder of a political foe.
   Pakistani press reports had said Ms. Bhutto's baby was due in
December, but family members later said it was due in late
September. The press reports sparked speculation that Zia set the
elections in November so pregnancy would hamper Ms. Bhutto's
campaign effort.
   Zia denied on Aug. 13, four days before his death, that Ms.
Bhutto's pregnancy affected his decision to call for November
elections, saying ``I'm not as dirty and as low as somebody may
think I am.''
   In an interview in late August, Ms. Bhutto declined to discuss
her pregnancy but said Zia set the elections for November ``as an
inconvenience to my health.''
   Ms. Bhutto is expected to mount a vigorous election campaign.
Her mother, Begum Nusrat Bhutto, returned Saturday from six years
of self-imposed exile in France to be present for the birth and to
help run the campaign.
   ``We are pleased to announce that God has blessed our family
with the first grandson of martyr Zulfikar Ali Bhutto to be born in
the country,'' the party leader's mother said in a statement.
   Begum Bhutto's other three children each have daughters. Those
children are Sanam, a housewife in London; Murtaza, a son who is in
Syria after a 1981 airplane hijacking in which he freed some of
Zia's political prisoners; and Shahnawaz, a son who committed
suicide in France in 1985.
</TEXT>
