<HEAD>Goldwater Tells Bush To Talk About The Issues</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with Fresno appearance, SUB three grafs for 12th
pvs, Quayle was...Los Angeles, picking up 13th pvs, At
Frye...chicken costumes.
^By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle went out of his way Wednesday to
bring retired Sen. Barry Goldwater to his campaign appearance, and
wound up getting a dig from the outspoken conservative about the
way George Bush is running.
   Goldwater introduced the Republican vice presidential nominee to
a Rotary Club luncheon, saying the Indiana senator had done ``the
most fabulous job'' on a Senate Armed Services subcommittee.
Goldwater called Quayle to come out from the wings, then returned
to the microphone to say:
   ``I forgot something that I had to say, and I hope you take this
kindly. But I want you to go back and tell George Bush to start
talking about the issues, OK?''
   Goldwater did not elaborate, and afterward he avoided reporters,
saying: ``I'm not talking. I want to get the hell out of here.''
   But the dig appeared aimed at Bush's capture-the-flag
campaigning, including his pillorying Democrat Michael Dukakis for
vetoing a mandatory Pledge of Allegiance school bill in 1977.
   Quayle laughed and said only, ``I wish Barry would just say
what's on his mind.''
   The Indiana senator, returning to the town where he spent part
of his youth, then launched into his standard stump speech,
portraying Dukakis as a liberal who supports gun control, is weak
on defense and belongs to the American Civil Liberties Union.
   He questioned whether Dukakis might not use ACLU membership as a
litmus test for his judicial appointees.
   Earlier, Quayle visited an award-winning school in Chandler,
Ariz., where he offered children a brief civic lesson on free
speech after demonstrators yelled ``chicken hawk'' at him.
   He detoured on his way to the Rotary luncheon to pick up
Goldwater at his hillside home.
   ``Is one of his requirements going to be that you have to be a
member of the ACLU?'' Quayle asked the 400 Rotarians. ``We know
what kind of judges George Bush is going to appoint. He's going to
appoint people like (William) Rehnquist and (Sandra Day) O'Connor
that are strict constructionists.''
   Later, at a rally at California State University-Fresno, Quayle
blasted Dukakis, saying he signed a proclamation on Feb. 27, 1985,
supporting a union boycott of grapes.
   Quayle, speaking in the heartland of California's raisin
industry, said, ``Dukakis has done all he can to put
(grape-growers) out of business.'' Bush made a similar assertion
while campaigning in California's Central Valley last week.
   The Dukakis campaign had no immediate information on whether he
signed such a proclamation. Dukakis says such a boycott wouldn't be
necessary under his administration, because it would adopt
stringent policies to regulate pesticides. The United Farm Workers
Union has been objecting to the exposure of workers to pesticides.
   Quayle also criticized Dukakis for opposing the death penalty
under any circumstances and again asserted that Dukakis would make
dangerous judicial appointments. Quayle said that if elected,
Dukakis would appoint judges like California's former Supreme Court
chief justice Rose Bird, who was recalled by voters in part because
of her opposition to the death penalty.
   Quayle was also making a stop in Bakersfield before teaming up
with his wife, Marilyn, for a party fund-raiser Wednesday night in
Los Angeles.
   At Frye Elementary School in Chandler, he got an enthusiastic
welcome from 600 flag-waving children and 200 adults _ and jeers
from a dozen pro-Dukakis demonstrators, some clad in chicken
costumes.
   ``Don't pay any attention to them. You know, in this country of
ours, we have a thing called freedom of speech. ... '' he said.
``They have the freedom of speech, but you know what, kids? So do
we.''
   Frye, a kindergarten-to-grade six school where two-thirds of the
670 youngsters are Hispanic or other minorities, was among several
hundred elementary schools named earlier this years as winners of a
coveted ``Excellence in Education'' award from the U.S. Department
of Education.
   Quayle kept his remarks mostly non-partisan, although he said he
was presenting the award ``on behalf of the U.S. Department of
Education, on behalf of Secretary Bill Bennett and on behalf of
George Bush.'' Bush swore in Lauro Cavazos as Bennett's successor
Tuesday.
   Police escorted Jim Driscoll, a local Vietnam veteran and leader
of the protest, away from the outdoor ceremony when he began
shouting.
   Quayle spent eight years of his youth in the Phoenix area, where
his father worked on one of the family's newspapers.
   His grandfather, Gene Pulliam, owned the Arizona Republic as
well as newspapers in Indiana.
   Goldwater, who said Quayle had done ``the most fabulous job'' on
a Senate Armed Services acquisitions subcommittee, quipped, ``We
all knew Gene Pulliam _ you either knew him or you better get out
of town.''
</TEXT>
