<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HurricaneGilbert-Hyatt     09-21 0178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hurricane Gilbert-Hyatt,0183</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hotel Company Announces Closings Due To Gilbert</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hyatt International Corp. is temporarily closing
its two hotels in Cancun because of devastation wreaked by
Hurricane Gilbert on Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula, the company said
Wednesday.
   The Hyatt Regency Cancun and Hyatt Cancun Caribe will close
immediately, the company hotel said in a statement.
   Rainer Mohaupt, Hyatt's regional vice president for Latin
America, said Hyatt would implement comprehensive rebuilding plans
as soon as possible.
   Mohaupt said all guests registered at either hotel and in
residence during the hurricane would be invited back to Cancun and
provided with complimentary rooms to finish their interrupted
vacations.
   The invitations would be good from April 15, 1989, through Dec.
15, 1989.
   Mohaupt also said guests holding future reservations with Hyatt
at either of the Cancun hotels would be given assistance for
rescheduling their vacations to Acapulco at a 25 percent discount
from Cancun prices.
   He said arrangements also could be made for alternative
accomodations at other Hyatt resort destinations, including Key
West, Grand Cayman, Puerto Rico or Hawaii.
