<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Syria-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0678 09-21 0692</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Syria-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0678,0710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lebanese Army Threatens To Take Over If No President Chosen</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT 2 grafs after 6th graf pvs, The army ... UPDATING with
Reagan comment on election. Picks up 7th graf pvs, Twenty-seven
Christians ..., with minor editing to trim</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Lebanese army said Wednesday it will
take over the country by Friday if Parliament fails to elect a new
president.
   ``The army is the only force capable of change and of leading
Lebanon to salvation,'' the army's commander, Gen. Michel Aoun,
said.
   President Amin Gemayel's six-year term expires on Friday, and
Parliament is scheduled to meet Thursday to elect his successor.
The Constitution prevents Gemayel from running again.
   But lawmakers are deeply divided over several candidates, and
the last time they scheduled a vote, not enough lawmakers showed up
to form a quorum.
   The impasse has threatened to reignite Lebanon's civil war,
which has claimed 130,000 lives since 1975.
   The army is considered stronger than the various warring
Christian and Moslem militias and is believed capable of
controlling them if it had the political mandate to do so.
   In Washington, White House spokesman Roman Popadiuk said
President Reagan sent a telegram to Cardinal John O'Connor of New
York saying the U.S. government ``attaches great importance to a
peaceful and constitutional presidential election in Lebanon on
Sept 22.''
   ``We remain strongly committed to helping restore Lebanese
unity, sovreignty and territorial integrity,'' Reagan said in the
telegram, sent in response to one by O'Connor urging Reagan support
Lebanon ``at this extremely critical moment.''
   Twenty-seven Christian parliamentarians said Wednesday they will
boycott Thursday's election unless the session is shifted from
Moslem west Beirut to the no-man's land at the city's dividing
Green Line.
   ``We shall not go to the Moslem side. There will be no session
tomorrow unless the venue is changed,'' said deputy Emile Rouhana
Saqr.
   The boycott again would prevent the 51-member quorum that the
76-seat Parliament needs to hold the election.
   Lebanon's main Christian militia, the right-wing Lebanese
Forces, are backing veteran politician Raymond Edde for president.
   Edde, a Maronite Catholic, is an outspoken critic of foreign
intervention in Lebanon. He says he will seek to force Israel from
its self-designated ``security zone'' in south Lebanon within 20
days if he is elected.
   Edde has been living in self-imposed exile in Paris since
fleeing Lebanon after three assassination attempts in 1976.
   Two other Maronite Catholic candidates, former President
Suleiman Franjieh and Parliament deputy Mikhail Daher, have Syria's
backing. Syria, a supporter of Lebanon's Moslem and leftist
factions, has 40,000 troops in eastern and northern provinces of
the country as well as Beirut's Moslem sector.
   The Christians charge that Franjieh, president from 1970 to 1976
and a close friend of President Hafez Assad of Syria, will make
Lebanon a Syrian satellite.
   Christian deputies boycotted the Aug. 18 presidential vote in
Parliament to prevent a quorum when Franjieh was the only serious
candidate.
   Lebanese sources said Franjieh was likely to withdraw his
candidacy in favor of Daher, who was selected this week as a
compromise candidate by U.S. envoy Richard Murphy and Syrian
leaders.
   The Christians have wielded political power since independence
from France in 1943, when they were considered to be the majority.
Moslems now comprise an estimated 55 percent of Lebanon's 4 million
population.
   According to an unwritten national covenant dating to Lebanon's
independence from France in 1943, the president should be a
Maronite, the house speaker a Shiite Moslem and the prime minister
a Sunni Moslem.
   If Parliament fails to elect a president Thursday, Gemayel was
expected to form a caretaker Cabinet, which could formalize the de
facto partition of Lebanon into sectarian areas.
   Syria's Moslem and leftist allies charge that Gemayel would name
a Maronite prime minister and have threatened to respond by
declaring their own republic in territory they control.
   Gemayel met in Damascus with Assad and Lebanese Christian
leaders. Afterward, presidential spokesman Jibrane Kourieh said,
``An agreement for saving Lebanon has been reached between the two
presidents.'' He gave no further details except to say the Lebanese
election will be held.
</TEXT>
