<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MilitaryStrength     09-21 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Military Strength,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armed Services Numbers Grow in August Despite Goal to Reduce
Personnel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of men and women in uniform
increased in August but still remained well below year-ago levels,
the Pentagon said Wednesday.
   As of Aug. 31, the Army, Navy, Air Force and Marine Corps had
2,122,874 men and women on active duty, up 11,742 compared to the
2,111,132 reported July 31 but down 43,940 compared to the Aug. 31,
1987, total.
   The U.S. military is in the midst of general personnel cutbacks
prompted by budget reductions, however, during August, two of the
four services reported increases in personnel.
   The Army reported 763,777 on active duty as of Aug. 31, up 5,750
compared to July. The Navy reported an increase of 7,334 men and
women in August, with 584,114 on active duty at the end of the
month.
   The Air Force, meantime, reported 577,902 men and women on
active duty at the end of August, down 1,076 compared to July. And
the Marine Corps reported 197,081 on active duty, down 266 compared
to July.
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci has ordered a cut of almost
36,000 positions from the active-strength totals reported at the
end of fiscal 1987. The cuts are to be completed and the services
stabilized at the new levels by the start of fiscal 1989 on Oct. 1.
   The defense secretary has told Congress he would rather maintain
a smaller force that is properly equipped and ready to fight than a
larger, but ``hollow,'' force.
</TEXT>
