<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Turkey-Kurds 1stLd-Writethru a0675 09-21 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turkey-Kurds, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0675,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Turkey Says 1,000 Kurds Volunteer To Return To Iraq</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADD 7 grafs at end UPDATING with British diplomatic
development.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,000 Kurdish refugees will return
voluntarily to Iraq, the Foreign Ministry announced Wednesday.
   Ministry spokesman Inal Batu said the Kurds will begin returning
Thursday under the supervision of a delegation from the
International Red Cross.
   About 60,000 Kurds fled to Turkey last month, and some claimed
Iraq dropped chemical bombs on their settlements.
   Iraq, acting at the urging of Turkey, has proclaimed an amnesty
for the Kurds. Only two Kurds have returned to Iraq so far.
   Shortly after the Kurdish refugees began arriving in Turkey,
Iran said it would accept all the Kurdish refugees who wanted to go
to that country.
   Batu said the transfer of 2,000 Kurds who chose to go to Iran
was made possible by Turkish authorities last week. He said about
6,000 Kurds went to Iran via Turkey earlier.
   Premier Turgut Ozal on Friday called on Western countries to
accept half of the refugees in Turkey or to extend financial aid to
ease Turkey's burden.
   Batu said only the Netherlands has made an offer to accept 60
Kurds.
   The United States has accused Iraq of using chemical weapons
against its Kurds, who are fighting for autonomy.
   The U.S. State Department has said the accusation was based on
evidence gathered from Kurdish refugees in Turkey and the
interception of Iraqi air force communications.
   Turkey has maintained no traces of poison gas was found on the
refugees in medical screenings. But Turkish officials have said
that this does not prove Iraq did not use chemical weapons in its
campaign against the Kurds in northern Iraq.
   Iraq has denied charges of poison gas use against Kurds but has
acknowledged using poison gas against Iran in the 8-year Persian
Gulf war.
   In London, British Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe said
Wednesday compelling evidence exists that Iraqi forces used
chemical weapons against Kurds in north Iraq.
   Howe said that if true, it was nothing less than barbaric.
   He spoke to reporters after meeting in London with Iraq's
minister of state for foreign affairs, Saddoun Hammadi.
   A Foreign Office spokesman, who in accordance with British
practice refused to be identified, said Howe and Foreign Office
minister of state William Waldegrave indulged in ``plain speaking''
at the meeting with Hammadi _ a catch phrase usually taken to mean
strongly worded criticism.
   The spokesman said Howe urged the Iraqis to allow a United
Nations team to investigate the allegations.
   The spokesman said Hammadi repeated Iraqi denials that it used
chemical weapons against the Kurds and said Iraq opposed a U.N.
team as ``an unprecedented intervention'' into Iraq's affairs.
   He said Hammadi was told Britain was consulting its U.N.
colleagues over what further action could be taken.
</TEXT>
