<1ST_LINE>u a AM-FiresRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0723 09-21 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fires Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0723,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Onset Of Dry Weather Doesn't Concern Yellowstone Firefighters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 5-7 `In northern ..., with 4 grafs to UPDATE with
outdoor smoking ban, new acreage, other details of northern
California fire.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Skies began to clear over
Yellowstone National Park on Wednesday, but fire managers there and
in California and Oregon said the worst was over for firefighters.
   ``I think we have enough precipitation on the ground to keep
these things down and still hold the upper hand,'' said Yellowstone
fire information officer Bob Valen.
   ``The worst is over,'' said area commander Ken Dittmer.
   Steady rain on Tuesday prevented any significant growth in the
blazes that cover more than 1 million acres of the park.
   In northern California, a backfire and favorable weather helped
hundreds of firefighters divert a 5-day-old blaze away from
expensive homes. But officials, citing the extremely dry conditions
that have allowed more than 40,000 acres to burn recently, banned
outdoor smoking in portions of 44 counties.
   The fire west and north of Vacaville, Calif., continued to burn
over a 32-mile area Wednesday, after 500 evacuated residents were
allowed back into their homes Tuesday.
   Firefighters completed a 10-mile-long fire break Tuesday just
west of Vacaville, about 45 miles east of San Francisco, and set
fire to brush west of the break. The only part of the blaze
uncontained by fire lines was in rugged terrain in an unpopulated
area.
   Fire officials predicted they will have the Vacaville fire out
by Saturday evening, one week after the start of the blaze, which
has destroyed seven homes and blackened 27,000 acres.
   Elsewhere across the West, the situation was improved as the
worst summer for fires in three decades wound to a close. Nearly
70,000 fires have blackened more than 4.1 million acres, about half
of them in Alaska.
   Fire crews in Oregon mopped up hot spots on the stubborn Shady
Beach wildfire Wednesday in the Willamette National Forest as fire
bosses prepared to declare the nearly 9,000-acre blaze contained by
fire lines.
   With the fire 85 percent contained at 8,987 acres, about 300
firefighters have been dismissed, putting the total personnel at
2,116, Forest Service spokeswoman Lorette Laferriere said.
   The fire was expected to be declared contained Wednesday night
and controlled on Sept. 30, she added. Fires are considered
controlled when they can not jump fire lines.
   As nights lengthen over Yellowstone, the period of ``humidity
recovery,'' when small fuels such as pine needles and twigs soak up
moisture, also becomes longer, said Dittmer.
   Fires continue to creep along some 1.2 million of the park's 2.2
million acres, but analysts do not expect more of the blazes that
in earlier weeks forced firefighters to retreat from advancing
100-foot walls of flame.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
