<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to DELETE 1st Ld-Writethru designation. This is the
first AM-Thatcher-Europe story filed for AMs.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Britain's Thatcher Stirs Storm With Anti-EEC Remarks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUXEMBOURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of Britain
said Wednesday that a Europe without borders would be a
``nightmare'' and lashed out at efforts to centralize the
continent's economy.
   She made her second stinging attack since Tuesday on the notion
of a United States of Europe, a key ideal of the 12-member European
Economic Community.
   Mrs. Thatcher, on a three-nation swing of Europe, told a
luncheon group in Echternach, Luxembourg:
   ``In the great changes which are taking place, we must ensure
that we do not allow Europe to become entangled in a new network of
rules and regulations which stifle initiative and enterprise.''
   Britain's leader warned against more centralized economic
control when the Common Market drops trade barriers among member
nations. These are due to fall in 1992 with the creation of a
single European market.
   She said a better alternative to centralized economic authority
is ``active cooperation'' between governments.
   ``I will only say that those countries like the Soviet Union
which have tried to run everything from the center are now learning
that success depends upon dispersing power and decisions away from
the center,'' she said.
   ``It would be absurd for us in Europe to move in the opposite
direction. A centralized European government would be a nightmare.''
   The remarks echoed statements she made Tuesday in Bruges,
Belgium, the first stop on her tour. She flew to Madrid, Spain,
after her visit to Luxembourg.
   The prime minister's strong comments set off a stir back home.
   Opposition leaders expressed fears that Mrs. Thatcher damaged
Britain's role in the Common Market with Tuesday's speech, in which
she also rejected moves to centralize power or to ``suppress
nationhood.''
   ``The prime minister must learn to hold her tongue and not treat
Europeans to her own inimitable brand of foghorn diplomacy,'' said
George Foulkes, foreign affairs spokesman for the Labor Party.
   The centrist Social and Liberal Democratic Party said Mrs.
Thatcher demonstrated ``xenophobia in velvet gloves.''
   ``She brings to the issues of European cooperation all the
finesse of a soccer hooligan on the rampage,'' said party leader
Paddy Ashdown.
   At its headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, the EEC Commission,
the group's executive body, withheld public comment.
   A spokesman for EEC Commission President Jacques Delors said:
``Mr. Delors believes that that which unites us is more important
than that which divides us.''
   Belgian Foreign Minister Leo Tindemans, however, called Mrs.
Thatcher's Tuesday comments ``disappointing.''
   Premier Andreas Papandreou of Greece, president of the European
Community, the EEC's umbrella organization, told the British
Broadcasting Corp. that he was worried Mrs. Thatcher's remarks in
Bruges run counter to the treaties the trade bloc already has
passed.
   ``I consider it extremely important at this stage that Mrs.
Thatcher informs the community of the exact meaning of her vision
of Europe,'' Papandreou said.
   He said it was difficult for him to believe Mrs Thatcher would
be prepared to question the European Single Act, which binds member
states to open trade under an international treaty already ratified
by their parliaments.
</TEXT>
