<HEAD>Polygamist Clan Members Arraigned; Arson Attempt Investigated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERN ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COALVILLE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three polygamist clan members already
convicted of federal firearms, attempted murder and bombing charges
were arraigned Tuesday on state murder charges in the death of a
corrections officer.
   Earlier, another man linked with the group was arrested for
investigation of attempted arson at a Mormon church that the clan
members had bombed earlier this year.
   Circuit Judge Maurice Jones set a tentative preliminary hearing
date of Sept. 27 for clan leader Addam Swapp, his younger brother,
Jonathan Swapp, and John Timothy Singer.
   The three are charged in the death of Department of Corrections
Lt. Fred House, who was killed during a shootout that ended the
clan's 13-day standoff at their farm on Jan. 28.
   The three men and clan matriarch Vickie Singer were sentenced
earlier this month for their convictions on federal firearms,
attempted murder and bombing charges. Assistant Attorney General
Creighton Horton has said that barring new evidence, the state
would not charge Mrs. Singer in House's death.
   Attorneys for Addam Swapp and Singer agreed to move the
preliminary hearing to circuit court in Salt Lake City, where the
trio and Mrs. Singer are jailed. The attorney for Jonathan Swapp
said he would discuss the proposed move with his client.
   Late Monday night, Summit County sheriff's deputies responding
to an alarm at the Mormon Church's Kamas Stake Center arrested a
man on suspicion of attempted arson, County Attorney Robert Adkins
said. Adkins and Sheriff Fred Eley declined to name the man, but a
source close to the investigation identified him as Kevin
Gunderson, 34.
   Gunderson's father, Joseph Gunderson, said his son had been
staying at the clan's farm, one mile away from the church, for
almost three weeks in an effort to overcome an alcohol problem.
Heidi Swapp declined to answer reporters' questions at the farm.
   Addam Swapp has said the January bombing of the church center
was ordered by God as a sign of the impending collapse of the
Mormon Church and all government. He also said the act would
trigger the return of family patriarch John Singer, slain by police
nine years before for resisting arrest.
   The clan maintained Singer was killed in a church-state
conspiracy and that the family had been harassed for years by
police and neighbors.
</TEXT>
