<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Helmsleys     09-21 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Helmsleys,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harry Helmsley Seeking Out of Tax Case for Medical Reasons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Real estate billionaire Harry Helmsley, charged
in a massive tax evasion case with his wife, Leona, and two former
aides, is trying to get himself removed from the case for medical
reasons, defense lawyers said Tuesday.
   Lawyers would not disclose the nature of the 79-year-old
Helmsley's health proble, but U.S. District Judge John Walker
agreed to unseal transcripts of previous closed door hearings on
the issue.
   The Associated Press and several other news organizations had
petitioned Walker to disclose the sealed papers, and at the start
of the hearing, the judge said he would ``permit the unsealing of
all records except grand jury materials.''
   Walker said the material to be unsealed ``the next day''
concerned ``the physical condition of Mr. Helmsley and whether he
is fit to stand trial.''
   Helmsley and his 67-year-old wife were indicted in April on
state and federal charges that they allegedly disguised about $4
million in renovations to their Greenwich, Conn., mansion as
business expenses and took bogus tax deductions.
   The Helmsleys have pleaded innocent to the 188-count state
indictment and the 47-count federal indictment. State prosecutors
have agreed to let the federal case go first.
   They are slated to go on trial next Monday, but Assistant U.S.
Attorney James DeVita said he wanted a three-week delay so
government experts could evaluate Helmsley's health records to see
if ``more medical examinations are warranted.''
   In another development, defense lawyers for the Helmsleys sought
to have the other two defendants, Joseph V. Licari and Frank J.
Turco, severed from the case because the Helmsleys plan a
conflicting defense.
   They plan to claim the pair created false invoices ``as a cover
to permit Turco and Licari to steal from the Helmsleys,'' said
defense lawyer Gerald A. Feffer, and not ``to perpetrate tax
evasion'' by the Helmsleys as charged by the government.
   Neither of the Helmsleys was present at the hearing.
   The judge also delayed considering a defense request to move the
trial to Philadelphia because of prejudicial publicity in news
reports. Walker said last week it was too soon to decide on moving
the trial, but said he would consider again if selecting impartial
jurors in New York proves difficult.
</TEXT>
