<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Norway-WelfareWoes ADV26   09-21 0778</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Norway-Welfare Woes, ADV 26,0805</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Sept. 26, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Anti-Tax Party Makes Headway Against Norway's Welfare State</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHAN RAPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When oil prices fell in 1986, support surged
for Carl I. Hagen's small but boistrous anti-tax party.
   The Progress Party, once shunned as a right-wing fringe group,
has been surging ever since.
   Recent polls indicate the party has the support of 22 percent of
Norway's voters in a political arena traditionally dominated by the
Labor Party and the Conservatives.
   The Storting (parliament), where the Progress Party has only two
of the 157 seats, appears headed for a ``political earthquake'' in
next year's elections, the weekly newspaper Nytt Fra Norge said
recently.
   Anti-tax forces have also gained ground in Denmark, another
Scandinavian welfare state. Norway, however, had grown rich from
its North Sea oilfields, and the 1986 price collapse hit Norwegians
particularly hard.
   The standard of living has dropped in Norway for the first time
since World War II, triggering a wave of discontent and criticism
of the established parties.
   ``We have a whole load of solutions to the problems,'' Hagen
tells Norwegians.
   Hagen, 44, wants to lower taxes, restrict immigration, cut down
the public sector and let private companies handle traditional
welfare state tasks, such as hospital care, child care and care for
the elderly.
   In a country where big welfare benefits, financed through taxes,
were taken for granted even by conservatives, Hagen's policies were
considered extreme.
   However, Conservative Party policies, recently outlined,
borrowed some of Hagen's ideas, an apparent attempt to ride the
trend in advance of the elections set for Sept. 11, 1989.
   Hagen is a powerful speaker who often shouts down opponents in
the Storting, a chamber more accustomed to hushed and polite tones.
   Sitting amid piles of newspaper clippings at his small office in
the Storting building, Hagen told a visitor that the state handles
defense, schools, hospitals in a ``miserably poor way.''
   He claimed the Scandinavian welfare state does not function well
because, he said, it is modeled after East bloc socialism and
``acts as a guardian interfering in all things between heaven and
Earth.''
   A strong advocate of a free-market economy, Hagen maintains the
government's functions should be restricted to basics such as
defense and law and order.
   Political analysts say Hagen became so popular mainly because
there is no other non-socialist alternative to Prime Minister Gro
Harlem Brundtland's Labor Party.
   Lars Hellberg, a political commentator for the conservative
newspaper Aftenposten, wrote that cooperation among the
Conservatives, the farmer-dominated Center Party and the Christian
Democrats had ``completely crashed,'' since conservative leader
Kaare Willoch's three-party coalition resigned in 1986.
   He said the consequent ``irritation, frustration and
desperation'' benefited Hagen.
   The Progress Party also is getting support for its attacks on
Norway's open-door refugee policy, Hellberg said.
   In a poll published in Aftenposten on Sept. 3, Hagen had support
from 22.2 percent of the voters, compared with 3.7 in the election
of 1985.
   The three non-socialist parties fell from 45.3 percent in 1985
to 33.1 percent, with the Conservative Party dropping from 30.4
percent to 20.8. The Labor Party dropped from 40.8 percent to 31
percent.
   Despite the potential impact of the Progress Party in the 1989
elections, the other parties in the Storting have refused to
cooperate with Hagen.
   He studied economics in Britain and formerly represented a
British sugar company in Norway. He joined the Progress party when
it was formed in 1973 and became its leader the same year.
   ``In 1985, when oil prices were at their highest point, our
election results were poor,'' he said in the interview in his
office. ``But in 1986-1987 when it became necessary to save, people
grew more interested.''
   Largely because of the oil, Norwegians had grown accustomed to a
steady rise in economic growth and an expanding welfare system.
   Government revenue from North Sea oil was $7.3 billion in 1985,
more than 21 percent of the national budget. For 1988 it is
expected to be about the same as for 1986 and 1987 at $2.3 billion,
or 5 percent of the budget.
   Finance Ministry spokesman Jan-Ove Ekeberg said the slump came
amid a two-year ``consumption party'' where private consumption
increasedby 16 percent.
   He added that Norwegians should brace for ``big reductions'' in
coming years.
   Brundtland's Labor government has lowered consumption levels,
slowed inflation and lessened the current trade deficit. But the
growth of the gross national product is expected to remain at about
1 percent in 1988, compared with 4.4 percent in 1984-1985 and an
expected 2.5 percent average for the Western industrialized
countries.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Sept. 26</NOTE>
