<DOCNO> AP880921-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-09-21-88 1119EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-YellowstoneViews ADV25   09-21 0893</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Yellowstone Views, ADV 25,0916</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>A Mosaic of Green and Black</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Yellowstone Recovery</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sun comes up, a
faraway fireball heralding another day of waning summer in
Yellowstone National Park.
   After three nerve-wracking months and a blessed few inches of
early snow, the walls of flame are gone. The 60 mph winds that
danced embers from treetop to treetop have died away. The small
tourist towns that hug the boundaries of the world's first national
park are no longer threatened with annihilation.
   On the horizon is only a hint of smoke and haze.
   But Yellowstone is a casualty of what historians describe as its
worst summer of drought and flames in 300 years. Famous around the
world as a pristine symbol of wilderness, this vast park is now a
mosaic of green and black, living forests and dead trees.
   Nearly half of Yellowstone's 2.2 million acres have been touched
by fires with names like Hellroaring and Storm, North Fork and
Clover Mist. Millions of black matchsticks are all that remain of
once-thriving lodgepoles and blue spruce, aspens and firs.
   Because the flames were fickle, there are also huge patches of
sweet-smelling pines growing next to miles of charred forest. There
are fragrant meadows hard by singed marsh. Delicate ferns, turning
gold with the equinox, still grow next to creekbeds seared of every
blade of grass.
   Yellowstone National Park is not a total wasteland of scorched
earth and moonscape, but it is not the place it used to be.
   Already, charges of mismanagement and bad policy are being
leveled against park rangers. Congressional hearings and internal
reviews promise to drag on from autumn into winter and beyond.
There are fears about the future of Yellowstone's fisheries and
wildlife when ash and silt flow into streams and lakes next spring.
   More than 8,000 firefighters from the National Park Service,
Forest Service, the Army and even the Marine Corps descended on
Yellowstone to do battle, taking on one of nature's most awesome
forces with picks and shovels, hoses and hand tools.
   Daily, they still criss-cross the park in camouflage-painted
armored vehicles and chartreuse pumper trucks bearing license
plates from California to Florida. They overflow campgrounds with
their tents and catering crews and line up at pay phones to call
faraway loved ones who demand to know when they're coming home.
   But beyond the hustle of command posts and bivouacs, the birds
are singing. Old Faithful still is. Trumpeter swans, swimming in
pairs, still grace the Madison River as it meanders through its own
plateau. The Fountain Paint Pots still gurgle and steam. And the
mountains cast the same shadows hunters saw as far back as 5,000
years ago.
   ``The park is just a howling wilderness of 3,000 square miles,
full of all imaginable freaks of a fiery nature,'' wrote Rudyard
Kipling of Yellowstone in 1889.
   And so it is today.
   Those who come to Yellowstone after the fires will still see the
same breathtaking vista from Artist Point that inspired painters
Thomas Moran and Albert Bierstadt in the 1800s.
   The 700-foot sheer drop and two roaring waterfalls of the Grand
Canyon of the Yellowstone are the same as when the park's first
superintendent, Nathaniel P. Langford, was prompted to write: ``I
realized my own littleness, my helplessness, my dread exposure to
destruction, my inability to cope with or even comprehend the
mighty architecture of nature.''
   Along Virginia Cascade drive are many unspoiled spots where
falling pine needles have created a soft carpet of ground cover.
But farther down the slope lies graphic evidence of the ominous
spiral of fire that swept through that place with particular fury.
   Right above the falls there are still little puffs of smoke, and
an occasional lick of distant flames still waiting for mop-up
crews. In one turnout, five tidy picnic tables stand ready for the
next batch of campers.
   In the pastoral Hayden Valley, herds of bison graze in the
untouched meadows, a ragged chevron of geese fly overhead and the
Yellowstone River, its flow diminished by drought, braids its way
through the vast open bowl. Bull elk are everywhere.
   Just as President Theodore Roosevelt wrote during his visit in
1903, ``we saw an occasional pine squirrel, snowshoe rabbit or
marten; and in the open meadows around the hot waters there were
Canada geese and ducks of several species, and now and then a
coyote.''
   Farther south, around Yellowstone Lake, some hills on the
horizon are charred, some are not. But the fabled evening stillness
of the lake remains, its surface sometimes a mirror of its
surroundings.
   The geysers erupt as they did for naturalist John Muir in 1885:
``The wildest geysers in the world, in bright, triumphant bands,
are dancing and singing in it amid thousands of boiling springs,
mud volcanoes, mush and broth caldrons whose contents are of every
color and consistency, splash and heave and roar in bewildering
abundance.''
   As has been the case in recent years, most of Yellowstone's
bears are elusive, but many firefighters have seen them. Park
biologists are confident the bears are still in the back country.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Tad Bartimus is the AP Mountain States regional
reporter, based in Denver.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880921-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-88 1626EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s w BC-WeeklyFarm ADV25   09-21 0722</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Farm, ADV 25,0739</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sun, Sept. 25, or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Economists Say Job Paychecks More Important Than Ever to Farm
Families</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Donn Reimund cq. in 4th graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The financial health of farm families has been
aided dramatically in recent years by federal subsidies, but
Agriculture Department economists say a good job in town is the
real meal ticket for a growing number of those who live on the land.
   All told, the jobs and government payments helped push farm
household earnings ahead of the U.S. average in 1985 and again in
1986, the first time that has happened since the 1970s.
   The mainstay for many families has been off-farm income. The job
in town. A regular paycheck that is isolated from drought and the
whipsawing of commodity prices.
   ``Although many observers and analysts previously considered
off-farm employment as a transitional step to full-time farming
operation, off-farm employment is becoming more common as farm
operators and members of their households choose to pursue dual
careers,'' says Donn Reimund of the department's Economic Research
Service.
   The agency noted in a report last winter that off-farm incomes
were of growing importance to farm families and that the income gap
between farm and non-farm narrowed again in the mid-1980s after
widening since 1978.
   In the latest installment, reported in a forthcoming issue of
Farmline magazine, Reimund and his colleagues noted that the
incomes of farm households trailed the U.S. average for six
straight years before moving ahead in 1985 to an average of $29,436
against the national average for all households of $29,066, a 1
percent lead.
   The gap widened in 1986 to 11 percent as the farm average rose
to $34,246 per household, compared with $30,759 for the U.S.
average. Both were record levels.
   Department analysts attributed the rise in 1985 and 1986 to
lower production costs and higher direct government payments to
farmers, although increased incomes from off-farm jobs were also
factors.
   Federal payments to farmers were $8 billion in 1985 and rose to
$12 billion in 1986. Comparatively, in 1981, those were only $1.9
billion.
   But comparisons of average incomes do not explain income
distribution and can mask differences at the very high and low
levels. That is true of urban as well as farm families, but Reimund
said ``a higher percentage of farm operator households are below
the official povery level than are other households.''
   Only about 16 percent of the nation's farm families reported
receiving no off-farm income in 1986, based on USDA's annual Farm
Costs and Returns Survey.
   Mary Ahearn, another agency analyst, said that about half of the
households of farm operators in 1986 depended on off-farm sources
for two-thirds or more of their total cash income.
   These households were generally involved in small farming
operations, with sales of less than $40,000 a year, she said. On
the average, they reported a loss of $2,950 on farm operations in
1986 but earned $40,904 off the farm, resulting in a net cash
income of $37,954.
   Only 20 percent of the households in this group participated in
federal direct payment programs, and they received an average of
$6,380 each. Their small size precluded larger payments, because
federal subsidies are related to production.
   ``Until the 1970s, the nation's farm operator households lagged
behind the U.S. average in household incomes,'' the report said.
``Today, their incomes remain much more volatile than the steadily
rising U.S. average, but no longer are they always in the bottom
position.''
   Farm household income exceeded the U.S. average in eight of the
17 years, 1970 through 1986. Only two of those years _ 1985 and
1986 _ were in the '80s.
   Reimund said the first time was in 1972 as farm export markets
began to grow rapidly. In 1973, farm income shot up to an average
of $17,854 per household, 47 percent more than the U.S. average of
$12,157, a difference that has not been matched since.
   Has the trend continued in 1987 and 1988? Reimund said he had to
hedge a bit, particularly for this year's income comparisons.
   ``Last year was pretty good,'' he said. ``But 1988, it's a tough
one, with the drought and all. I guess we'll just have to wait and
see.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sun, Sept. 25 or Thereafter</NOTE>
