<2ND_LINE>BC-Campaign Charters, ADV 25,1034</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>For the Boys on the Plane, Sometimes the Excitement Is in the Air</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The reporters trailing George Bush could
overlook the smell of something burning aboard their Boeing 727,
but two days later when the pilot dumped fuel over Lake Michigan to
make an emergency landing, they'd had just about enough.
   Once on the ground in Chicago, they refused to reboard the Key
Air charter jet and scurried to make their own arrangements on
scheduled flights to the West Coast to catch up with the candidate,
who had flown on Air Force II.
   Key Air, meanwhile, trying to salvage its $1.8 million contract,
shadowed the Bush campaign with an empty airplane.
   The unexpected return to Chicago was prompted by concern about
flaps working properly.
   Mechanical troubles, aborted takeoffs, surprise government
inspections, the grounding of at least one plane, even a delay
caused by Secret Service agents poking holes in a plane when they
closed a door improperly, have marked this year's presidential
campaign trips.
   Among reporters, a skeptical lot under any circumstances,
there's been much chatter about safety aboard the chartered flights
which carry the press, campaign staff and candidates, except for
Bush who normally travels on Air Force II.
   The concerns were not eased after the Bush campaign dumped the
Key Air charter and temporarily hired United Airlines. On the first
United flight, an overheated engine prompted a pilot to abort a
takeoff as his Boeing 737 raced down a runway in Houston, Texas.
   ``Key Air, Key Air,'' came the sarcastic chant from the press
corps.
   The following week trouble struck Democratic presidential
nominee Michael Dukakis' campaign plane in Chicago. It's the same
plane he has flown all year and one aides say he particularly
favors, although members of the press have dubbed the stubby
20-year-old Boeing 737 ``Sky Pig'' because it can't make a
cross-country trip without landing for fuel.
   The plane, owned by Presidential Airways, was grounded after FAA
inspectors found several problems including a faulty emergency exit
light and a damaged vane that measures air flow and triggers the
alarm that would warn the pilots if their aircraft was about to
stall.
   The FAA inspection unleashed a controversy because of its
timing. Dukakis staffers wondered why inspectors showed up only 15
minutes before departure when the jet had been parked at the
airport all night. Dukakis had to cancel a campaign trip to Ohio.
   FAA officials denied any political motives and said the
inspectors had not been told they had so little time before the
scheduled departure. In the future ``we'll try to stay invisible,''
said Bob Goodrich, director of flight standards.
   Even for vice presidents, there are no guarantees. Once when
Vice President Spiro Agnew was on board, Air Force II was struck by
lightning and several years ago with Bush aboard it almost collided
with a small plane while landing in Seattle.
   News organizations reimburse the campaigns for the cost of the
charters with prices ranging from about 1{ times the cost of a
first class ticket to considerably more, depending on how many
people are on board. A seat on one coast-to-coast flights early in
the Bush campaign cost $5,000 because few reporters were aboard.
   Until recent years, the planes usually belonged to one of the
major airlines. But they no longer have the extra aircraft to
accommodate demands for charters.
   Recently when United took away its plane, Bush reporters were
told on the tarmac at Andrews Air Force Base near Washington they
had better make up their minds quickly about the replacement
airline, American Trans Air, because the Dukakis campaign was
negotiating for the plane as well.
   The charter airlines insist their safety record ranks favorably
with the major, regularly scheduled air carriers. The FAA agrees.
   ``I think it's unfortunate that these events (involving the Bush
press entourage) occurred. But mechanicals are sort of a way of
life,'' said Scott Andrews, a vice president of World Corp., the
owner of Key Air. He said his airline has a good maintenance record.
   World Corp., formerly World Airways when it was providing
scheduled air service, and its Key Air subsidiary has six DC-10s
and eight Boeing 727s carrying everything from a planeload of
tourists to rock bands.
   Flights on campaign charters over the years have never been
examples of decorum or _ for that matter _ strict compliance with
cabin safety regulations.
   ``People have been known to surf and ski down the aisles on
takeoff,'' says AP political writer Evans Witt. A favorite pastime
begun is the rolling of an orange down the aisle on takeoff to see
how far it gets before disappearing under a seat. Nancy Reagan used
to be a frequent participant.
   It also has not been unheard off for a flight attendant to be
hooted down during a preflight safety announcement.
   Some campaign veterans say the in-flight antics aren't as
rambunctious this year. They also suggest that this year's horror
stories pale when compared to some in campaigns past.
   Four years ago, a Lockheed Electra carrying Sen. John Glenn's
campaign flew into Sioux City, Iowa in a blinding snowstorm. On the
first approach the plane flew closer to the terminal than to the
runway, so Glenn, the former Marine fighter pilot and astronaut,
stuck his head into the cockpit to make sure the second landing was
more on target.
   Those covering Jesse Jackson's 1984 primary campaign still talk
about a trip on the same Electra from Washington to Dallas when it
was buffeted so severely by a storm that passengers were thrown
into the aisles. Upon landing Jackson knelt and kissed the ground,
vowing never to fly the plane again _ and didn't.
   Nine months later the same Electra, belonging to Galaxy
Airlines, crashed upon takeoff from the Reno, Nev., airport,
killing 68 people aboard. This time the plane was carrying a
Minnesota group returning from a weekend gambling excursion.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sun, Sept 25</NOTE>
