<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-88 1610EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-ShuttleCrew-Hilmers ADV25   09-21 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Shuttle Crew-Hilmers, ADV 25,0563</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Astronaut Dave Hilmers Says Space Flight Rewards Outweigh Risks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marine Lt. Col. Dave Hilmers says
the Challenger disaster made him realize the importance of
explaining to his family how he feels about being an astronaut
before he flew into space again.
   ``This is a dangerous world that we live in and I think that
everyone should be ready to tell the people that they love how they
feel and what they believe is important,'' said the former jet
pilot, who will help deploy a $100 million communications satellite
on the Discovery mission.
   ``Where your faith lies, what your beliefs are, what you want
them to accomplish in life _ all these sorts of things.''
   Hilmers said the rewards of being an astronaut outweigh any
risks involved and he feels privileged to be flying on the first
post-Challenger mission. But he acknowledged with a smile that his
wife, Lynn, sometimes may wish he had picked a different profession.
   Hilmers, 38, has two sons, Matthew, who will be 12 on Sept. 28,
and Daniel, 9.
   Hilmers grew up in DeWitt, Iowa, and graduated with a bachelor's
degree in mathematics, summa cum laude, from Cornell College in
1972. He earned a master's degree in electrical engineering in 1977
and the degree of electrical engineer from the U.S. Naval
Postgraduate School in 1978.
   Two years later, he was selected as an astronaut.
   His only other shuttle mission, launched in October 1985, was
the maiden voyage of the orbiter Atlantis. Hilmers was a mission
specialist on that flight, a classified Department of Defense
mission.
   He often jogs with his fellow Discovery crew members along the
backroads at the Johnson Space Center. Discovery Pilot Dick Covey
said Hilmers generally runs the most, about four miles.
   When he was asked to be part of the Discovery crew, Hilmers said
he felt no reluctance to accept.
   ``There was a big lump in my throat. When I was chosen, there
really was just a real sense of privilege,'' he said.
   Hilmers will take several Bible verses written on ribbons into
space for friends who have supported him with prayers, he said.
He'll also take several flags, including one from Texas.
   Like the other astronauts, Hilmers said the liftoff generally is
the most tense time of the mission.
   ``It's a very awesome two minutes,'' he said.
   When he first flew, he said he was so ``overcome by the physical
sensations'' that he didn't get much of a chance to think. This
time, he believes he will be concentrating more on his job.
   But he's sure he will think about Challenger, which exploded 73
seconds after takeoff.
   ``We're going to be remembering what happened back then. We're
going to be remembering the crew, our friends. We're going to
remember that something did happen in the first two minutes and
hopefully it's not going to happen again. But I don't think we're
going to be dwelling on that,'' he said.
   ``I think that when it gets right down to the last couple of
minutes, that we're going to be looking up at the sky and not
behind us.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sun, Sept. 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
