<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-88 1615EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-ShuttleCrew-Lounge ADV25   09-21 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Shuttle Crew-Lounge, ADV 25,0555</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Astronaut Mike Lounge Taking Hometown's Banner Into Space</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When astronaut Mike Lounge soars
into orbit aboard Discovery, he will carry a symbol of a bygone era
of transportation _ a picture of a wagon wheel.
   The wheel is displayed on a banner honoring the centennial of
his hometown of Burlington, Colo. It contains the signatures of
about 4,000 people, has a picture of a wagon wheel with a shuttle
orbiting it and says ``100 years of pioneers.''
   Lounge, who made his first shuttle flight three years ago aboard
Discovery, also will carry his wife's wedding ring, pins and
drawings and several cassettes of music on the shuttle, including a
``rap'' tape a teen-age friend made for him.
   The memory of the Challenger tragedy will add to the anxiety
astronauts always feel during the first few moments after launch,
Lounge said.
   ``I think the first 10 minutes of flight are always the ones
you're most tense because you're converting so much potential
energy in those solid rocket boosters into kinetic energy as you
get up above the atmosphere,'' he said in an interview. ``Once we
get off the solids, and the three main engines are running smoothly
and it gets real quiet, my heartbeat will probably go down quite a
bit.''
   Tanned and relaxed, the former Navy aviator is the lead
astronaut in charge of deploying the $100 million communications
satellite.
   His other flight, which launched Aug. 27, 1985, is described by
NASA as its most successful shuttle mission so far, with astronauts
deploying three satellites and repairing an ailing satellite.
   Lounge said there hasn't been much tension at home about the
upcoming mission. His wife, Kathryn Anne, is an engineer at the
Johnson Space Center and she understands ``the challenges as well
as I do.'' His family, including his children Shannon, 17, Kenneth,
7, and Kathy, 4, plan to be there for the liftoff.
   ``To my two little children who live at home, it hasn't become
real to them yet. We talk about going to Florida and (how) they get
to go watch Daddy launch and they get to go to Disney World and I'm
not sure which is the more important of the two.''
   But, seriously, Lounge said his children do understand what he
does.
   ``A couple of times my 4-year-old has talked about how `you're
going to go fly in the space shuttle, but it's not going to blow up
_ right?' So, she's remembering that image of Challenger,'' he said.
   ``But it's not like a cloud of anxiety that's following her
around. She wanted some reassurance and I reassured her and that
was OK because Daddy knows everything,'' he said, smiling.
   Lounge, a member of the Texas Air National Guard who flies with
his unit at least once a week, said he doesn't think much about the
risks and dangers.
   ``But it's characteristic of people that get into this kind of
profession _ that we're all bullet-proof. You can shoot at me but
you can't hit me, it might hit someone else but it won't hit me,''
he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sun, Sept. 25</NOTE>
