<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   09-21 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0514</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An improving trade deficit helped economic
growth remain strong in the second quarter despite the Farm Belt
drought, but inflation was more severe than previously believed,
the government says.
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday the gross national product
grew at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 3.0 percent in the
April-June period, compared to the earlier estimate of 3.3 percent.
   The GNP deflator, which measures inflation, rose at an annual
rate of 5.5 percent, instead of 5.1 percent as previously estimated.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corporations reported an 8.9 percent surge in
profits for the second quarter, the biggest increase in nearly five
years, the government announced.
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday that after-tax profits in
April, May and June jumped to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
$162.7 billion.
   Tuesday's report represents a downward revision from an estimate
of 11.5 percent. Still, it was the sharpest rise since an 11.4
percent gain in the third quarter of 1983.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retailers expect higher sales and prices as the
holiday season approaches, while business executives in general
foresee fatter profits in the final quarter of 1988, a private
report says.
   Dun & Bradstreet Corp. said Tuesday its survey of 1,500
executives found that although expectations had moderated along
with signs of a slowing economy, business executives were painting
the rosiest profit picture since 1984.
   Retailers have high expectations for holiday sales, the firm
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interco Inc.'s board has rejected a revised
$2.66 billion takeover offer and says the furniture and apparel
maker instead will pursue a major restructuring and
recapitalization program.
   Interco said Tuesday it had decided to sell its Ethan Allen
furniture subsidiary as part of the restructuring and declared a
special dividend of $25 a share in cash and securities.
   Interco is being pursued by an investment group headed by
brothers Steven and Mitchell Rales of Washington, D.C.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prospect of a bidding war over Kroger Co.
is looming as the investment firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. has
offered $4.6 billion for the supermarket operator, topping an offer
from Dart Group Corp. made the day before.
   Kohlberg Kravis _ which earlier this year outbid Dart for Stop &
Shop Cos. _offered Tuesday to pay $58.50 per share for Kroger. Dart
offered $55 a share on Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lafarge Corp., one of North America's biggest
producers of cement and building materials, has received an
unsolicited $1.47 billion cash takeover offer, but the company's
French parent says it won't sell.
   The offer came Tuesday from a group of private anonymous
investors. Lawrence Orbe, a New York attorney handling the matter,
said his clients were willing to pay $30 a share in cash for
Lafarge, which has about 49 million shares outstanding.
   France's Lafarge Coppee owns a 58 percent interest in the
company.
</TEXT>
