<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0511</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp. has advised its
stockholders to reject a sweetened $2.6 billion takeover bid from
Roy E. Disney's Shamrock Holdings Inc. and has moved to strengthen
its defenses.
   Polaroid's board of directors on Tuesday described the
$42-a-share offer as financially inadequate and not in the best
interest of the company and its stockholders.
   It was the second time Polaroid turned down a takeover bid from
Shamrock, a Burbank, Calif.-based television and radio concern.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Democrats have maneuvered to force a
vote on raising the $3.35 minimum wage for the first time in eight
years, stopping just short of accusing Republicans of filibustering
the issue in deference to presidential politics.
   Vice President George Bush's presidential campaign said Tuesday
that Bush likely would not unveil any specific minimum wage
proposal until after his debate next Sunday with Democratic nominee
Michael Dukakis.
   Senate Republican leaders, meanwhile, sought to tie action on
the minimum wage bill hostage to 30 federal judge nominations that
they said Democrats are delaying confirmation votes on.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banking's biggest trade group says $74 billion
is needed to clean up the ailing savings and loan industry and the
use of taxpayers funds ``now appears unavoidable.''
   The estimate Tuesday from the American Bankers Association,
which represents 95 percent of the nation's 13,500 commercial
banks, is higher than the largest government projections but well
within the estimates of private analysts.
   Proposals by some to use the $18 billion bank insurance fund to
help the S&L fund are ``unrealistic and unwise,'' the bankers'
group said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders who believe a proposed free
trade pact makes too many concessions to the United States hope to
dominate the upcoming election campaign with attacks on the accord.
   The Free Trade Agreement, negotiated by Conservative Prime
Minister Brian Mulroney and President Reagan, was passed Monday by
the U.S. Senate.
   The pact still must be approved by the non-elected Canadian
Senate, where the opposition Liberal Party has stalled passage of
the bill.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drought appears to have slowed the
recovery in farmland values, but appraisers think land prices will
rise at a healthy clip in 1989, the Agriculture Department says.
   Rural appraisers surveyed in August by the department's Economic
Research Service reported only a 1.2 percent increase nationally in
farmland values for May, June and July, compared with a 1.8 percent
gain in the first quarter of the year, the department said Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market posted a modest gain in lethargic trading
Tuesday. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks rose 6.40
points to close at 2,087.48.
   Gold prices rose abroad but retreated in New York, falling
toward the $400- a-troy-ounce level in active trading.
   The dollar was little changed in light foreign-exchange dealings.
   Bond prices rose slightly.
   Petroleum futures prices were mixed.
</TEXT>
