<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Prices Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC-related news has been put aside as the oil
futures market anticipates lower oil inventories stemming from last
week's hurricane-related disruptions.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the October contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, settled
31 cents higher at $15.04 a barrel Tuesday. Other contract months
closed lower.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for October delivery gained 0.19
cent to close at 44.43 cents a gallon, while other contract months
closed higher.
   The October wholesale heating oil contract lost 0.04 cent to
settle at 41.32 cents a gallon. Other heating oil contracts settled
mixed on the day.
   Analysts said Tuesday's late rally was led by last-minute
trading in advance of the October contract's expiration at the
close of the trading day, coupled with expectations that the
American Petroleum Institute's weekly statistics would show a
substantial drop in oil and gasoline stocks.
   The API report, released after the close of trading, indicated
U.S. crude oil stocks fell by 6.212 million barrels in the week
ended Sept. 16, while gasoline stocks fell by 2.58 million barrels.
   Last week's hurricane threat in the Gulf of Mexico closed
refineries and disrupted oil and gasoline production for several
days. Traders said the market was poised Tuesday for an API report
reflecting a larger-than-expected drop in inventories.
   Bud Degorgue, an oil broker with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.,
said there were market rumors speculating crude oil inventories
could be down by as much as 16 million barrels because of last
week's hurricane, although analysts did not expect stocks to be off
by more than 5 million to 6 million barrels.
   OPEC-related news was pushed to the back burner until after the
API report, traders said. Oil futures prices have fluctuated wildly
in recent weeks in anticipation of an Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries price committee meeting scheduled for next
Monday and Tuesday.
   The market has had mixed response to whether such a meeting
could lead to a gathering of all 13 OPEC members at a later date
and possible curtailment of the cartel's oil output.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
