<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessExpectations     09-21 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Expectations,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retailers Bullish on Economy for Holiday Season</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business executives expect profits to rise
during the final three months of this year, while retailers in
particular expect higher sales and prices during the crucial
holiday selling season, according to a private survey.
   Dun & Bradstreet Corp., a leading marketer of business
information, said its quarterly survey of 1,500 executives found
that although expectations had moderated along with signs of a
slowing economy, business executives were painting the rosiest
profit picture since 1984.
   ``Retailers are headed into the fourth quarter with high
expectations for the holiday sales season,'' said Joseph W. Duncan,
corporate economist and chief statistician for Dun & Bradstreet.
   ``At the same time, the outlook among durable manufacturers
remains strong, so we should close out the year on an economic high
note.''
   However, the survey indicated manufacturers and wholesalers were
less optimistic about the economy than retailers, as sustained
consumer demand and increased exports have pushed the manufacturing
sector to full capacity.
   The survey was conducted during the final half of August.
   Overall, the report said Dun & Bradstreet's sales optimism index
fell slightly for the fourth quarter, to 70 from 73 in the third
quarter. But among retailers, the index rose to 72 from 65.
   The index is calculated by subtracting the percentage of
respondents expecting decreases in a category from the percentage
expecting increases.
   An index measuring expectations for increased profits rose to
67, the highest level since the fourth quarter of 1984, and up from
63 last quarter. Retailers were the most optimistic, with a
10-point increase from the third quarter to 69. The index among
wholesalers slipped to 63 from 64 and among manufacturers to 68
from 70.
   While the overall index of expectations for higher prices fell
to 42 from 44, retailers are forecasting prices will climb during
the year's final quarter, with their index rising from 39 to 45,
the report said.
   In the category for employment prospects, the index decreased to
22 from 25. The retail sector index rose one point to 14 while
wholesaler and manufacturer indexes declined.
</TEXT>
