<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-88 0206EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Polaroid-Shamrock Bjt   09-21 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Polaroid-Shamrock, Bjt,0666</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polaroid Rejects Latest Shamrock Bid As Inadequate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Shamrock Holdings Inc. says
the company will continue its unwanted bid for Polaroid Corp.,
despite Polaroid's rejection of a sweetened $2.6 billion offer and
proposal for a defensive stock issue.
   Polaroid's board of directors on Tuesday rejected Shamrock's $42
a share offer as inadequate and urged shareholders not to tender
their stock.
   The instant photography company also indicated in a filing with
the Securities and Exchange Commission that it had begun
preliminary negotiations regarding a possible issuance of preferred
stock to third parties, a defensive move that would make a takeover
more difficult.
   In a letter to Polaroid's directors Tuesday, Shamrock President
Stanley P. Gold said he was disappointed with the rejection, which
marked the second time Polaroid has turned down an offer from
Shamrock, a Burbank, Calif.-based radio and television concern.
Gold also reiterated Shamrock's willingness to raise its offer
further if it believed an increase was warranted.
   ``We believe that your continued unwillingness to meet with us
is contrary to the best interests of Polaroid's stockholders,''
Gold wrote.
   He also claimed Polaroid's stock proposal was intended simply to
impede the Shamrock offer.
   ``We will therefore make every effort to stop any such placement
and will hold Polaroid directors and management and the purchaser
of any such securities responsible for participating in what we
percieve is an unlawful scheme. Furthermore, any such placement
will not achieve its purpose since it will not divert us from our
efforts to acquire Polaroid,'' Gold said.
   Polaroid stock fell $1.12{ a share to close at $40.12{ in New
York Stock Exchange composite trading.
   ``It's a very good defensive move,'' Alex Henderson, a
photography analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities in New York,
said of the stock plan.
   ``The question now is, what is the next step?'' he said. ``The
ball's in Shamrock's court now.''
   Polaroid last month rejected an unsolicited offer from Shamrock
that would have paid stockholders $40 a share plus 40 percent of
the eventual award in Polaroid's $5.7 billion patent infringement
lawsuit against Eastman Kodak Co. Analysts valued the offer at
about $44 a share, assuming a $1 billion settlement in the Kodak
case.
   Shamrock, which is owned by the family of Roy E. Disney, nephew
of the late animator Walt Disney, has indicated that if its bid
succeeded it would drop Polaroid's fledgling venture into 35mm
film, sell most of the company's undeveloped real estate, narrow
the company's manufacturing facilities and simplify Polaroid's
research and development to focus on core businesses.
   Shamrock's offer was contingent on the invalidation of
Polaroid's recent issuance of 9.7 million shares to a new employee
stock ownership plan, a move Polaroid made early in its attempt to
block Shamrock.
   The hostile bid values the company at $2.6 billion, based on the
62 million shares that would be outstanding if the issue of 9.7
million shares is rolled back.
   In a statement, I. MacAllister Booth, Polaroid president and
chief executive officer, said the board was advised by its
financial adviser, Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., that the latest
offer from Shamrock was inadequate.
   Booth said Polaroid's own plan to restructure the company, which
includes massive job cuts, would benefit stockholders more.
   ``The foundation of our plan is a carefully targeted
reorganization and streamlining of operations to focus more sharply
on key growth areas,'' Booth said. ``This will result in a
strengthening of the company's competitive posture, improved future
operating prospects for the company and a 15 percent reduction in
the number of Polaroid employees in the United States.''
   Booth said Polaroid will save about $100 million a year as a
result of its restructuring.
   Shamrock has filed suit in Delaware, where Polaroid is
incorporated, to block the employee stock ownership plan. A trial
has been set for next month.
</TEXT>
