<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Interco Bjt   09-21 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Interco, Bjt,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interco Rejects Revised Takeover Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interco Inc. says it will sell its Ethan Allen
furniture subsidiary as part of a major restructuring program aimed
at stopping a $2.66 billion hostile takeover from a Washington,
D.C., investment group.
   Interco, a major maker of furniture and apparel, said Tuesday
that its board of directors rejected as inadequate a revised
$72-a-share bid from Cardinal Acquisition Corp., headed by the
brothers Steven and Mitchell Rales of Washington.
   The board instead approved a previously announced restructuring.
It includes paying a special dividend of $25 per share to
shareholders on Nov. 7 and selling the Ethan Allen unit.
   Interco suspended the regular quarterly dividend pending
completion of the restructuring program, which it valued at $76 a
share.
   But Wall Street seemed unimpressed. In composite trading on the
New York Stock Exchange, Interco shares closed down $1.12{ to
$69.25 Tuesday.
   Interco said the board had been told by its financial adviser,
Wasserstein, Perella and Co., that Cardinal Acquisition's latest
offer was inadequate to shareholders.
   ``Recognizing the bright prospects for Interco's leading
consumer brands, we believe it is not an opportune time to sell the
company,'' Interco Chairman Harvey Saligman said in a statement
Tuesday.
   Interco has rejected the Rales' overtures since they first
offered in July to acquire the company by paying $64 for each of
the 37 million shares outstanding. The Rales already own about 8.7
percent of Interco's shares.
   On Monday, the Rales made public a letter that had been sent to
Interco warning against an anti-takeover restructuring. The
response was to an Interco filing with the Securities and Exchange
Commission last week in which the company disclosed the possibility
of a defensive restructuring.
   Interco said in its filing that it had retained a group of
bankers to explore how to finance the restructuring.
   Selling Ethan Allen could make Interco, whose products also
include London Fog outerwear, Florsheim and Converse shoes and
Broyhill furniture, an unattractive acquisition target.
   Interco said that if Cardinal Acquisition was interested it
would be provided the same information on Ethan Allen under the
same terms and conditions as other potential buyers.
   The Rales had said in their letter that they wanted a chance to
bid on assets that Interco might put up for sale.
   ``In order to avoid any unfortunate consequences should you
decide to pursue asset sales, we expect to be consulted well in
advance so that we can evaluate the effect that any such sale would
have on our offer,'' the Rales' letter also said.
   The group did not elaborate on what the ``unfortunate
consequences'' might be, but presumably it was warning of legal
action or a shareholder proxy fight to block a restructuring plan
that would spoil its strategy.
   As part of the special dividend portion of its restructuring,
Interco said it plans to pay shareholders of record on Oct. 13 $14
in cash and $11 in securities.
   The board plans to announce additional distributions of cash,
securities or share repurchases ``as the company progresses with
its divestiture and cost savings program,'' Interco said.
</TEXT>
