<2ND_LINE>PM-Chicago-Japanese Investment,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Buy Into Chicago Real Estate Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese life insurance company has bought a 20
percent stake in LaSalle Partners Ltd., one of the nation's largest
privately held corporate real-estate firms.
   Dai-Ichi Mutual Life Insurance Co., Japan's second-largest life
insurance concern, acquired its interest in the Chicago real estate
firm for an undisclosed amount of money, the Chicago Tribune
reported in today's editions.
   Officials at LaSalle Partners would neither confirm nor deny the
purchase agreement on Tuesday, but the Tribune quoted unidentified
real-estate sources as saying the deal was signed June 30.
   The transaction was believed to be only the second direct
Japanese investment in a Chicago real-estate brokerage and only the
third such investment in the United States, the Tribune said.
   Last year, Orient Leasing Co. Ltd. of Tokyo bought a 23.3
percent stake in Rubloff Inc., another Chicago commercial
real-estate firm, and in December 1986, Nomura Securities Corp.
acquired a 50 percent interest in Eastdil Realty Inc., of New York.
   Industry sources said the deal with Dai-Ichi would broaden
LaSalle's capital, enabling it to expand its corporate real
estate-service business, and provide the Chicago company with
direct access to Japanese investors.
</TEXT>
