<2ND_LINE>PM-Consolidated Gold Fields, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minorco Launches Takeover Bid For Consolidated Gold Fields</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Fixes spelling of `conglomerate' and `immediately' in lead.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A South African-controlled gold conglomerate today
offered to buy Consolidated Gold Fields PLC for about $4.9 billion
in Britain's largest-ever takeover attempt, but Consolidated
immediately rejected the bid.
   Consolidated said the cash-and-stock offer by Minorco SA, based
in Luxembourg and run by two South African mining companies, was
``lacking financial justification'' and ``devoid of commercial
logic.''
   ``The proposals announced show that Minorco will be forced to
begin dismembering Gold Fields both to help finance the bid and in
recognition of the regulatory and commercial problems associated
with South African control,'' Gold Fields Chairman Rudolph Agnew
said in a statement.
   The offer would be the largest takeover of a publicly held
British company, surpassing Nestle SA's $4.3 billion acquisiton of
confectioner Rowntree PLC earlier this year.
   Minorco, controlled by Anglo American Corp. of South Africa and
De Beers Consolidated Mines Ltd., currently owns 29 percent of
Consolidated Gold Fields. On London's Stock Exchange, Gold Fields'
shares quickly shot above the takeover offer price to 14.08 pounds,
or $23.65 a share, up from Tuesday's closing price of 10.78 pounds,
or $18.11.
   Minorco said the bid fits in with its strategy to become a
worldwide natural resources group with direct operating control of
its activities. Gold Fields is one of the largest gold producers in
the world.
   The Gold Fields stake ``represents too large a proportion of
Minorco's assets to remain a passive investment,'' the company said.
   Minorco said that if successful, it would immediately begin
negotiations on the sale of Gold Field's 38 percent holding in Gold
Fields South Africa and would review Gold Field's 49.3 percent
stake in Newmont Mining Corp. of New York.
   Minorco's offer includes about $31.92 in cash and one new
Minorco share for every two Gold Fields shares it doesn't already
own.
   A successful bid by Minorco would result in an increase in the
number of its own outstanding shares by about 47 percent and
effectively reduce the combined holdings of the company's two major
shareholders to a minority stake.
   The companies issued a joint statement supporting Minorco's bid.
</TEXT>
