<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market edged upward today, bolstered
by some encouragement over the latest news on inflation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 3.74 to 2,091.22 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 6 to 5 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 427 up, 354 down and
561 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 18.53 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Activity was curtailed somewhat by the absence of investors
observing the Jewish holiday Yom Kippur.
   The Labor Department reported this morning that the consumer
price index rose 0.4 percent in August, matching its July increase.
   The latest figure was in line with advance estimates on Wall
Street, and thus did not stir up much excitement.
   Still, brokers said there was some relief at the suggestion in
the data that inflation wasn't gathering much momentum.
   Among actively traded blue chips, American Express rose [ to
28|; General Electric added [ to 42~; International Business
Machines rose [ to 112~, and American Telephone & Telegraph was
unchanged at 26{.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained .17 to 152.61. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down .35 at 298.28.
   On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 6.40 points to
2,087.48.
   Advancing issues outpaced declines by about 8 to 5 among issues
listed on the NYSE, with 866 up, 581 down and 504 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 142.22 million shares, against 135.77
million in the previous session.
