<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 2ndLd-Writethru   09-21 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consumer Prices Up, Housing Construction Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with reports on personal income
and consumer spending. Picks up 6th graf pvs, The Commerce ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer prices rose 0.4 percent in August due to higher costs
for food, shelter and gasoline, although inflation remained under
control, according to a government report released today.
   Meanwhile, the government also reported that housing
construction fell 3.3 percent last month and personal income rose a
modest 0.2 percent, the least in eight months. Consumer spending
rose a brisker 0.5 percent.
   In its Consumer Price Index for August, the Labor Department
said last month's increase was equivalent to an annual inflation
rate of 5.2 percent, the same as in July. Higher rents and gasoline
prices in large part replaced food as the sharpest spurs to higher
prices, the department said.
   Shelter costs, reflecting higher rates for hotel and motel
rooms, were up 0.6 percent, the steepest gain in seven months. Food
and beverage prices were up 0.5 percent last month while energy
prices jumped 0.9 percent.
   In its housing report, the Commerce Department said a steep drop
in apartment construction more than offset a modest gain in
single-family home building. The decline followed gains of 1.4
percent in July and 5.2 percent in June.
   As in June and July, personal income was held back by declines
in subsidy payments to farmers. In an apparent indication of the
drought's impact, farm income excluding subsidies fell $3.2 billion
in August.
   With spending rising faster than income, the personal savings
rate edged downward in August to 3.9 percent.
   The Commerce Department reported Tuesday that the gross national
product grew at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 3.0 percent in
the April-June period, slower than the 3.4 percent expansion rate
in the first quarter, but nonetheless brisk.
   If not for the summer drought, second-quarter growth would have
been a more robust 3.9 percent.
   The government's report also showed inflation picking up during
the second quarter. One price measure tied to the GNP rose at the
fastest pace in nearly six years and was more than triple the
first-quarter rate.
   The GNP deflator, which reflects changes in buying patterns as
well as prices, rose at an annual rate of 5.5 percent in the second
quarter, compared with 1.7 percent in the first quarter. It was the
biggest jump since the third quarter of 1982.
   The various changes left the GNP, after adjusting for inflation,
at an annual level of $3.99 trillion in the second quarter, $29.1
billion higher than the January-March period.
   In another report, the Commerce Department said after-tax
profits by corporations surged 8.9 percent in the second quarter to
an annual rate of $162.7 billion, up from a 2.5 percent annual rate
of increase in the first quarter. It was the most profitable
quarter since the July-September period of 1983.
   A private report issued Tuesday said the profit picture should
continue to brighten in the fourth quarter. Dun & Bradstreet Corp.,
a leading marketer of business information, said its quarterly
survey of 1,500 executives found retailers the most upbeat.
   ``Retailers are headed into the fourth quarter with high
expectations for the holiday sales season,'' said Joseph W. Duncan,
corporate economist and chief statistician for Dun & Bradstreet.
   ``At the same time, the outlook among durable manufacturers
remains strong, so we should close out the year on an economic high
note.''
   The survey was conducted during the final half of August.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880921-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-88 2147EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f PM-OntheMoney Adv22   09-21 0851</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-On the Money, Adv 22,0876</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Thursday Sept. 22 and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Pre-Cut, Do-It-Yourself Homebuilder Aims For Those Priced Out Of
Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PLYMOUTH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As more Americans find themselves priced
out of the housing market, do-it-yourself home building could get a
taste of the good old days when thousands cut costs by raising
their own roofs.
   One company in the business, Miles Homes, believes the concept
of ``sweat equity'' still has some attraction, particularly among
consumers with annual incomes of less than $60,000.
   The company's biggest years were in the late 1970s, when it sold
do-it-yourself packages to as many as 2,200 people a year, many of
whom lived in then-booming Texas.
   Having taken some hard licks during the recession, Miles is now
happy to sell 800 homes a year. But the company is optimistic about
the future.
   ``This is not our best year, but we expect 1989 to improve,''
said Richard Cornwall, president and chief operating officer of
Miles Homes.
   The real heyday for do-it-yourself home construction in this
country was from 1900 to 1940, when two of the biggest kit-home
manufacturers were Sears Roebuck & Co. and Montgomery Ward,
according to research published earlier this year by Tab Books Inc.
of Blue Ridge Summit, Pa.
   Sears alone sold more than 100,000 kit homes from 1900 until the
start of World War II, when all domestic construction came to a
virtual standstill, according to Tab.
   It wasn't until the late 1960s that a resurgence in the
do-it-yourself attitude and an upswing in construction costs caused
kit homes to become popular again, Tab says.
   Since that time, the industry has grown to the point where about
20 percent of the new single-family homes built annually in the
United States have some degree of owner involvement, according to
the National Association of Home Builders.
   The Build Your Own Home Directory says about 138,000 Americans
built their own houses last year.
   Currently there are more than 2,000 kit-house manufacturers and
dealers nationwide, according to the Tab research.
   Although Cornwall admits Miles' share of the market is small, he
said Miles is one of the few companies in the country offering a
complete package for the do-it-yourselfer: land evaluations,
blueprints, materials, construction loan money and mortgage
financing.
   Under new owner Peter DeGeorge, who paid Meriden, Conn.-based
Insilco Corp. about $100 million for the company in April, Miles
has pulled in its territorial reins so that its principal markets
are in the Midwest and along the Eastern seaboard.
   Cornwall said Miles makes much of its money off the package of
pre-cut materials used in the construction process, but the
company's financing arm also profits when customers make good on
the three-year construction loans that are at the heart of the
sales pitch.
   Dave Dunnigan, publicity director for Miles, said 65 percent of
the customers are first-time homebuyers, many of them with annual
incomes of $25,000 to $60,000 a year who often do not have enough
savings to make a big down payment.
   Land costs not included, Miles will finance the purchase price
of its homes, which range from $25,000 to $65,000, for up to 36
months around market rates. No down payment on materials is
required, but an appraisal fee of $250 is required upon credit
approval. Payments on the three-year loan cover interest only and
at the end of the three years the construction loan balance is due
in full and usually is paid through the use of a mortgage, which
can be obtained from Miles.
   ``We've front-ended so much money out of our pocket, the
customers are usually in a good position,'' said Scott Gerber,
marketing manager. ``But most people will not come out ahead unless
they are involved in building it.''
   Ideally, if the customer does enough of the construction and the
home is built in a location that has value, the result will be a
structure that is worth more than it cost to build it.
   But, as Gerber said, ``we have people whose expectations aren't
met.''
   Indeed, in April 1978 the Federal Trade Commission ordered Miles
to stop making ``false, misleading and deceptive'' claims related
to the construction process. For instance, the company used to
advertise that the only skill required for assembly was ``the
ability to drive a nail or use a hammer.''
   Dunnigan said the company has long since made the corrections
and no other action has been taken by the FTC.
   Now when customers do not come out ahead, it is usually because
they added a luxury item like a whirlpool bath that was not called
for in the blueprints.
   Only a handful of people have walked away from their houses as
they were under construction, Gerber said. Those who have
frustrations in the process can turn to company experts for advice.
   The sweat, by the way, still produces some equity. The Council
of American Building Officials says consumers can cut home
construction expenses by 25 percent to 50 percent depending on how
much labor they do themselves.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday Sept. 22</NOTE>
