<HEAD>Soybean Futures Open Higher; Grains Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices opened moderately higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade in a technical recovery from
the low levels of the past few days. Grain futures were mixed.
   Active European markets for soybean products and a large
purchase of U.S. soybean oil by Pakistan added further support to
soybean prices, analysts siad.
   Wheat and corn futures were mixed in early trading with the
strength provided by a growing line-up of export bids. Reports of
quality problems with some newly harvested Illinois corn were
another bullish factor, analysts said.
   But overall gains were limited by selling linked to the
advancing corn and soybean harvest, said Walter Spilka, a grain
market analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. in New York.
   `We're slowly getting into the harvesting season and these
markets have a hard time sustaining any momentum to the upside as
long as buyers know that just around the corner there's going to be
some good supplies coming onto the market,'' he said.
   In early trading, wheat was 2 cents lower to 1{ cents higher
with the contract for delivery in September at $4.06 a bushel; corn
was \ cent lower to } cent higher with September at $2.74{ a
bushel; oats were 1 cent lower to { cent higher with September at
$2.51 a bushel; soybeans were 3{ cents to 7 cents higher with
September at $8.24 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .45 cent lower to .30 cent higher with October
at 69.02 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .17 cent to .65 cent
lower with September at 80.05 cents a pound; hogs were .45 cent
lower to .33 cent higher with October at 38.55 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .15 cent to .35 cent lower with February
at 59.42 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures finished higher on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
