<2ND_LINE>PM-Personal Income, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0057,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Income Gain Smallest in 8 Months; Spending Up Briskly</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs White House reaction before last graf pvs;
Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans' personal income rose a modest 0.2
percent in August, the weakest gain in eight months, while consumer
spending was up at a slightly brisker 0.5 percent rate, the
government reported today.
   The Commerce Department said that the small $7.2 billion gain in
income last month to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $4.08
trillion followed strong increases of 0.7 percent in July and 0.6
percent in June.
   Personal consumption spending, which includes everything except
interest payments on debt, rose 0.5 percent in August following a
0.3 percent gain in July and a 1.3 percent jump in June, the
biggest in nearly a year.
   As in June and July, personal income was held back by declines
in subsidy payments to farmers. The payments shrank $6.2 billion in
August and $6.1 billion in July. However, in an apparent impact
indication of the drought, farm income excluding subsidies fell
$3.2 billion in August, compared with $700 million in July.
   Wages and salries, a key component of personal income, were up a
modest 0.3 percent in August compared with a healthy 1.0 percent
gain in July. That's consistent with an earlier report from the
Labor Department showing unemployment rising from 5.4 percent in
July to 5.6 percent last month.
   Disposable, or after tax, income was up 0.2 percent in August
and 0.6 percent a month earlier.
   With spending rising slightly faster than income, the personal
savings rate _ savings as a percentage of after-tax personal income
_ edged down from 4.2 percent in July to 3.9 percent in August. The
savings rate this year has been averaging around 4 percent, up from
3.2 percent last year.
   At the White House, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
commented:
   ``Growth of consumer expenditures continues and the personal
savings rate remains well above last year's average of 3.2 percent.
The savings rate for the last three months has been 4 percent.''
   The spending gain was strongest for services, up $12.7 billion
following a $9.6 billion rise in July. Purchases of non-durable
goods rose $2.5 billion following a $3.6 billion increase a month
earlier. However, purchases of durable goods, ``big ticket'' items
expected to last three or more years, fell $200 million after
falling $10.9 billion in July.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
