<HEAD>London Shares Up 24.7 Points</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rose strongly Wednesday, boosted by
the announcement of Britain's largest-ever takeover bid.
   Before official trading began, Minorco S.A. launched its hostile
offer for the 71 percent of Consolidated Gold Fields PLC, which it
doesn't already own in a cash and stock offer valuing the whole
company at 2.9 billion pounds ($4.9 billion).
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index finished 24.7
points, or 1.4 percent, better at 1,796.8.
   The 100-share index surged as much as 25.8 points at one point.
   Several dealers said they thought the index would break the
psychologically important 1,800 barrier Thursday, which might boost
sentiment.
   Volume was relatively strong, as 438.6 million shares changed
hands, compared with Tuesday's volume of 309.2 million shares.
   The Financial Times 30-share index was up 13.9 points at 1,443.8
at the close.
   The Financial Times 500-share index rose 10.22 points to close
at 1,012.12.
