<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-88 1444EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     09-21 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gold Tumbles, Dollar Slightly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold prices slumped as much as $10 an ounce
Wednesday and bullion dealers said it was poised to fall below $400
an ounce for the first time in 18 months.
   The dollar strengthened in quiet trading, boosted by a few large
corporate orders.
   Bullion dealers said bearish sentiment was pushing gold down.
Eased concern about inflationary trends worldwide has depressed the
metal, which investors historically have used as a hedge against
inflation.
   Interest rate hikes in late August, aimed at curbing inflation,
have ``broken the bull trend in gold'' and forced a change in
people's perceptions, said analyst Julian Baring of brokers James
Capel and Co.
   One dealer said: ``The impetus is there for it to go lower, but
a part-correction is still likely before it breaks through 400
dollars.''
   A correction is market terminology for a temporary move in the
opposite direction.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $401.50 a troy ounce,
compared with late Tuesday's $410.00.
   In Zurich, gold fell to $400.50 compared with $410.50 late
Tuesday.
   Gold last closed below $400 an ounce on March 20, 1987 in London
and on March 19, 1987 in Zurich.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold dropped $7.74 to close at $405.38.
   Silver bullion prices fell in London to $6.22 a troy ounce,
compared with Tuesday's $6.36.
   Most foreign currency dealers have refrained from trading
dollars, determined to avoid taking big positions ahead of the
Saturday meeting of finance ministers from the leading
industrialized democracies.
   Few participants are expecting anything out of the meeting other
than another reaffirmation of the ministers' desire for stable
exchange rates.
   One chief corporate dealer said a few big orders out of the
Middle East early in the day helped move the dollar above 1.8700
marks. The momentum pushed the dollar to a session high of 1.8780
marks before it retreated.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.6755 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.6865 late Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday:
1.8748 West German marks, up from 1.8641; 1.5833 Swiss francs, up
from 1.5740; 6.3710 French francs, up from 6.3385; 2.1145 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.1075; 1,395.60 Italian lire, up from 1,391.50;
1.2183 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2203.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar edged up 0.03 yen to a closing 134.18 yen. Later in
London, it was quoted at 134.25 yen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880921-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-88 1757EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Citizens-Scotland     09-21 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Citizens-Scotland,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Citizens Shareholders Ok Acquisition By Scotland Bank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citizens Financial Group Inc.'s
shareholders overwhelmingly approved the sale of the company to
Royal Bank of Scotland, the sixth-largest bank in Britain, for $440
million in cash.
   If the $30.50-a-share deal is approved by regulators, it would
be the first foreign takeover of a major New England bank and
transform Citizens into the top tier size-wise of the regional
banking companies in the Northeast.
   Citizens, whose best-known business is Citizens Savings Bank,
has assets of $2.6 billion, while Royal Bank of Scotland has about
$35 billion in assets.
   Citizens said 82 percent of its shareholders approved the
acquisition at a special meeting Tuesday, while 2 percent were
opposed and the rest refrained from voting.
   ``It was gratifying,'' said Citizens President George Graboys.
   He said that no major changes were planned after the merger.
   The deal still must be approved by the Federal Reserve Board and
the Massachusetts Board of Bank Incoporation. The Massachusetts
approval is needed because Citizens recently bought Fairhaven
Savings Bank in that state.
</TEXT>
