<1ST_LINE>r f BC-KDIMerger     09-21 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-KDI Merger,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>KDI Board Approves Merger with Management Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The board of directors of KDI Corp. has agreed
to sign a definitive merger agreement with a management group for
$19 a share, or about $184.3 million, the company announced
Wednesday.
   The merger agreement with KD Holdings Corp., a new company to be
formed by Wasserstein, Perella Partners L.P.; KDI Chairman Eugene
Cafiero; and a group of KDI senior management, calls for a cash
tender offer of $19 a share for all of KDI's 9.7 million
outstanding shares.
   KDI, based in Cincinnati, is a diversified manufacturer of
electronic and electrical components, swimming pool and pool
equipment products and custom engineered products.
   Cafiero said conditions have been attached to the offer,
including the tendering of 60 percent of KDI's outstanding shares
and receipt of definitive financing commitments.
   Once the merger is completed, holders of shares not purchased in
the tender offer also will receive $19 a share in cash.
   The buyout group also said it has signed agreements to purchase
49 percent of KDI's outstanding shares from Ariadne Australia Ltd.
and its affiliates.
   A special committee of KDI non-management directors unanimously
approved the agreement. It also ordered company management and its
adviser, Salomon Brothers Inc., to be available to accept inquiries
from any other parties interested in buying the company.
   Merrill Lynch & Co. Inc. has committed to provide as much as
$105 million in bridge financing for the acquisition. The financing
will be repaid through a public or private offering of senior
subordinated notes, the company said.
   Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co. also has committed up to $150
million in senior acquisition financing and $20 million in working
capital.
   The management group and Wasserstein, Perella have agreed to
provide the equity portion of the financing.

</TEXT>
