<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-88 1902EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CardBattle     09-21 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Card Battle,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blue Mountain Accuses Hallmark Of Delaying Tactics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOULDER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blue Mountain Arts Inc., which is battling
greeting card industry giant Hallmark Cards Inc. over the look of
its cards, on Wednesday asked the U.S. Supreme Court to deny
Hallmark's request for a review of the case.
   Hallmark has asked the U.S. Supreme Court to review an
injunction affirmed by the U.S. 10th Circuit Court of Appeals in
Denver that prohibits the Kansas City-based company from producing
and marketing the cards that resemble Blue Mountain Arts' cards
pending a trial on the dispute.
   But Blue Mountain Arts submitted a plea to the high court to
reject the proposed review, and accused Hallmark of trying to delay
the trial, now scheduled for Jan. 2, 1989.
   ``Hallmark is engaging in piracy not competition,'' said Bob
Gall, general manager for the Boulder-based Blue Mountain Arts.
``Like a pirate ship with a hundred guns, Hallmark's army of
lawyers are trying to prove that might makes right.''
   The dispute developed when Hallmark produced a line of cards
like Blue Mountain Arts' _ both featured watercolor decorations and
long free-verse poetry with mostly personal messages.
   Blue Mountain brought a lawsuit against Hallmark for copying its
product, and after testimony in a Denver federal court the
injunction was issued against Hallmark. The appeals court in Denver
later upheld the injunction pending the scheduled trial, but
Hallmark wants the U.S. Supreme Court to step into the case.
   Its request for the action claimed that the injunction was the
equivalent of granting Blue Mountain Arts the exclusive rights to a
particular artistic style of card, arguing that the decision was in
direct conflict with the Constitution and with the Copyright Act.
   ``Hallmark argues that it may counterfeit the appearance of
competitive products with impunity,'' Blue Mountain said in its
filing. ``Contrary to Hallmark's assertion, Hallmark does not need
to copy Blue Mountain's cards in order to compete.''
   Gall said the request was mailed to the U.S. Supreme Court on
Wednesday.
   Hallmark spokesman Steve Doyal said the company's general
response was a reflection of its petition.
   ``Our petition is simple and straightforward,'' he said. ``We
question the constitutionality of granting Blue Mountain perpetual
exclusive rights to an idea or artistic style.
   ``They are seeking a monopoly and we believe that is unfair and
anti-competitive,'' he said.
   He said the company sees the issue as completely separate from
the scheduled trial, for which its attorneys are preparing at this
time.
</TEXT>
