<HEAD>Crop Markets Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean and wheat futures prices closed higher
Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade, but corn finished mixed in
a day of lackluster trading dominated by technical factors.
   The moderate gains in the soybean market were partly due to
forecasts for harvest-slowing showers in the Midwest and active
trading of soybean meal in Europe, analysts said.
   ``But mostly the soybean market has been pounded so hard after
hitting the $9 (a bushel) level that from a technical viewpoint
we're due for some bottom picking, just to see if it'll bounce back
up,'' said Walter Spilka, a grain analyst with Smith Barney, Harris
Upham & Co. in New York.
   September soybean complex futures went off the board at 12:01
p.m. CDT. The September soybean contract expired at $8.27{ a
bushel, up 7 cents.
   Wheat futures advanced marginally, reflecting consolidation of
the market after Tuesday's sharp gains, Spilka said.
   The corn market enjoyed some spillover buying from the soybean
pit but the gains were slight.
   At the close, wheat was \ cent lower to 1 cent higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $4.05 a bushel; corn was 1}
cents lower to 2} cents higher with September at $2.76{ a bushel;
oats were 3{ cents lower to 1 cent higher with September at $2.49 a
bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to 7 cents higher with November at
$8.37 a bushel.
