<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Sumita-Rates     09-21 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sumita-Rates,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sumita Says Japan Not Bowing To Pressure on Rates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Japan's central bank denied Wednesday
that Japan was being pressured by its allies to keep interest rates
low and said the bank would raise its key discount rate whenever it
felt such a move was necessary.
   Satoshi Sumita, governor of the Bank of Japan, made the comment
at a news conference when he was asked about market speculation
that Japan's benchmark rate was being held down because of
international pressure.
   Sumita said the bank would not hesitate to take action on
interest rates to defend the prevailing price stability in the
country.
   There had been expectations that the Bank of Japan might push up
its discount rate following increases in key lending rates in the
United States and some Western European countries. But the bank
held the rate at 2.5 percent.
   The currency markets briefly pushed up the yen against the
dollar following Sumita's remarks, but then the yen slipped back.
   ``People at first thought the Bank of Japan might raise the
discount rate and sold dollars,'' said one dealer. ``On further
reflection they realized that Sumita didn't say anything he had't
said before.''
</TEXT>
