<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     09-21 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Strengthens Slightly, Gold Slumps Below $400</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose mildly against most key
currencies Wednesday, but analysts attributed the strength to
internal market influences and said trading remained light because
of the Yom Kippur Jewish holiday.
   Gold prices tumbled worldwide, falling through the
$400-a-troy-ounce level in the United States for the first time
since early last year. Republic National Bank of New York quoted
bullion at $396.35 an ounce, down $8.15 from its level late Tuesday.
   Currency analysts said the dollar's behavior reflected technical
strategies among professional money brokers and was not a response
to outside news.
   Commerce Department reports on August inflation, personal income
and housing construction had no impact on foreign-exchange
dealings, they said.
   In Tokyo, the dollar edged up 0.03 yen to 134.18 yen. Later in
London, it was quoted at 134.25 yen. By the time trading ended in
New York the dollar fetched 134.29 yen, up from 134.08 yen late
Tuesday.
   The British pound weakened against the dollar in London, falling
to $1.6755 from $1.6865 late Tuesday. Later in New York the pound
fetched $1.6737, vs. $1.6817 late Tuesday.
   Other late-dollar rates in New York vs. levels late Tuesday:
1.8744 West German marks, up from 1.8669; 1.5820 Swiss francs, up
from 1.5767; 1.2158 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2183; 6.3650
French francs, up from 6.3450; and 1,395.75 Italian lire, up from
1,389.00.
   Gold prices dropped as much as $10 an ounce in Europe and
flirted with $400, later breaking through that level in active U.S.
trading. John Jonat, a trader at Deak International Trading (U.S.)
Ltd. in New York, said ``it moved faster through $400 than it did
at any point during the day.''
   Precious-metals strategists have attributed the recently
depressed market for gold to growing investor disillusionment with
bullion as a hedge against inflation, which appears to remain tame
in the United States because of Federal Reserve pressure to tighten
interest rates.
   ``The key is how long can the Fed can control the inflation
rate,'' said Sharon Ziemian, assistant vice president for precious
metals at Citibank in New York. ``We've got to see some numbers
that show the Fed has started to lose its grip before gold turns
around.''
   Some strategists predicted gold would fall to as low as $380 an
ounce in the next few weeks.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current delivery
fell $6.90 an ounce to $398.40. It was the first time the metal
closed below $400 since Feb. 18, 1987, when it fetched $392.70.
   Earlier, gold fell $8.50 an ounce in London to $401.50; it fell
$10 in Zurich to $400.50; and it fell $7.74 in Hong Kong to $405.38.
   Silver for current delivery fell 7.5 cents a troy ounce on the
New York Comex to $6.177. In London silver fell 14 cents an ounce
to $6.22.
</TEXT>
