<HEAD>Japanese Were Net Purchasers Of Stocks, Group Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese investors bought more stocks in the
United States than they sold in the April-June period, but most
other foreign investors reduced their net holdings of stocks, the
Securities Industry Association said Wednesday.
   The Japanese added $1.5 billion to their holdings of U.S.
stocks, but sales by other foreigners reduced the overall net
foreign purchases of U.S. stocks to $588 million, the industry
group said.
   U.S. investors sold $1.2 billion more in foreign stocks than
they bought during the second quarter, the group said.
