<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     09-21 0793</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gold Futures Close Below $400; New 19-Month Low</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold futures prices fell for the sixth straight day Wednesday on
the Commodity Exchange in New York and settled below $400 a troy
ounce for the first time in more than 19 months due to slack
investor demand.
   With the latest economic statistics still indicating only modest
inflation, gold futures could fall as low as $385 a troy ounce
before finding many buyers, analysts said.
   On other markets Wednesday, other precious metals futures also
declined; copper futures were lower; livestock and meat futures
were higher; energy futures were mixed; grains and soybeans were
mixed; and stock-index futures advanced.
   Gold for delivery in October settled at $399.20 a troy ounce, $7
below Tuesday's final price. Gold futures last closed below $400 on
Feb. 18, 1987.
   ``The market did break that psychological barrier today and the
next stop in in the $385-$388 area,'' said Peter Cardillo, an
analyst in New York with Josephthal & Co.
   The gold market, pressured for the last four months by a
stronger dollar and only slight inflation, sold off in reaction to
the government's report that consumer prices rose just 0.4 percent
in August, analysts said.
   The Labor Department said the increase in the Consumer Price
Index was equivalent to an annual inflation rate of 5.2 percent,
the same as in July.
   The Commerce Department's report that Americans' personal income
rose a modest 0.2 percent in August _ compared with 0.7 percent in
July _ also was bearish for gold prices, analysts said.
   Gold is considered a good investment hedge against rising
prices, so investor demand for gold tends to rise and fall with
expectations of inflation.
   ``The latest batch of economic statistics are generally
non-inflationary,'' said James Steel, metals market analyst with
Refco Inc. in New York. ``There appears really to be no worry of
inflation, therefore the precious metals are coming off.''
   Steel said the extremely bearish tone of the precious metals
markets was evident in the narrowing gap between gold and platinum
prices. Platinum almost always trades at least $100 above gold. But
on Wednesday, platinum for October delivery on the New York
Mercantile Exchange settled at $485.10 a troy ounce, $9.80 below
Tuesday's final price and just $85.90 above the October gold price.
   Silver settled 7.5 cents to 8 cents lower on the Commodity
Exchange with September at $6.177 a troy ounce.
   Copper futures declined markedly on the Commodity Exchange amid
profit-taking, but the fundamentals of tight supplies and steady
demand remained strongly bullish, Steel said.
   There hasn't been any fundamental news to change anybody's mind
about copper,'' he said.
   Copper settled .95 cent to 2.60 cents lower with the spot
September contract at $1.123 a pound and the more active December
contract at $1.01 a pound.
   Most cattle futures moved lower on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, pressured by continued weakness in the cash markets due
to slack demand, analysts said.
   Hog futures were mixed with prices for near-month deliveries
steady to lower on speculation that cash prices would be pressured
Thursday by large hog marketings.
   Live cattle were .45 cent lower to .17 cent higher with October
at 69.10 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .33 cent to .75 cent
lower with September at 79.75 cents a pound; hogs were .32 cent
lower to .28 cent higher with October at 38.77 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .05 cent to .55 cent lower with February
at 50.65 cents a pound.
   Energy futures finished mixed on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, with higher prices for gasoline and near-month deliveries
of crude oil reflecting concerns about about falling inventories
and the outcome of an OPEC pricing committee meeting next week,
analysts said.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 3 cents lower to 19
cents higher with November at $14.56 a barrel; heating oil was .23
cent lower to .18 cent higher with October at 41.09 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .30 cent to 1.01 cents higher with October at
45.35 cents a gallon.
   Soybean and wheat futures prices finished higher on the Chicago
Board of Trade but corn was mixed in a day of lackluster trading
dominated by technical factors, analysts said.
   Wheat settled unchanged to { cent higher with September at $4.05
a bushel; corn was 1} cents lower to 2} cents higher with September
at $2.76{ a bushel; oats were 3{ cents lower to 1 cent higher with
September at $2.49 a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to 7 cents higher
with November at $8.37{ a bushel.
   Stock index futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
where the contract for December delivery of the Standard & Poor's
500 index settled .65 points higher at 273.30.
</TEXT>
