<1ST_LINE>u f AM-EasternMachinists 1stLd-Writethru   09-21 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern Machinists, 1st Ld-Writethru,0638</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Machinists Reject Eastern Offer; Carrier Urges Impasse</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf to CORRECT cuts to 10-20 percent sted 28. Picks
up 9th graf ``THe predictable ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By A.J. DICKERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines' Machinists union overwhelmingly
voted down a cost-cutting proposal described by a company
spokeswoman Wednesday as ``our best offer.''
   There were 7,596 ``no'' ballots, or 98.2 percent, against the
offer that union local President Charles Bryan said would cut
salaries by 56 percent. The tally compiled Wednesday also showed
nine void votes and 90 ballots favoring the offer.
   The union represents about 9,500 mechanics and ground-support
workers, Bryan said.
   ``It makes it crystal-clear that the membership were very
concerned, by the number who turned out,'' said Bryan. ``For 81
percent to show up to vote is an unprecedented turnout.''
   The offer was unacceptable because it would reduce pay, sick
days, vacation time and medical benefits, he said.
   Eastern ``just kind of gutted what had been accomplished over
the last 45-50 years,'' said Bryan, who said he expected contract
talks would now be resumed.
   ``We believe it was our best offer,'' Eastern spokeswoman Karen
Ceremsak said of the proposal offered in July.
   Eastern estimated the $161 million in wage concessions sought in
the proposal amounted to 10 to 20 percent of salaries, and accused
union leaders of stalling contract talks that began nine months ago.
   ``The predictable defeat of the contract proposal by more than
98 percent should send another strong message to the National
Mediation Board that the two parties are at an impasse,'' said Tom
Matthews, senior Eastern vice president of human resources.
   While negotiations are stalled, ``Eastern's losses continue. In
the meantime, Eastern has been forced to sell assets, lay off
employees and reduce service in order to survive,'' Matthews said.
   In the latest round of cuts, Eastern cut service to 14 cities in
late August and eliminated about 4,000 jobs, or about 12 percent of
its work force, on Sept. 10.
   Eastern, which has lost about $1 billion in the past decade, has
repeatedly sought to have an impasse declared. That would happen if
federal mediator Harry Bickford, a veteran of solving union
disputes at the Miami-based carrier, told the board he could do no
more.
   If the board agreed, both parties would have a chance for
arbitration. If either party declined, a 30-day cooling off period
would kick in. If no resolution were reached in that time, the
union would be free to strike and Eastern could impose its
conditions.
   ``While the board has caused the Eastern situation to drag on
for almost one year,'' Matthews said, ``it released Pan Am and its
Transport Workers Union from federal mediation Monday after only
eight months of negotiations and less than two weeks of mediation,
clearing the way for arbitration or the possibility of a negotiated
settlement within 30 days.''
   But Bryan charged Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern's parent
firm Texas Air Corp., hoped for a strike. As he has in the past,
Bryan contended that Lorenzo aims to give Eastern assets to sister
carrier Continental Airlines, which is largely non-union.
   ``Absolutely not true,'' Ms. Ceremsak said. ``What we do want is
a 30-day cooling-off period. We believe the only way we can reach a
settlement is if we have a deadline. Without a deadline, there's no
incentive for the IAM to settle.''
   Eastern is also negotiating a contract with its pilots union,
which with the flight attendants union, took 20 percent wage cuts
in 1986. The carrier contends the cuts are needed to restore
Eastern to profitability. Bryan, who blames the company's money
troubles on poor management, said the union offered to take a
one-year pay freeze.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
