<2ND_LINE>AM-American-Engines,0160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Airlines Signs Contract for Rolls Royce Engines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines on Wednesday
completed its previously announced $1.69 billion deal with
Rolls-Royce of Britain to buy engines for 50 Boeing 757s.
   American Chairman Robert L. Crandall signed the pact at the
Rolls-Royce factory in Derby, England, and made a speech to the jet
engine manufacturer's management, a spokesman for American said.
   ``We got a good price,'' said spokesman Steve McGregor at the
airline's headquarters in Fort Worth. ``These are high-thrust
engines, the latest version of engine that Rolls-Royce has produced
for 757s. They're incredibly fuel-efficient and very reliable.''
   Under the agreement, American will purchase 116 engines,
including spare parts, to outfit 50 757s. American also agreed in
May to buy another 112 engines later for 757s.
   McGregor said the 757s will not be used to expand the airline
but rather to replacing aging Boeing 727s and 737s.
</TEXT>
