<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-88 2224EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Hunts-Chronology     09-21 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Hunts-Chronology,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Hunts-Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a brief chronology of major business and
legal actions involving the Hunt brothers.
   _April 1980: A $1.2 billion loan is secured by Nelson Bunker,
William Herbert and Lamar Hunt to cover margin calls from silver
purchases. The loan is secured by domestic oil and gas reserves of
the Hunts' Placid Oil Co.
   _August 1983: Six trusts of H.L. Hunt, who died in 1974, are
separated into individual entities for the three brothers and
``Hassie,'' Margaret, and Caroline Hunt.
   _March 1985: Two Hunt companies _ Hunt International Resources
Co. and Great Western Sugar Co. _ file for bankruptcy
reorganization in Dallas. The companies list debts of more than
$237 million.
   _July 1986: The Hunt brothers file suits against 23 banks that
had lent them $1.5 billion, charging them with attempting to take
over the offshore oil industry and requesting $13.8 billion in
damages.
   _August 1986: Bankruptcy is filed for Placid Oil Co., and
William Herbert Hunt's personal trust and interest ownership in
Thanksgiving Tower in downtown Dallas.
   _December 1987: Nelson Bunker and Lamar Hunt file bankruptcy for
their personal trusts and interest in Thanksgiving Tower.
   _July 1988: After months of negotiations, Placid Oil files joint
debt reoganization plans with bank lenders on a 10-year plan to
settle its debts and settle related litigation.
   _August 1988: A federal jury in New York rules the Hunt brothers
must pay more than $130 million in damages to the Peruvian
government's mineral marketing company, Minpeco SA, for conspiring
to corner the world silver market in the late 1970s.
   _September 1988: A federal judge in Dallas approves the
reorganization plan to settle $750 million in loans and lift the
brothers' trust funds out of Chapter 11 bankruptcy.
   _September 1988: William Herbert and Nelson Bunker Hunt file for
personal bankruptcy protection to prevent Minpeco from foreclosing
on their assets before they can appeal the verdict in the silver
trial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
